1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5
{ Welcome to my first Chessable course, and welcome to the wonderful world of the Caro-Kann Defense.  The Caro-Kann has been with me for almost my entire chess journey. It's an opening I have an emotional relationship with. It's been there for many beautiful attacking victories, and some heartbreaking defeats. One of the beautiful things about choosing a chess opening is they are always there for you as a kind of friend, and they can play a large role in shaping your chess identity, as it's shaped mine.  Why is the Caro-Kann the greatest opening in chess?  I'm glad you asked. There are many reasons, but here are the main three in my opinion:   1. It's solid: Chess players REALLY don't like to lose, and some openings are more risky than others. Because of this modest but sturdy central pawn chain, the Caro-Kann is extremely reliable, involves minimal risk, and there are clear strategic plans you can use to even steer the game in your favor. The Caro-Kann is related to the French Defense @@StartBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  @@EndBracket@@ in that the d5-push is made on move 2. The difference is that in the French, Black's light-squared bishop is trapped behind the wall of pawns erected with the move ...e6. Bishops don't like staring at their own pawns - they want to see the light of day! Thus, some consider the French to be a somewhat passive defense.   The Caro, on the other hand, does not condemn the bishop to such a fate.  One may ask then, what is the drawback of the Caro-Kann? The answer probably lies in the Advance Variation after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/3PP3/8/PPP2PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@  3.e5  when White is able to take more central space. In that line, after  3...Bf5  and a sample line:  4.Nf3  e6  we notice a couple of things:   A@@EndBracket@@ Our f5-bishop is free and happy, and    B@@EndBracket@@ Our c-pawn will likely need to move again. This one may not be obvious to you yet, but that's what this course is for!  Because our c-pawn will need to move again, one may argue this constitutes a loss of time in the opening - something we generally want to avoid.  All that being said, despite this slight loss of time, the Caro-Kann is fully playable, even at the very top.    A huge emphasis on the opening moves in this repertoire will be on this philosophy of fast and harmonious development. In other words, finding cozy squares for all our pieces.   2. It's imbalanced: Some believe the Caro-Kann to be a boring opening, but this couldn't be further from the truth. From move 1, the stage is set for an imbalanced pawn structure. This means the battleground will almost surely not be symmetrical, thereby giving both sides dynamically opposed strategic directions.   Comparing with the French once again, the exchange variation after  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  exd5  leaves the position in a completely symmetrical pawn structure. In the Caro-Kann, there is no chance for such symmetry so we will always have a fight on our hands.    3. It's uncommon: When your opponent sees you make the move 1...c6, whether visibly or not, it's very likely your opponent will be groaning. From the very first move, you are steering the game into waters you are more familiar with than your opponent. Not because you study harder, but because you will simply have more games played in the Caro-Kann than your opponents.   An e4 player will see the Caro-Kann in roughly 5% of their games. Even the Scandinavian Defense @@StartBracket@@  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  @@EndBracket@@ is more commonly played!    Despite how infrequently it's played, the Caro-Kann is one of the big four defenses for Black against 1. e4. These are:   B@@EndBracket@@ The King's Pawn Defense  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5   B@@EndBracket@@ The Sicilian Defense  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5   C@@EndBracket@@ The French Defense  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e6   D@@EndBracket@@ The Caro-Kann Defense  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6   That's all fine and good, but why is the Caro-Kann such a good opening for beginners?   I think it's one of the best openings a beginner can learn because it lends itself to understanding plans rather than memorizing moves. Because White has so many ways to meet the Caro-Kann, beginners will be exposed to a range of different positions. Therefore, I like to think with this repertoire, in some sense, you're getting several openings in one!   The chapters in this course mark all of White's major options within the Caro-Kann in just over 100 lines. Go through them all and you'll be set!   In my video coverage of this course, I held nothing back. I thoroughly covered every variation from the MoveTrainer and many more if I thought there is more instructive value to be extracted from my decades of experience. At the end of every variation, I detail the typical middlegame plans so you will have a clear compass to navigate the game with confidence. For this reason, I ended up recording over 20 hours of video which I'm confident you will find well-worth the investment.   My goal with this course is to provide you with a good foundation to help you pick up and understand my favorite opening. Maybe it's even your very first opening! I believe I've constructed the course in a way that is suited for that purpose. If you have been around the chess block but are looking for something new, this course will be an excellent primer.    Now that I've introduced you to my good old friend, the Caro-Kann, theQuickstarter Guide is a fantastic place to start your journey. There I'll show you some of the most important lines to remember from each chapter to give you a holistic overview.   See you there, and I hope you enjoy this course as much as I've enjoyed making it! Maybe the opening chooses you. Maybe the Caro-Kann has chosen you as well!   Jovanka }
*

