{ With the specific variations I chose, I aimed to satisfy the following criteria:  1@@EndBracket@@ There are thematic ideas going into the middlegame. When possible I opted for lines which end with similar pawn-breaks, maneuvers, and attacking ideas. That way, there is even less to remember and you can really start to get a feel for the most common ideas in the Caro-Kann.   2@@EndBracket@@ The variations generally end before move 15. This way, it's beginner-friendly and an emphasis is put on learning the opening, not some random middlegame position you will likely never see in your life.   3@@EndBracket@@ The lines are minimally theoretical. This course is less about memorizing specific moves, and more about learning and understanding strategic motifs. However, there are times when you will need to buckle down and let the power of Chessable's MoveTrainer guide the way. In these cases, the variation will be clearly marked with dynamite Emojis: 🧨, as well as in the variation's title so it's clear when you need to really pay attention to the concrete moves, or heighten your sense of danger. I have set these variations as 'priority variations' so you can toggle an option in your study settings to study only these variations if you so choose. There are 32 of them, and unsurprisingly, half of them are in the Advance Variation.  4@@EndBracket@@ When possible, I chose moves that develop new pieces. I want to instill fundamental opening principles in the moves I recommend so you can see how solid play in a solid opening leads to fantastic results!  5@@EndBracket@@ The chapters are ordered in most to least popular. Broadly it's also most to least critical. This way, you get the hard work out of the way to start, and it's smooth sailing from there. The three major tries for White against the Caro-Kann  (from most to least critical)  are:   A@@EndBracket@@ The Advance Variation  B@@EndBracket@@ The Exchange Variation   C@@EndBracket@@ The Classical Variation  There are other decent tries as we will see, but I recommend getting a feel for these to begin with before moving on to the rest. You will see, however, that I chose to cover the Exchange Variation first in Chapter 1 because you're much more likely to see it at the lower levels.  6@@EndBracket@@ Many of the variations I've chosen for Black are not yet covered on Chessable, thereby making it a fresh, new approach to the opening while still exemplifying the Caro-Kann's key strategic motifs.  7@@EndBracket@@ The variations I chose are a healthy balance of what is popular at lower levels  (as shown on the online database)  versus what are the critical mainlines. I will do my best to make clear which is which within the course so you can understand what to expect to face over the board versus what to watch out for against a well-prepared opponent.  8@@EndBracket@@ When possible, I chose setups for each line not yet covered on Chessable to make for a fresh and new Caro experience.  When you begin studying this course, you will notice an informational variation summarizing the chapter's content. This will provide a strategic overview of the variation covered in that chapter so you know which common plans to aim for. In the theory, I have also included the most popular line played at the lower levels according to the online database for interest's sake and so you can get a sense of what kind of thing to expect in your own games.   You will notice some variations I've marked as 🤺 'Sparring Positions'. These are what I consider to be the most useful positions for you as a student to take a closer look at.  Whether it means playing against a friend from these positions, or analyzing it yourself, you will become a better Caro-Kann player by studying them and understanding the strategic ideas that arise from them. For the stronger players out there, I recommend playing these positions out against Stockfish or whatever chess engine you have access to. But here's a secret tip if you have a thick skin: Don't only practice in these positions as Black, but also as White! This way, you can learn from the cool plans Stockfish uses to dismantle the White position.  You will also notice some percentages within the annotations marking the popularity of each key variation. This will inform you what is popular at the lower levels according to the online database. This is an indication of what the mainlines are at lower levels, not what is popular amongst titled players. As a result, the course starts with the mainline at the lower levels, the Exchange Variation. I took all the data I share throughout the course from games played between players between 400-1600 on a major online platform.  Here is how often you should expect to see each variation at the lower levels:  Exchange Variation - 56%  Advance Variation - 16%  Hillbilly Attack @@StartBracket@@2. Bc4@@EndBracket@@ - 9%  Classical Variation - 7%  Two Knights Variation - 4.5%  2. d3 - 3%  Pseudo-Panov Attack - 2%  Panov-Botvinnik Attack - 1.5%  Fantasy Variation - 1%  You can use this data to study the course however you like, but here are two plans you can follow depending on your goals:  A@@EndBracket@@ Short-Term Results Approach: Study the Quickstarter Guide, then then each chapter in the order shown above along with the associated video. For example, if you follow this approach, you shouldn't touch the Fantasy Variation for a while. You can find coverage of the Hillbilly Attackhere.
  B@@EndBracket@@ Long-Term Understanding Approach: Study the chapters in the order they're given in the course along with the 20+ hours of video provided.  C@@EndBracket@@ Prep Approach: If you are preparing for a game, and you are expecting a certain variation, start by reviewing the introduction of that chapter including brushing up on My Five Lifelines. Depending how much time you have, you can either then study the entire chapter, or toggle the Learn setting to Priority Only. This will show only the most critical and sharp variations to get you in a fighting mindset. Use the Video Sync functionality to refresh your understanding of the variation  (s)  . }
