{ Before we dive into how to play my beloved Caro-Kann Defense, let's briefly discuss its history.   1.e4  c6  was first seen long, long ago in a time before chess-playing computers, before chess World Champions, and even before chess notation existed. This shouldn't come as a surprise, since it is the best opening ever, after all.   Such a modest-looking pawn move was scoffed at during the romantic era of sacrificing pawns and pieces alike. Although it didn't gain traction until decades later, in a German Open in 1885, Austrian amateur player, Marcus Kann used it to defeat one of the first chess Grandmasters ever - Jacques Mieses.   Fast-forwarding to the middle of the 20th century, even World Champions started using it, starting perhaps with the father of Soviet chess, Mikhail Botvinnik. It's also been wheeled out by Petrosian, Karpov, and Anand, all who have put their own unique spin on it. Even Magnus Carlsen used it in his 2013 match against Viswanathan Anand when he first became World Champion!   Modern players who like to use the Caro-Kann to steal victories with the black pieces include: Valentina Gunina, young phenom, Alireza Firouzja, and even the current World Champion @@StartBracket@@2023@@EndBracket@@, Ding Liren. However, the list of players who whip it out on the odd occasion as a surprise weapon goes on and on.   The theory of the Caro-Kann has equally been shaped by its victims  (those playing against it with the White pieces)  . That's because after 1...c6, White has a bunch of directions to go on the very next moves, and even more options within each of those. But don't fret - we will cover everything you are likely to see in this handy course! }
