[Black "Glossary of Chess Terms"]
[Result "*"]

{ As you proceed through this course you will encounter terms that you may not be familiar with. In many cases, they will be hyperlinked to this glossary for your reference.  Backward Pawn: A pawn that cannot be defended by an adjacent, friendly pawn, and is thus especially vulnerable to attack.  Balanced: Describing the evaluation of an aspect of a position, or the position as a whole. A balanced position gives relatively equal chances for both sides.  Battery: Describes a powerful cooperation between a queen and bishop along a diagonal, or rooks @@StartBracket@@or rook  (s)  and queen@@EndBracket@@ along a rank or file.   Bishop Pair: Having both bishops is a great asset in most middlegame scenarios, especially in open positions. They work well together to control both colour complexes.  Blockade: When a pawn is prevented from moving forward by an enemy piece sitting on the square in front of it. Knights are the most effective blockaders since they can hop around the pawn at a moment's notice, their scope uninhibited.  Break: A pawn move that threatens to capture another pawn, opening up squares, files, and diagonals for the pieces to play on. Pawn breaks are an essential element of middlegame strategy.  Compensation: You often have to give something to get something in chess. When one side wins material, the other side can often get something in return, including an attack or time to pursue their own plans effectively.  Concrete: Describing a type of sequence that is forcing: 'I go there, they go there'  Counterplay: A general term for active play sought by Black in the opening, or the side with some kind of disadvantage in the middlegame.  Critical: Describing a good move or sequence of moves, or even an opening setup that puts the opponent to the test, forcing them to prove the viability of their strategy.  Deflection: A tactic involving distracting a piece away from its defensive duties of watching over a piece or square.  Discovered Attack: A tactic where one piece moves to reveal an attack by another piece standing behind it on a rank, file, or diagonal. A discovered attack on the king is called a Discovered Check.  Doubled Pawns: Two friendly pawns on the same file which cannot support each other. Doubled pawns, while they sometimes control a lot of important squares, are more often a liability.  Dynamics: Describing active piece play and the interactions between.  Equalize: The act of going from a worse position to an equal position.  Equality: When neither side has an advantage. Some say that since White has the first move, Black's opening mission is to gain equality before pushing for more.  An Exchange: The trade of a rook for minor piece @@StartBracket@@knight or bishop@@EndBracket@@  Fork: Also called Double Attack - a tactic attacking two pieces at once. Beware of knight forks!  Gambit: A sacrifice, usually of a pawn, offered in hopes the gambiting side will get time for an attack.  Hook: A pawn pushed forward in front of one side's king which can be exploited by the enemy in order to open up the king's position for an attack.  Imbalance: When there is a difference in quality of position in one or more aspect: 'material', 'structure', or 'king safety' to name a few. An imbalanced position tends to provide more opportunities to outplay your opponent, especially at higher levels.  Inaccurate: A suboptimal move, or plan @@StartBracket@@not as severe as Blunder@@EndBracket@@.  IQP: Isolated Queen's Pawn - most often a pawn on the d4 square which cannot be defended by an adjascent pawn on the e or c-files. An IQP is a weakness, but the side with the IQP often has dynamic counterchances.  Lucena Technique: A must-know winning technique in a rook & pawn vs. rook endgame, in which 'building a bridge' is the key concept.  Major Pieces: Rooks and queen.  Minor Pieces: Knights and bishops are minor pieces.  Minority Attack: A modern strategy that occurs when a smaller group of pawns advances against a larger group of pawns on a given side of the board, with the intention of creating a weakness.   Outpost: An active square for a piece, often a knight, from where it cannot be kicked away by an enemy pawn.  Outside Passed Pawn: A very powerful pawn, especially in an endgame that is running down the h or a-files with a clear path to becoming a queen, as there is no enemy pawn on an adjacent file to stop it.   Overworked Piece / Overloaded: A piece overburdened with the task of defending more than one square or piece at the same time. Often the piece is vulnerable to being distracted from at least one of its defensive roles, resulting in a loss of material or a bad position.  Pawn Chain / Pawn Arrow: A group of pawns lined up and protecting each other on the same diagonal, often in the centre. A pawn chain can be thought of as the skeleton of a chess position.  Pawn Majority: A group of adjacent pawns on one side of the board that outnumbers that of your opponent on the same side. Pawn majorities usually come with the opportunity of eventually creating a passed pawn.  Pawn-Triangle: A triangle formation of pawns on adjacent files. In the Caro-Kann, this formation is typically seen in the more 'closed' positions in the Fantasy Variation and the Advance Variation.  Principle of Two Weaknesses: It's usually not enough to win an endgame of equal material without there being more than one weakness for the stronger side to exploit. With two weaknesses, the defending side's defenses can more easily stretched to the limit.  Principled: Describing a good move or strategy that broadly follows conventional rules.  Prophylactic: Taking a time out of your main strategy to stop your opponent's plan.  Rook-lift: An 'up and over' rook maneuver that often gets the rook to an active, aggressive square.  Royal Fork: A double attack by a knight on the king and queen.  Skewer: A tactic where a piece of higher value is attacked, and when it moves away, a piece sitting behind it on a rank, file, or diagonal is vulnerable to capture.  Tempo: Refers to a 'turn' in chess. If one side makes a purely reactive move, they are said to 'lose a tempo'.  Tension: When two pieces are attacking each other and could capture at any moment.  Three-fold Repetition: The game is declared a draw if the same position occurs three times.  Transposition: When the same position occurs from another move-order, most often in the opening.  Wedge Pawn: An pawn far advanced into the opponent's territory, often on the 6th @@StartBracket@@or 3rd@@EndBracket@@ ranks, which is a major nuisance as it can act as an attacker, and controls key squares.  X-ray: When a piece indirectly attacks an enemy piece through another piece on the same rank, file, or diagonal.  Zwischenzug: An in-between move, often made after a capture and before the re-capture of a piece. }
