[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange: 4.Bd3 (Mainline)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Taking in the centre on move 3 can result in one of two opening variations - the Exchange Variation or the Panov-Botvinnik Attack.    The exchange variation is, by far, more common because the Panov-Botvinnik Attack necessitates the further c4 push, however, we will certainly do our due-dillegence on both! }
4. Bd3
{ If your opponent plays this move, they know what they're doing. It's the move all the cool kids play at higher levels of play. White wants to stay flexible with both knights. It's clear the bishop belongs on d3, but depending on what Black does, the knights might have multiple routes into the game. }
4... Nc6
{ A perfect move! Developing a piece towards the centre and attacking White's hanging pawn.   Are we getting checkmated if we develop the other knight first?   Not at all, but it's good to be precise. }
5. c3
{ White has a nice connect-3 pawn chain aiming towards the centre and kingside. }
5... Nf6
{ Knights before bishops! That is, unless White gives us the chance to pin a knight on f3. }
6. Bf4
{ The main move. This is one of the rare openings in chess where White develops both bishops before either knight. }
6... Bg4
{ I've been excited to suggest this line against the Exchange Variation ever since I was invited to write this course. Magnus, Mamedyarov, So, and many more top players share my opinion that this is the most reliable defense.    We develop our bishop outside the pawn chain, just like normal, and poke the queen in the process. Another reason I like this setup is because we play ...Bg4 in a lot of other lines as well, most notably when it pins the f3-knight. }
7. Qb3
{ White's most logical move. We're told not to bring out our queen too early but here it attacks the pawn that is now undefended.  7.f3  Bh5  is another one you may see at lower levels just to kick the bishop out of their house, but it only weakens the white kingside.   Next is ...e6, ...Bd6, ...O-O, and soon we can play ...Bg6 and trade off White's best piece. }
7... Na5
{ Here Black has a few options, but I'm recommending the safest one that still gives White a chance to overpress. We attack the queen and ask White to please make a decision. As it turns out, White can easily walk into trouble here.   7...Qc8  This is my recommendation for if you're more in a fighting mood and you'd rather avoid exchanges and slow down the game. This strategy is effective against weaker players than yourself. We simply defend the pawn and intend to continue normally and look for a fight on the queenside. }
8. Qa4+
{ If White prefers to stay active with the queen, this is the usual move. White better think twice before going  8.Qb5+  Bd7  Whoops! By making the most forward check, White has walked into our trap, and the queen is a goner.   For amateurs, this is a very easy mistake to make since it's the most forward and aggressive move. }
8... Nc6
{ There's a reason I'm suggesting this passive-looking retreat.  First of all, White is given the choice to repeat moves with Qb3 or play something else. We like asking questions. Additionally, there is a psychological effect on amateurs who like to make aggressive-looking moves.   Here, the most aggressive-looking moves only help us. Look at it as a sort of trap.  8...Bd7  9.Qc2  Qb6  10.a4   This is the line most often played at the higher levels, but I'm not so sure our queen is comfortable on b6 and I find this kind of position harder to play as I'm not sure we're getting our usual play on the queenside. However, I suggest you look into this position more if you prefer not to repeat moves. }
9. Bb5
{ This is the 'aggressive' move I alluded to.  But is it actually an aggressive move if White's pieces on the queenside will eventually be kicked backwards? }
9... Bd7
{ Patience, grasshopper! Simply defend the knight a second time.    In themain chapter you will see how we continue to develop our kingside and push White's pieces backwards, as they've run into a bit of a brick wall since any exchanges on c6 only help Black. }
