[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Advance: 4.Nc3 / 5.g4 (Shirov Attack) "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation   White takes the opportunity to gain central space as early as move 3.   SeeOverview for details. }
3... Bf5
{ My favorite treatment of the Advance Variation, and the main move, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain before pushing ...e6.   I will talk in detail about my reasons for this choice in the main chapter, but I like it because it develops a piece that could otherwise become problematic. }
4. Nc3
{ The Shirov Attack! Named after the Latvian legend, Grandmaster Alexei Shirov, this is one of the most aggressive ways to fight the Caro-Kann. If we take this move in isolation, it looks pretty stupid because normally White wants to use the c-pawn, and here the knight sits in the way of it.   But there is venom, so pay attention because White wants blood! }
4... e6
{ One of the clever points of 4. Nc3 is that they would like to play g4, but only after Black commits to ...e6 so that the retreat square on d7 is no longer available.   We are going to end up sacrificing a pawn in this line, but fear not - as always, our central and queenside play is going tocompensate! }
5. g4 Bg6 { Our bishop was hit, so we move it back. No problem. } 6. Nge2 c5
{ White is clearly up to no good on the kingside, so we need to drum up our typical central counterplay.    By the way, we don't call it counterplay because it's inferior to White's play, only because it's the usual convention when referring to Black's play out of the opening. }
7. h4 { Threatening h5 when Black's bishop is in a bad way. } 7... h5
{ A move to remember! We can't allow White to keep pushing that h-pawn, so once again, we stop it in its tracks! }
8. Nf4
{ Oh no, our h5-pawn is falling!   It's okay, we are very aware of that, but we are allowing it for active play! Call it a distraction. }
8... Bh7
{ 8...hxg4  9.Nxg6  fxg6  10.Qxg4  is an absolute nightmare for Black. Please don't allow your bishop to be taken in this way, ruining your pawn structure! }
9. Nxh5 Nc6
{ Keep calm and carry on pressurizing the centre, and White's wanton greed will be punished! After all, knights on the rim are dim, and White will struggle to recoordinate their forces.   In themain chapter, we will see how Black gets sufficient central counterplay by taking a look at one of the most aggressive ways to play commonly seen at the amateur level.   Take a mental note at this point that after the ...c5 break, the b8-knight is usually best developed on c6 where it sits happily behind the c-pawn and puts extra pressure on White's centre. You can imagine the horse happily grazing on c6 in such cases. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Advance: 4.h4 (Tal Variation)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation   White takes the opportunity to gain central space as early as move 3.   SeeOverview for details. }
3... Bf5
{ My favorite treatment of the Advance Variation, and the main move, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain before pushing ...e6.   I will talk in detail about my reasons for this choice in the main chapter, but I like it because it develops a piece that could otherwise become problematic. }
4. h4
{ The Tal Variation! This one is named after the former World Champion, Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@also of Latvia@@EndBracket@@.   Kind of funny that two adjacent, aggressive pawn moves in the same position are named after two Latvian Grandmasters.  It's another way to harass the f5-bishop, but we're used to it by now. First and foremost, White has set a little trap. Do you see it? }
4... h5
{ Just as in the Shirov Attack, we meet h4 with ...h5. Only this time, there is no pawn on g4, so the position is quite different.  While White can go after that h5-pawn here too, the usual plan is to try to attack us on the kingside, but the system I've chosen, as in the Shirov, will usually redirect play towards the centre and queenside.  Let's see.  4...e6  would be a fatal blunder as after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  The bishop has run out of squares. Whoops! Do NOT fall for this one and play ...e6 on autopilot! }
5. Bd3
{ The main move.  5.Nf3  is possible but after  e6  6.Bd3  Bg4  We start to understand why White prefers Bd3 immediately. White would rather trade the bishop and not allow this pin when since h4 has been played, it's not easy to deal with that bishop.   Black is extremely comfortable here. }
5... Bxd3
{ When a bishop lands on d3, we usually take it because White's light-squared bishop is usually the strong one in all variations of the Caro-Kann.   Time out! Why is that, you might ask?   There are good bishops and bad bishops. The good bishop is on the opposite colour complex as the friendly central pawns, and the bad bishop is on the same colour as the friendly central pawns @@StartBracket@@because the pawns tend to block the bishop's vision@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Qxd3 e6 { Solidifying our centre the usual way. } 7. Bg5
{ This is the most critical variation, but not the most popular.   The benefit is that White hits the queen and simultaneously prepares Nd2 when the bishop is already developed. }
7... Qd7
{ Black has many options including  7...Qa5  and  7...Qb6  @@StartBracket@@which I seriously considered for this course@@EndBracket@@ but I went with the modest, and solid ...Qd7, which is the current World Champion, Ding Liren's move of choice when he plays the Caro-Kann. I hereby dub the variation beginning with this move, Ding d7.   I like it because it is a bit less dynamic and risky than the other options, the queen continues to support the d5-pawn, and next we are breaking with ...c5, a typical move which in this course I'm calling Old Faithful. You will soon become very familiar with it. :@@EndBracket@@ }
8. Nf3
{ The main move, since it doesn't make as much sense to strike in the centre right away with the queen on d7.  8.c4  This move allows us to reveal another clever point behind Ding d7...  8...dxc4  9.Qxc4  Qd5  The queens will come off the board either this move or next @@StartBracket@@after  10.Qb3  Qxb3  @@EndBracket@@ after which our position is perfectly healthy. Remember to recapture with the c-pawn! }
8... Ne7
{ Although this wasn't Ding's preference @@StartBracket@@he went for the immediate  8...c5  @@EndBracket@@, I think some patience is called for.    This is definitely one of the most critical variations in the entire course, so I think it's better not to initiate a sharp, tactical skirmish unless you're well prepared!    Furthermore, White's c4 advance is much less scary if our c-pawn is still on c6, lending support to our centre. We can always open things later with ...c5 when the moment is right. For now, let's focus on developing! }
9. O-O
{ The way I see it, White has two stylistic options in this position - going for c4 straight away, or castling, with slower play.  Let's see what happens if White continues developing without putting any pressure on us. }
9... Nf5
{ Here, we should hold off on committing the knight until it becomes clear where it belongs. So, we play the only move we know is necessary, preparing to finish kingside development. The e7-square is ready for the bishop, and the knight can come in via a6, as we will see in themain chapter as this variation proceeds. }
