[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Advance: 4.Nf3 (Mainline)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation   White takes the opportunity to gain central space as early as move 3.   SeeOverview for details. }
3... Bf5
{ My favorite treatment of the Advance Variation, and the main move, developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain before pushing ...e6.   I will talk in detail about my reasons for this choice in the main chapter, but I like it because it develops a piece that could otherwise become problematic. }
4. Nf3
{ White's most natural move, played on occasion by innumerable top Grandmasters. White simply develops a piece and bringing themselves one move closer to castling.  It's the mainline and you will see it in roughly a third of your games in the Advance Variation.   Here, I have a new @@StartBracket@@but thematic@@EndBracket@@ three-part idea not shown in any course that I know of which will ideally lead toequality. }
4... e6 { The routine move, setting up our favourite pawn triangle! } 5. Be2
{ This move marks the start of the Mainline. You won't see this nearly as often as Bd3 either on this move or the last, but   I've decided to make it the mainline of this chapter anyway because it's a much better try for an advantage for White. This is because White keeps the light-squared bishops on the board and from e2, the bishop has some influence on the queenside, where we normally like to play. }
5... Ne7
{ The secret to success in the Advance Variation: Find good squares for all of yourminor pieces!  Often times, Black runs into issues finishing kingside development because both the knight and bishop want to sit on the e7-square. In the Mainline, the e7-knight needs a stable home so the bishop can get out.  Here's the plan:    A@@EndBracket@@ The knight first goes to e7.   B@@EndBracket@@ We break with Old Faithful @@StartBracket@@...c5@@EndBracket@@.   C@@EndBracket@@ The e7-knight continues its journey to the c6-square!  Then, broadly, the b8-knight can go to d7, ...Be7, ...O-O and Voilà! All of our pieces have found a home, we've found counterplay in the centre, and our opponents will gracefully resign on move 19! @@StartBracket@@Okay, maybe not, but that would be nice, huh?@@EndBracket@@   Of course there will be exceptions depending what White does, so unfortunately you can't turn off your brain and slam down these moves willy nilly, but such is chess!  5...c5  is the main recommendation in Erwin L'Ami's Lifetime Repertoire, but I thought it was a bit too sharp to recommend to beginners. But if you're looking for a dynamic fight right out of the gate, you can look into this one.   I prefer to play it a bit slower with an emphasis on harmonious piece development. }
6. O-O
{ The main move. White knows they want to castle, and they're staying flexible with the rest of their pieces. }
6... c5 { Phase two of our plan! } 7. c3
{ A better version than the one where White lost a bunch of time in the Nh4 variations, but this still puts no pressure on our position.   7.dxc5  looks like it drops a pawn, but we will win one of them back after  7...Nec6  when we've tricked White into giving up one of their strong central pawns. We will see more lines like this in themain chapter. }
7... Nec6 { Phase three complete! } 8. Be3
{ White would like to activate the bishop before developing Nbd2, but this arrangement of the pieces is a little awkward and cramped for White. }
8... Nd7
{ Simply defending the pawn and developing. You can also take on d4 first - it doesn't really matter. }
9. Nbd2 Be7
{ Do note that after you play ... Nd7, you can no longer bring this knight to  c6  in case that square is freed up by an exchange of knights. Therefore, once the knight is committed to d7,  it's best to avoid taking on d4 unless there's a goodconcrete reason to. You can see how this kind of position can evolve in themain chapter.   9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nxd4  11.cxd4  After this exchange, Black is okay, but you would prefer your knight on c6, not d7, so just try to remember to keep a knight on c6 to maintain pressure. }
