[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Two Knights: 5.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3
{ The starting position of the aptly named Two Knights Variation. Here, White opts to develop the knights first thing, instead of taking the full centre.   It's a serious try, which can sometimes transpose to the Classical Variation if White decides to later play d4. That's why I'm putting them together in the same chapter in the course. }
3... dxe4
{ In order to reduce your workload, I want to play the same way we do against the Classical Variation and take off this pawn.  3...Bg4  is the old mainline.  4.h3  Bxf3  5.Qxf3  e6  This is a completely reasonable way to play as well, but my suggestion is more consistent with how we play against the Classical Variation. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Preparing ...Ngf6 when we would recapture on f6 with the knight in order to avoid doubled pawns. Compared to the Classical Variation in which I also recommend this move, it's the same position, only with a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on d4.   Because of White's extra developed piece, there are a couple of tactical opportunities White may have that we need to be aware of. }
5. Qe2
{ This tricky move already creates a mate in one threat, so we definitely need to stay on our toes. }
5... Ndf6
{ We want to trade off, or at least displace White's strong e4-knight ASAP. Remember to use this knight, otherwise White's response might give you nightmares.  5...Ngf6  6.Nd6#  Oops! The e-pawn is pinned to the king, who has nowhere to run.   Let's take care that this kind of smothered mate exists only in White's fantasies. }
6. d4
{ White can expand in the centre now, perhaps with dreams of castling queenside, but that's asking for too much. }
6... Nxe4
{ If given the chance, we should certainly make this trade and bring out our next knight with tempo! }
7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qd3
{ The best square for the queen.  8.Qh4  simply misplaces the queen on the side of the board and after  Bf5  and ...e6 next, Black has no problems. }
8... Bg4
{ Threatening @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/8/3P2b1/3Q1N2/PPP2PPP/R1B1KB1R b KQkq - 3 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxf3  Qxf3  10...Qxd4  . }
9. Ne5
{ Sidestepping the threat and gaining a tempo on our bishop.  9.Bd2  would blunder  Bxf3  when we will either double White's pawns, or win the d-pawn next. }
9... Bh5 { Holding onto the bishop pair for now. } 10. c3 e6 11. Be2 Bxe2
{ Similarly to the Exchange Variation, we are thrilled to exchange light-squared bishops. }
12. Qxe2 Be7
{ White has a pretty central knight after all, but that's nothing ...Nd7 can't solve! White doesn't have enough pieces to attack us with anymore.   12...Bd6  is playable as well, but we would have a harder time playing the desirable ...Nd7 after something like  13.O-O  O-O  14.Bf4  when  Nd7  is met tactically by  15.Nxf7  Rxf7  16.Bxd6  when Black loses a pawn. }
