[Black "Two Knights: 5.Bc4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3
{ The starting position of the aptly named Two Knights Variation. Here, White opts to develop the knights first thing, instead of taking the full centre.   It's a serious try, which can sometimes transpose to the Classical Variation if White decides to later play d4. That's why I'm putting them together in the same chapter in the course. }
3... dxe4
{ In order to reduce your workload, I want to play the same way we do against the Classical Variation and take off this pawn.  3...Bg4  is the old mainline.  4.h3  Bxf3  5.Qxf3  e6  This is a completely reasonable way to play as well, but my suggestion is more consistent with how we play against the Classical Variation. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Preparing ...Ngf6 when we would recapture on f6 with the knight in order to avoid doubled pawns. Compared to the Classical Variation in which I also recommend this move, it's the same position, only with a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on d4.   Because of White's extra developed piece, there are a couple of tactical opportunities White may have that we need to be aware of. }
5. Bc4
{ The most common move, and consistent with White's plan of early piece development.   From here, the bishop stares menacingly at our vulnerable f7-pawn, so already we need to start taking care to avoid any devious sacrifices. }
5... Ngf6
{ There's no immediate tactical threat, so we can challenge White's powerful central knight by developing a new piece. }
6. Nxf6+
{ The most common move at amateur level, but not the most critical. Gotta love when that happens!   6.Neg5  is by far the main move at top level, dodging the trade and immediately going after the vulnerable f7 point.   We will get into this in themain chapter. }
6... Nxf6 7. O-O
{ This is the most popular variation at amateur level in the entire Two Knights. While it's not bothering us at all, White has a little trap. }
7... Bf5
{ Because the more normal ...Bg4 is tactically impossible, this is the next best thing, ensuring the bishop is outside the pawn chain before pushing e6.   7...Bg4  would blunder a pawn and likely the game after  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Ne5+  A thematic sacrifice to watch out for when White's bishop eyes your f7-square.   After moving out of the check, our castling rights would be stripped away and White will regain the piece on g4 and remain a pawn ahead. No bueno! }
8. d3
{ An unambitious, but understandable move for an amateur to make to block our f5-bishop's scope.   We will cover the position arising after  8.d4  in the Classical Variation segment of themain chapter. }
8... e6 9. Bg5 Bd6 10. Re1 O-O
{ With the d3 move, White has committed their bishop to living on the queenside where it's not so active staring at our e6-pawn.    We can continue with moves like ...b5, ...a5, and ...Qc7 when Bxf6 ...gxf6 is usually favourable for Black. That's because it helps control the centre with another pawn and our king is plenty safe after having already exchanged some pieces. }
