[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason. White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov.  He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  . Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Nf3
{ The main move at all levels, highlighting an unfortunate side-effect of Black's last move. Black would love to be able to leapfrog the knight and pin the knight with ...Bg4, but that's not allowed!   However, I'm always happy to see it since it's also probably the least tricky. }
5... Ngf6
{ Our intended follow-up, when the knights are working well together. } 6. Bd3
{ The most popular move at amateur level. } 6... Nxe4
{ As we know, whenever we can take the knight on e4, we do. } 7. Bxe4 Nf6
{ Let's go for two! If we are allowed to take the bishop as well, we would be over the moon. }
8. Bd3 Bg4
{ Pin it to win it!  As a bonus, we are threatening to win the d-pawn by removing the f3-defender. }
9. O-O { The most common move at lower levels, overlooking the loose d4-pawn. }
9... Bxf3 { Removing the defender of d4. } 10. Qxf3 Qxd4
{ This has been seen in THOUSANDS of games! } 11. Be3 Qg4
{ We can respond to this by 'checkmating' the white queen. There is no way for White to avoid the queen exchange.  We are slightly behind in development, giving White some compensation, but we also have no visible weaknesses. }
