[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Fantasy: 3.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. f3
{ They call this one the Fantasy Variation because White has a 'fantasy' of keeping two pawns in the centre for as long as possible. But of course, it comes with the price of playing the move f3, which undeniably weakens White's kingside. Since White maintains the tension in the centre, it has the tendency to become quite sharp in many lines.  That being said, I'm happy to inform you that White will not be getting what they want against our repertoire. On the contrary, similar to the Panov-Botvinnik Attack*, my setup of choice is full of pitfalls for White. }
3... e6
{ Against the Fantasy, I like to expedite the construction of mypawn triangle.  Yes, the bishop is inside the pawn-chain this time, but since we aren't taking on e4,  the f3-pawn is looking a little clumsy!  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  is the variation Erwin recommends in his Lifetime Repertoire, which is a great way to meet the Fantasy head-on.  But, a line like this that involves taking on e4 showcases another of White's ambitions - castling and using the half-open f-file for the rook.   Objectively, it's nothing to fear, but I don't like to play the opening on White's terms. }
4. Nc3
{ Since Nf3 is an impossibility, White likes to bring out the other knight. }
4... Bb4
{ Pin it to win it! In this variation, we like our knight coming to e7 quickly to support the centre, so we first make sure the bishop gets involved.   We will learn more about the merits of this move in themain chapter. }
5. Bf4
{ Of all the possible moves in this position, this move @@StartBracket@@the correct one@@EndBracket@@ is played a mere 3% of the time - basically never! Amazing.    The bishop is developed to an active square and simultaneously defends against our ...Qh4+ idea. }
5... Ne7
{ This knight belongs on e7 in the Fantasy. We don't want it being kicked away from f6 with tempo at any moment by an e5-push.  As you can see, our development scheme has revolved around quick castling. Then we can start play in the centre or on the queenside. }
6. Ne2
{ White can opt to defend the knight with the other knight, but this only confuses White's development as the knights are fighting for the same squares. }
6... O-O 7. a3 { Will you pleeeease capture me? pleads the c3-knight. } 7...
Ba5
{ It's important to know when to take, and when not to take. Here, taking would only help White finish kingside development. }
8. Qd3
{ White realised castling short would take an age and a half, so they resort to castling long. }
8... Nd7
{ Our knights, on the other hand, have great, harmonious posts from which they can dynamically contribute to the battle once the position starts to open. }
9. O-O-O b5
{ Black is better, with a lovely attack as the a3-pawn acts as ahook, allowing us to open the queenside more easily with the ...b4 push. You'll have fun with this position, throwing all your pieces towards the queenside and giving checkmate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Panov: 7.cxd5 (Sideline)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. d4 { The mostprincipled way to play, grabbing the centre with both pawns. }
2... d5
{ Our intended central thrust, which we will play on move two no matter what.  Unless your opponent loses their mind and plays  2.Bb5  or something, in which case we shrug and take the bishop.  2...cxb5  . }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Taking in the centre on move 3 can result in one of two opening variations - the Exchange Variation or the Panov-Botvinnik Attack.    The exchange variation is, by far, more common because the Panov-Botvinnik Attack necessitates the further c4 push, however, we will certainly do our due-dillegence on both! }
4. c4
{ A club player's favourite - the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. White strikes at our centre, setting the stage for an open and fighting game. You will learn more about this opening in themain chapter!
There are many ways to combat it, but I really like the setup I've chosen which never fails to take my opponents by surprise. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@   The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6
{ Knights before bishops!  5...e6  is another setup, supporting the centre with a pawn at the cost of our light-squared bishop's active development. I find this approach a bit too passive. I think a different piece belongs on the e6-square! }
6. Nf3
{ By far the most commonly played move, at all levels. You might call this the four-knights variation.  6.cxd5  Quite a common move at lower levels, releasing the tension too early. We're always happy to see White capture a second time on d5!  Nxd5  7.Nf3  Bg4  Pin it to win it! We are threatening to take the knight and if Qxf3, take the d4-pawn.    It's a position resembling the exchange variation, except without a c-pawn for White and d-pawn for Black. This is in Black's favour as it makes it easier to attack White's isolated pawn! }
6... Be6
{ I get so excited when it comes time to play this move because of the surprise factor. At lower levels, this move is played a mere 1% of the time!   In this kind of position, you might expect us to pin the knight with  6...Bg4  . That's the most popular way to play, but I like putting it on e6 here since, compared to the Exchange Variation,  White has more pressure on the centre.    This busy bishop is really the star of the show in this chapter. }
7. cxd5
{ This is the most popular way to play at amateur level, releasing the central tension. We love to see it! }
7... Bxd5
{ I like taking with the busy bishop because it's on payroll and we should get our money's worth, right? ...And also because the central tension has been released and its job on e6 is done.    Notice White'sIQP, which our next moves aim to target. }
8. Nxd5
{ The most common variation, unsurprisingly, is the one where White takes on d5 and helps us develop, until they have no pressure left.   I sound like a broken record, but it's an amazing selling point for our repertoire that so often the most popular variation is the one that gives us an easy game!   8.Be2  Nothing special about this move, but...  e6  It's best to continue normal development. I just wanted to check your tactical awareness.   Please don't get greedy and try to take that pawn right away!  8...Bxf3  9.Bxf3  Qxd4  10.Bxc6+  Doh! The bishop removes the defender of the queen with check!  bxc6  11.Qxd4  9.O-O  Be7  Black has a slight advantage due to the pressure on the isolated pawn. }
8... Qxd5 { Of course we recapture by developing a new piece! } 9. Be2 g6 10.
O-O Bg7
{ White is strategically worse since after ...O-O and bringing the rooks to the central open files, we have continued pressure on the IQP. }
