[Black "Pseudo-Panov: 5.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6
{ Here we are at the start of the greatest opening in the world, the Caro-Kann.  You've already read about why I favour this opening in theintroduction and we will get into even more detail in the main chapters.   Instead of immediately occupying the centre with a pawn with  1...e5  or  1...d5  @@StartBracket@@both fully playable@@EndBracket@@, I want to first prepare to occupy the centre with the d-pawn. This way, if White ever captures, we can recapture with a pawn. }
2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack. In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with  2.d4  ,  and only later pushes the c-pawn.   If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!  In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a soundgambit, but for simplicity sake, I recommend playing the same way regardless with cxd5  . }
3... cxd5 4. exd5 { The only reasonable move for White. } 4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Nc3 { The main move by far at all levels, but a relatively toothless one. }
5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
Nf3 Nc6 { White develops both knights, and we do the same. } 7. Bc4
{ This looks like the most active square for the bishop, attacking our knight, and eyeing the tender f7-square. }
7... Nb6
{ A fine square for the knight where it still has influence on the d5-square, and gains a tempo on the bishop. }
8. Bb3 g6
{ The fianchetto structure is especially effective against IQP positions not only because the g7-bishop eyes d4, but also because it's harder for White to attack us. }
9. d4
{ White should definitely push the pawn to d4 sooner or later in order to develop their queenside. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3
{ A passive post for the bishop, but a post nonetheless. } 11... Bg4
{ Straightforward play: They defend the pawn, we attack it - this time indirectly.  In themain chapter, we will look at both  12.h3  ,  asking our bishop to declare its intentions, and the aggressive,  12.d5  .   Regardless of White's next move, an open position like this requires careful calculation and tactical awareness. }
