[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Offbeat: 2.d3 / 3.Nd2 (King's Indian Attack)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ Now let's take a look at some of the bits and bobs White can throw our way. Because the setups are unusual, how we play against them is a bit less consistent than in other chapters. The Move-Trainer will be especially useful in this chapter, as a result.   2. d3 says I'm not coming at you with my pawns, and I'm content quietly developing my pieces from a distance. }
2... d5 { The normal Caro-Kann second move, and the justification of 1. c6. }
3. Nd2
{ White is opting for more reserved development. It's indicative that White wants to use a King's Indian Attack setup with Nf3, g3, and Bg2.   It's a system opening, which means White likes to play the same moves almost no matter what Black does. }
3... e5
{ White hasn't prevented us from taking the whole centre, so I'm recommending to do so! I played around with  3...g6  here for consistency's sake but Black has nothing better than to eventually play ...e5 in those lines, anyway. }
4. Ngf3 Bd6
{ Our pawn was attacked, and this is the most natural move to defend it.   4...Nd7  is possible to defend e5, but it's already clear our bishop belongs on d6 anyway, and it wasn't as clear the knight should come out to d7 yet, blocking the queen and light-squared bishop's scope. }
5. g3
{ The King's Indian setup. Since Black is allowed to take the centre, White is clearly not maximising their potential with the white pieces and this allows us to play natural moves with minimal risk. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...d4  as tempting as it may be, is inadvisable because after normal play,  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.Nc4  White can make use of the c4-square, a typical motif in King's Indian-type positions, when our 'backward' e-pawn comes under fire and we would need to part with our d6-bishop. In general, I prefer to keep the central tension as long as possible, and one day in the future when the centre is well-defended, we can re-evaluate and either push ahead, or take on e4 at a good moment.   Note that grabbing space with  5...d4  , with a white knight on d2, is much worse than in the3. Nc3 variation since here, the knight can comfortably slot into the c4-square  6.Nc4  where it pressurizes the centre. }
6. Bg2 O-O { Very harmonious, castling at the earliest opportunity. } 7. O-O
Re8
{ You may wonder why not develop a minor piece instead.   The answer is flexibility! e8 is clearly the best square for the rook. Why wait? }
8. Re1 Nbd7
{ White usually wants a kingside attack in the King's Indian, but it's not so easy for White to arrange here. A typical idea for White is Nf1, h3, g4, Ng3-f5, making use of the attractive f5-square with a knight. But, this kind of slow plan shouldn't work if you remember to play in the centre.    Therefore, I recommend keeping the central pawn tension as long as possible until it's the right moment to take on e4. Rarely would I voluntarily push ...d4, handing White the thematic kingside attack with the f4-break on a silver platter. The queenside is Black's stronger side of the board. If White doesn't do much, my next moves would likely be ...a5, activating the a8-rook, Qc7 and further queenside expansion with ...b5. }
