[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Offbeat: 2.Bc4 (Hillbilly Attack)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ Last, and probably also least, let's have a quick look at the so-called Hillbilly Attack!  White disregards the opening principle of knights before bishops and brings the bishop to a seemingly active diagonal. But in reality, once we put pawns on d5 and e6, it's simply misplaced along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... d5
{ This time, our second move comes with the bonus of gaining time against the bishop! }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3 Nf6
{ Standard development. It's pretty clear our knights belong on f6 and c6. You will see why we start with this knight after our next move. }
5. d4
{ White really has nothing better than to push d4, taking their fair share of the centre and facilitating the development of their dark-squared bishop. }
5... Bg4
{ ...Nf6 supports this move, when we can play the same way we do against the Exchange Variation. The Hillbilly Attack is only an Exchange Variation with a misplaced bishop on b3. As a rule of thumb, ...Bg4, attacking the queen is especially disruptive when the queen can't come out to the queenside with Qb3, for example. That's because White doesn't want a pinned knight, nor is it any good to play f3. }
6. Ne2
{ The lesser of all evils.  6.f3  Bd7  We could also play ...Bf5, but this is even safer, when our bishop won't be subject to harassment on the kingside.  7.Ne2  e6  White's moves have made very little sense.   The f3-pawn and the b3-bishop hurt White's position much more than it's worth to put our light-squared bishop inside our pawn-chain. Black is slightly better. }
6... e6 { The move that makes fun of the hillbilly bishop. } 7. O-O Nc6 8. c3
Bd6
{ SPARRING POSITION   Black is better based solely on the fact that White's bishop is misplaced, and it cost them an extra move to misplace it! After ...Qc7 and ...O-O, we can look forward to a smooth minority attack with ...b5-b4, undermining White's pawn chain. That's about it as far as the offbeat options for White. The 2. d3 variations are interesting and viable, in which I recommend a solid kingside fianchetto setup, and remember to take the full center with ...e5 if allowed. The Hillbilly Attack is less threatening than the name indicates, as White's hillbilly bishop is off drinking moonshine somewhere on the queenside.   There you have it, ladies and gentlemen - the Caro-Kann! You're now equipped with the greatest opening in chess! Whenever you're ready for a refresher on how to play a certain variation, I suggest starting with the chapter overview and playing through the model game. Another great way to improve your openings is to find a player who plays the same setup and carefully play through their games. I hope you've learned a lot, not only about the opening, but also about chess strategy in the process.   May it bring you success in your games! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange Variation Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: ~55% of Caro-Kann games in all iterations of the Exchange Variation@@EndBracket@@   Keep in mind I gathered all the data in the course through a single datababase of online games on a major chess playing platform, which I trust is very representative of what you will see in your own games.  Welcome to the Exchange Variation! A relatively tame approach for players who enjoy defined pawn structures from the very outset. It's also by far the most common way that amateurs choose to fight the Caro-Kann. This is because White sometimes gets multiple chances to capture on d5, and because amateurs simply like to take stuff! :@@EndBracket@@   It's definitely not the most critical approach, and because the pawn structure is already defined, we can put our pieces on largely the same squares. }
4. Bd3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 11%@@EndBracket@@   I'm excited to show you what I have prepared here in the mainline, for concrete as well as psychological reasons.   4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 29%@@EndBracket@@   A popular line, but immediately misplaces the knight, blocking its own c-pawn.  4...Nc6  5.Nf3  Bg4  Pin it to win it! You might see this position a lot at lower levels because White develops both knights quickly.   4.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 29%@@EndBracket@@   There are also a couple of independent lines where White develops the king's knight first.  4...Nc6  5.Bb5  Bg4  Get used to pinning the f3-knight in this variation. We don't want it hopping to e5 too easily. }
4... Nc6 5. c3 Nf6
{ Although our king's knight stays flexible in some variations, here we have nothing better than to bring it out. }
6. Bf4 Bg4
{ My favourite move, attacking the queen, and tempting it out to the queenside where it might not end up doing much. This line can end in a quick repetition, a misplaced queen on a4, or a normal kind of position where we aim for queenside counterplay and to exchange off the light-squared bishop.   My Five Lifelines:  A@@EndBracket@@ Develop quickly, usually with the knights on f6 and c6 and a ...Bg4 pin if possible.   B@@EndBracket@@ After development is finished, harass and/or trade White's bishops. For instance, with the ... Bg4-h5-g6 maneuver, or the ...Nc6-e7 - ...Bf5 plan.   C@@EndBracket@@ If White plays aggressive-looking moves early on, have patience. Develop and castle normally and push them back later with tempo.   D@@EndBracket@@ Try to play on the queenside and remember the thematic ...b5-b4 break, creating a weakness on c3 if possible.   E@@EndBracket@@ When White castles queenside, play fast and furious, following my attacking rules as outlined in the chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange: 4.Ne5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Nf3 d5
{ There are several move orders from which the Exchange Variation can come about. Before we get into the main one, let's briefly check this weird one where White puts a knight on e5 as fast as humanly possible. I've seen it before, but a good friend of mine showed me a cool way to fight it. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Ne5
{ White is moving the same piece twice in the opening - usually not a good strategy. Our moves will revolve around making this knight question what it's doing on e5. }
4... g6
{ My favourite setup.   The fianchettoed bishop will gaze at the knight and eventually make it decide why it's sitting in the heart of our position. }
5. d4
{ 5.Bb5+  Such early aggression doesn't yield White anything.  Bd7  We block the check with the bishop, encouraging trades.  6.Nxd7  Nxd7  White may have the bishop pair, but it's only temporary.  7.O-O  a6  We'd rather not be pinned all game, so it's time to evacuate the bishop and make it find a new home especially before White has the chance to go Re1 and create a cozy f1-square for the bishop. }
5... Nf6
{ A natural developing move and adding a little extra protection to the d7-square. We could start with ...Bg7, but our plan isn't to capture the invader knight, but rather to make it look silly! }
6. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ White has lost their chance to take the bishop pair for free. This pin doesn't bother us as we will soon castle and start to kick back the White forces. }
7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O
{ It's starting to become clear that White isn't threatening anything except to trade off our pieces... works for us! }
9. c3 Nxe5
{ Let's show an example of what can happen if we're allowed to snap off that knight... }
10. dxe5
{ 10.Rxe5  is also bad in view of  Ne4  when suddenly the rook is trapped! }
10... Ng4
{ Easily overlooked by an amateur player. White has no good way to hold onto the e-pawn. }
11. f4
{ This would be the obvious defense, but White is in big tactical trouble!  11.Bf4  defends one pawn, but gives up another after  Nxf2  12.Kxf2  Qb6+  with a fork on the king and b5-bishop. }
11... Qb6+ { Now White has to give up loads of material to prevent checkmate! }
12. Kh1
{ If White refuses the material, they will be checkmated!  12.Kf1  Qf2#  would be the quick way out. }
12... Nf2+
{ Aroyal fork, but we don't want to take the queen. We want checkmate! } 13.
Kg1 Nh3+
{ A double check. White's king must choose between h1 and f1, but there's no escape. }
14. Kh1 Qg1+ { BOOM!  White has no choice but to accept the sacrifice. } 15.
Rxg1 Nf2#
{ It's not every day you get to show off with the crowd-pleasing smothered mate on move 15 with the black pieces. }
