[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange: 4.Ne5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Nf3 d5
{ There are several move orders from which the Exchange Variation can come about. Before we get into the main one, let's briefly check this weird one where White puts a knight on e5 as fast as humanly possible. I've seen it before, but a good friend of mine showed me a cool way to fight it. }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Ne5
{ White is moving the same piece twice in the opening - usually not a good strategy. Our moves will revolve around making this knight question what it's doing on e5. }
4... g6
{ My favourite setup.   The fianchettoed bishop will gaze at the knight and eventually make it decide why it's sitting in the heart of our position. }
5. d4
{ 5.Bb5+  Such early aggression doesn't yield White anything.  Bd7  We block the check with the bishop, encouraging trades.  6.Nxd7  Nxd7  White may have the bishop pair, but it's only temporary.  7.O-O  a6  We'd rather not be pinned all game, so it's time to evacuate the bishop and make it find a new home especially before White has the chance to go Re1 and create a cozy f1-square for the bishop. }
5... Nf6
{ A natural developing move and adding a little extra protection to the d7-square. We could start with ...Bg7, but our plan isn't to capture the invader knight, but rather to make it look silly! }
6. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ White has lost their chance to take the bishop pair for free. This pin doesn't bother us as we will soon castle and start to kick back the White forces. }
7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O
{ It's starting to become clear that White isn't threatening anything except to trade off our pieces... works for us! }
9. Nf3
{ When I was shown this line, I was amused to see that retreating the knight and losing a tempo is actually White's best option! That's because if we are allowed to take the knight and lure a pawn to e5, it will be difficult for White to hold onto it. }
9... Nb8
{ White retreated their knight, so we have time to do the same in order to put our knight on the square it feels most at home - c6. }
10. c3 Nc6 11. Nbd2 Qc7
{ White has played it smart and avoided too many exchanges by retreating the knight. Lower-level players are not likely to do this, so I have my doubts you will ever get here. But I'd say Black has equal chances here with a few plans to choose from:   A@@EndBracket@@ ...Bf5 and ...Ne4, initiating trades   B@@EndBracket@@ ...a6 and ...b5, expanding on the queenside   C@@EndBracket@@ ... Re8 and a well-timed ...e5 break. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "🤺 Exchange: 4.Bd3 (Mainline) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Welcome The Exchange Variation!   In some ways, this is the most important chapter of the course. You will see your opponent take your d5-pawn, whether on this move, or in the next couple of moves, far more than any other variation available. That's because amateurs love to take stuff. This is delightful news because the Exchange Variation frankly isn't that scary. Besides, even if they do play the best setup, I have the perfect solution.    But it's played at top-level. Even Magnus has played it! Note that the reason it's one of the smaller chapters is because of the nature of the Exchange Variation and the lines I chose against it are quite basic, uniform, and easy to grasp. Before we look at the moves, let me point your attention to one thing: pawn structure. White has a half-open e-file to work with, and we have a half-open c-file. Additionally, our pawn structure @@StartBracket@@later with ...e6@@EndBracket@@ will point towards the queenside, White's towards the kingside. This is a hint that we want to direct play towards the queenside, as we're used to doing.   Pay attention to the sparring positions in this chapter because, statistically, you will benefit most from practicing variations arising from this chapter.   Let's go! }
4. Bd3
{ If your opponent plays this move, they know what they're doing. It's the move all the cool kids play at higher levels of play. White wants to stay flexible with both knights. It's clear the bishop belongs on d3, but depending what Black does, the knights might have multiple routes into the game. }
4... Nc6
{ A perfect move! Developing a piece towards the centre and attacking White's hanging pawn. Are we getting checkmated if we develop the other knight first? Not at all, but it's good to be precise. }
5. c3
{ White has a nice connect-3 pawn chain aiming towards the centre and kingside. }
5... Nf6
{ Knights before bishops! That is, unless White gives us the chance to pin a knight on f3. }
6. Nf3 { The most common move at amateur level, it's pretty harmless! } 6...
Bg4
{ One of the reasons I love the Exchange Variation and even the wider Caro-Kann is because White is allowed so many options, which gives them innumerable chances to make our lives easy!   This is one of those cases. Introducing our Bully Bishop! I lovingly call it a bully because of the strategic reality that if we succeed in trading it for White's light-squared bishop, or put it to work pinning a knight, we very likely have a comfortable position!   With this move we Pin it to win it! ...Okay, we're not winning anything for the moment, but I enjoy the phrase. }
7. O-O
{ 7.h3  White can include this any moment, but our typical response is  Bh5  maintaining the pin on the knight. There are exceptions though!  8.g4  Bg6  White pushing the bishop back to g6 is completely harmless because we haven't castled our king over there, and they're actually helping us to exchange White's best minor piece! }
7... e6
{ We don't have a pawn triangle in the Exchange Variation since we had to part with our c-pawn, but we have the next best thing - apawn arrow@@StartBracket@@or pawn chain@@EndBracket@@. The arrow points eastward towards the queenside, and we can use it as a compass for our pieces. }
8. Bf4 Bd6
{ The majority of the time, this is our dark-squared bishop's home, and most active square - even if it trades itself off in the process! }
9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. Nbd2 O-O { Don't forget to castle! } 11. Qc2 Rfc8
{ Our pawn arrow is pointing towards the queenside, and we have a half-open c-file, and rooks like open files. Additionally, we have a small threat. ;@@EndBracket@@ }
12. a3
{ Darn, they saw it. A move like  12.Rfe1  would allow us to carry out our evil plan...  Nb4  with a double attack on the queen and bishop. Notice the knight cannot be captured due to the rook's pin against the queen.  13.Qb1  Nxd3  14.Qxd3  Anytime we can trade off White's light-squared bishop in the exchange is a big opening success! }
12... Ne7 { But not to worry, that knight has another purpose now. } 13. Rfe1
Bf5
{ SPARRING POSITION   Success! We are trading off the light-squared bishops and if they take ours, we will recapture with the knight.   This is a perfect sparring position to practice carrying out aminority attack. }
