[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "🧨 Exchange: 4.Bd3 (Mainline) #6 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Welcome The Exchange Variation!   In some ways, this is the most important chapter of the course. You will see your opponent take your d5-pawn, whether on this move, or in the next couple of moves, far more than any other variation available. That's because amateurs love to take stuff. This is delightful news because the Exchange Variation frankly isn't that scary. Besides, even if they do play the best setup, I have the perfect solution.    But it's played at top-level. Even Magnus has played it! Note that the reason it's one of the smaller chapters is because of the nature of the Exchange Variation and the lines I chose against it are quite basic, uniform, and easy to grasp. Before we look at the moves, let me point your attention to one thing: pawn structure. White has a half-open e-file to work with, and we have a half-open c-file. Additionally, our pawn structure @@StartBracket@@later with ...e6@@EndBracket@@ will point towards the queenside, White's towards the kingside. This is a hint that we want to direct play towards the queenside, as we're used to doing.   Pay attention to the sparring positions in this chapter because, statistically, you will benefit most from practicing variations arising from this chapter.   Let's go! }
4. Bd3
{ If your opponent plays this move, they know what they're doing. It's the move all the cool kids play at higher levels of play. White wants to stay flexible with both knights. It's clear the bishop belongs on d3, but depending what Black does, the knights might have multiple routes into the game. }
4... Nc6
{ A perfect move! Developing a piece towards the centre and attacking White's hanging pawn. Are we getting checkmated if we develop the other knight first? Not at all, but it's good to be precise. }
5. c3
{ White has a nice connect-3 pawn chain aiming towards the centre and kingside. }
5... Nf6
{ Knights before bishops! That is, unless White gives us the chance to pin a knight on f3. }
6. Bf4
{ The main move. This is one of the rare openings in chess where White develops both bishops before either knight. }
6... Bg4
{ I've been excited to suggest this line against the Exchange Variation ever since I knew I was going to write this course. Magnus, Mamedyarov, So, and many more top players share my opinion that this is the most reliable defense.    We develop our bishop outside the pawn chain, just like normal, and poke the queen in the process. Another reason I like this setup is because we play ...Bg4 in a lot of other lines as well, most notably when it pins the f3-knight. }
7. Qb3
{ White's most logical move, and the only serious way to put pressure on our position. We're told not to bring out our queen too early but here it attacks the pawn that is now undefended.  7.f3  Bh5  is another one you may see at lower levels just to kick the bishop out of their house, but it's only weakened the white kingside. Next is ...e6, ...Bd6, ...O-O, and soon we can play ...Bg6 and trade off White's best piece.   7.Ne2  is nothing special. If anything, the knight is misplaced on e2 where it won't be going to the desirable e5-square anytime soon. We can continue normally with  e6  followed by ...Bd6, ...O-O and a minority attack. }
7... Na5
{ Here Black has a few options, but I'm recommending the safest one that still gives White a chance to overpress. We attack the queen and ask White to please make a decision. As it turns out, White can easily walk into trouble here. }
8. Qa4+
{ If White prefers to stay active with the queen, this is the usual move. }
8... Nc6
{ There's a reason I'm suggesting this passive-looking retreat.    First of all, White is given the choice to repeat moves with Qb3 or play something else. We like asking questions. Additionally, there is a psychological effect on amateurs who like to make aggressive-looking moves. Here, the most aggressive-looking moves only help us. Look at it as a sort of trap.   8...Bd7  9.Qc2  Qb6  10.a4  This is the line most often played at the higher levels, but I'm not so sure our queen is comfortable on b6 and I find this kind of position harder to play as I'm not sure we're getting our usual play on the queenside. However, I suggest you look into this position more if you prefer not to repeat moves. }
9. Nd2
{ This is a somewhat rare continuation where White prefers to maintain the pin on the knight but not put extra pressure on it immediately. This was Karsten Muller's move you can see in amodel game. }
9... e6
{ If I made you guess the move here, I would hope this would be your guess! We need to develop our kingside!   Take note that this pawn structure @@StartBracket@@which you will see in the Exchange Variation over and over@@EndBracket@@ is called the Carlsbad Structure. White has a pawn arrow that points towards the kingside, and ours points the queenside. This tells us we want to eventually push our pawns and pieces towards that side of the board. }
10. Ngf3 Bd6 { Our usual square for the bishop in the Exchange Variation. } 11.
Ne5
{ An aggressive move that startsconcrete actions by attacking multiple pieces. }
11... O-O
{ But it's not as scary as it looks. Surprisingly, we can simply castle! No need to fear taking twice on c6, nor Nxg4. }
12. Bg3
{ A good move, defending the bishop so the threat of Nxg4 is renewed.  12.Nxg4  would allow  Bxf4  13.Nxf6+  Qxf6  After which we've succeeded in exchanging some pieces and activating our queen. White still needs to castle and it's not possible immediately because the knight is loose! }
12... Bf5
{ Naturally, we sidestep the knight's attack on the bishop and instead offer it for their best piece! }
13. Bxf5 exf5
{ This structure, although it isolates the d-pawn, is not so bad. In exchange, we get the lovely e4-square for the knight. Also, White better castle soon or they'll get in trouble along the newly opened e-file after ...Re8. }
14. O-O Bxe5
{ It's necessary to finally do something about the threat on c6, so we capture. But not with the knight, getting forked! }
15. dxe5 Ne4
{ If White deals with the threat on the d2-knight by  16.Nxe4  ,  we happily recapture with  16...dxe4  ,  ridding ourself our isolated pawn.   All of a sudden, we would have a huge mass of kingside pawns for attacking purposes, and White's e-pawn is not long for this world.  Otherwise, we carry on with our e-pawn hunt. }
