Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 Bh5
{ SPARRING POSITION   This is a typical position you could easily reach in many very similar iterations. That's why I made this a sparring position. Take the time to play this position against your friends, or against an engine in order to internalize the ideas.    Generally, we want to go ...Bg6 exchanging White's best piece then expand on the queenside with tempo against White's queen. Black will aim for the ...b5-b4 break while White will try to maintain a knight on e5 and expand on the kingside. }
