[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Mueller, Karsten vs. Agdestein, Simen, Bundesliga, 1998"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game is between two interesting characters in the chess scene. Karsten Muller of Germany is a respected author and PhD holder in mathematics. He is known for his endgame expertise.  Simen Agdestein is a former coach of Magnus Carlsen and former football star on the Norwegian national team!    Here, they do battle in the Exchange Variation which is maybe no surprise given Mueller's inclination towards endgames. However in this game, Black doesn't shy away from the endgame, and the more pieces that came off the board, the more his position incrementally improved. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ The starting position of the Exchange Variation. } 4. Bd3 Nf6
{ I am suggesting the more mainstream move-order with 4...Nc6 since sometimes our knight goes on e7. }
5. c3 Nc6 6. Bf4 Bg4
{ But we quickly transpose to the mainline where White correctly prefers to bring out the bishops first.    I'm recommending this move because it's simply where our bishop goes in the Exchange Variation with, or without a knight to pin on f3. }
7. Qb3
{ The usual response, putting pressure on Black's centre and queenside. would end the game in athreefold repetition. }
7... Na5
{ Attacking the queen for a second time in a row, and simultaneously defending b7. We won't tolerate this queenside pressure. }
8. Qa4+
{ 8.Qb5+  of course is what we are hoping for!  8...Bd7  9.Qc5  e5  The queen is a goner. But of course, a player of Mueller's calibre won't consider it for a moment. }
8... Nc6 { The argument is the white queen is less purposeful on a4. } 9. Nd2
{ Preparing Ngf3 without allowing Black to take and ruin the kingside pawn structure. }
9... e6 10. Ngf3 Bd6
{ Agdestein wisely develops the bishop to its most active square while simultaneously challenging one of White's powerful bishops they so pride themselves on in the Exchange Variation. }
11. Ne5
{ The main move, in accordance with White's plan - to sink a knight in the centre and use it as a fulcrum point to attack. It may look like a double-threat, but while Nxc6 is indeed a threat, Nxg4 is not for the moment since the f4-bishop is hanging. }
11... O-O 12. Bg3 { 12.Nxg4  Bxf4  allows a very favourable trade for Black. }
12... Qc7
{ Agdestein went a slightly different direction, opting to allow, and even encourage White to exchange the bishop for the knight, which is also solid enough.   I recommend  12...Bf5  in the course, a consistent move which insists on those bishop trades! We aren't afraid of the structure after  13.Bxf5  exf5  when we get a lovely outpost on e4 for the knight. You can see more on this variation in the theory section. }
13. Nxg4 Nxg4 14. Qd1 Nf6
{ White uses a move to return the queen to civilization, and Black does the same with the knight. }
15. O-O Bxg3
{ A good moment to exchange now that there is no rook on h1 White can use to attack down the h-file. A couple of pieces have been exchanged and it's a good moment to evaluate where things stand. White still has their good bishop which we usually aim to trade off. However, because there have been multiple exchanges, White will have difficulty using it to attack with. Because of this, Black has no problems.    Another consequence of the recent action is that Black is actually the one with more control over the important e5-square, which explains Agdestein's next move. }
16. hxg3 e5
{ Black could have prepared this break more as it's hard for White to constructively prevent it, but Agdestein thought, why not now? One may wonder why not go for the usual queenside expansion and not leave ourselves with an isolated d-pawn?   16...a6  17.Nf3  b5  is definitely a possible plan, but I think it's just a bit slow. After a move such as  18.Qe2  the desirable  18...b4  may not be immediately working due to  19.Bxa6 }
17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nf3 Nc4
{ Furthermore, the isolated pawn is turning out to be more of an asset, allowing the knight to become more active on c4. }
19. Bxc4
{ Karsten preferred to avoid passive moves such as  19.Rb1  which might have been a better practical choice. }
19... dxc4
{ White felt the knight couldn't be tolerated there, but now Black, with extra space, has the better side of equality along with the possible d3-square as a knight outpost on a very good day. }
20. Re1 Rad8 21. Nd4 Qb6 { Putting pressure on White's backwards b-pawn. } 22.
Rb1
{ In a funny twist of fate, White wound up passively defending b2 anyway! From this point, while Mueller played well for several more moves, it's already quite a difficult position in practice. }
22... Rfe8 { Activating the last piece. } 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Qa4
{ Activating the queen and tickling the e8-rook, rendering the black knight immobile for now. }
24... Qc5 25. Qb5 Qc7
{ Agdestein wisely opts to keep queens on the board as White would have no problems otherwise. }
26. Rd1 a6 27. Qg5 { Threatening Nf5 with an attack. } 27... h6
{ ...An easy threat to extinguish. } 28. Qf4 Qxf4
{ Agdestein probably felt with Nf5 in the air at any moment, it was worth trading queens at this point.  Even without queens, Black still has the better side of equality. }
29. gxf4 Rd8
{ I really like this move from a practical standpoint, pinning the knight and preparing a rook lift towards the queenside! }
30. Kf1 Rd5
{ I'm sure the maneuver,  30...Rd6  31.f5  Rb6  crossed Black's mind, but after the simple defence,  32.Rd2  Black runs out of steam. }
31. Ke2 Ra5 32. a3 Rd5
{ What has Black acheived by provoking a3?  Visibly, not much. But it's it weakens the b3-square, and renders White's pawns even more static, ruling out any future b3 pushes when White can recapture with the a-pawn. }
33. Kf3 Nd7
{ The knight starts its journey to the d3 promise land from which it can attack several of White's pawns! }
34. Ke4 Rd6 35. Rd2 Nc5+ 36. Ke5 Rd8 37. f5
{ White's king is very active, and it's true that king activity is critical in the endgame, but it's not doing much here since it has no easy targets. }
37... b5 38. g4 Nd3+ 39. Ke4 Nc5+ 40. Ke5 f6+ 41. Kf4 Re8 42. Nc6
{ White isn't sure what to do at this point. The rook belongs on d2 to protect the pawn weaknesses while the black rook, by contrast, is free to roam. This makes the black side much easier to play. }
42... Nd3+ 43. Kf3 Re1 { The rook starts its pawn-hunting campaign! } 44. Nb4
Ne5+ 45. Kf4 Rg1
{ Black is offering the a6-pawn for the much more valuable g-pawn. } 46. Nxa6
Rxg4+ 47. Ke3 h5
{ With this pawn trade, Black acheives anoutside passed pawn which is incredibly difficult for White to deal with. It may look as if White is acheiving the same on the queenside, but it's far slower. }
48. Nc7 h4 { Passed pawns are meant to be pushed! } 49. f4
{ A better defense was  49.Rd1  h3  50.Rh1  When it becomes apparent that White has bought themselves some time for their queenside counterplay! }
49... Rg3+
{ The only winning move, making way for the knight's involvement on the kingside which will overpower White's defenses. }
50. Ke4 Ng4 51. Ne6 Re3+
{ 51...h3  is completely winning as well as White has no attack on the king.  52.Rd8+  Kh7  53.Nf8+  Kh6  and the king is safe and Harry can't be stopped. }
52. Kd4 Rd3+
{ Black, very professionally, opts for a simplification to a winning position. }
53. Rxd3 cxd3 54. Kxd3 h3
{ Harry can't be stopped! I like this game because it demonstrates a couple important things about the Exchange Variation:   A@@EndBracket@@ Piece trades are good, even if it's not the ideal bishop for bishop trade we aim for.    B@@EndBracket@@ Patience is rewarded. Especially from the black side, you will very rarely acheive some big attack. After finishing development and trading some pieces, you will still need to play good moves to outplay your opponent by putting pressure on their position and waiting for them to crack, as Mueller eventually did with 49. f4. }
*

