9. O-O-O { Time for Attacking the Queenside-Castled King: Lesson #2: } 9... Be7
{ Before we can think of attacking, we must finish development and bring our own king to safety.  We're not putting the bishop on the normal d6-square because we want to give the knight some extra protection so that our queen can go wandering on the queenside. ;@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Kb1 O-O 11. g4 { White's standard attacking push. } 11... Rc8
{ Just like in many lines of the Sicilian Defense, when the white King castles long, we like to put a rook on c8 as quickly as possible because we know for a fact it will be useful there. You might be surprised how it will be used. }
12. Be3
{ A natural-looking move in order to get out of the way of the g-pawn's advance. }
12... Qa5 { The most aggressive square for the queen. } 13. h4
{ A routine attacking move, but already a losing blunder. Black's attack is too strong. }
13... Nb4
{ Also the most aggressive square for the knight! Notice the pressure on a2. At this point, my favourite ...Rxc3 is coming whether White likes it or not.   Don't even think about playing a reactive move like  13...h6  when after  14.g5  hxg5  15.hxg5  Nd7  16.Qh5  it's Black's king that is getting mated!  f5  doesn't help.  17.g6  Cutting off Black's escape square on f7.  Rfe8  18.Qh7+  Kf8  19.Qh8# }
14. a3 { Maybe the best try to stay alive. } 14... Rxc3
{ BOOM!   Demolishing the White pawn-structure around the king. Now White has a choice whether to capture our knight or our rook, but both are miserable! }
15. axb4
{ 15.bxc3  Qxa3  Threatening mate in 2 with ...Qa2+ / ...Qxc2#.  16.cxb4  Qxb4+  It's important to take with the queen with check so we have time to involve our knight on e4!  17.Kc1  Ne4  Cutting off the king's escape on d2 and now there's nothing White can do to prevent checkmate!  18.Bf4  At least this defends against ...Qa3+ and keeps the game going.   If White's not careful, they're getting mated immediately after  18.Be2  Qa3+  19.Kb1  Nc3#  18...Qa4  I like this move, making way to involve the bishop with check, after which the rook joining the party will be overwhelming for White, who has no sniff of an attack.   In summary of these attacking variations: When the kings are castled on opposite sides, it's important to act quickly and forcefully! Here are some rules to remember:   A@@EndBracket@@ First, put your pieces on their most active squares towards the enemy king. For example, ...Nb4 and ...Qa5.    B@@EndBracket@@ It can be tempting to play moves near your own king to try to defend, but don't do it! It can easily backfire. Instead, focus on your own attack.   C@@EndBracket@@ Remember the ...Rxc3 exchange sacrifice, destroying the king's shelter.   D@@EndBracket@@ The follow up to your sacrifice should be as forceful as possible, involving checks, and checkmate threats as often as possible, otherwise White will have time to coordinate a defense. }
15... Bxb4
{ Calmly involving another attacker. We are intent on sacrificing that rook! }
16. bxc3
{ If White doesn't accept our sacrifice, the attack will continue anyway and Black is lost. That's a good scenario to practice against the engine! }
16... Bxc3 { Now Checkmate on a1 is inevitable. } 17. g5 Qa1# { Checkmate! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "🤺 Exchange: 4.Nc3 #4 (Most Popular)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Welcome The Exchange Variation!   In some ways, this is the most important chapter of the course. You will see your opponent take your d5-pawn, whether on this move, or in the next couple of moves, far more than any other variation available. That's because amateurs love to take stuff. This is delightful news because the Exchange Variation frankly isn't that scary. Besides, even if they do play the best setup, I have the perfect solution.    But it's played at top-level. Even Magnus has played it! Note that the reason it's one of the smaller chapters is because of the nature of the Exchange Variation and the lines I chose against it are quite basic, uniform, and easy to grasp. Before we look at the moves, let me point your attention to one thing: pawn structure. White has a half-open e-file to work with, and we have a half-open c-file. Additionally, our pawn structure @@StartBracket@@later with ...e6@@EndBracket@@ will point towards the queenside, White's towards the kingside. This is a hint that we want to direct play towards the queenside, as we're used to doing.   Pay attention to the sparring positions in this chapter because, statistically, you will benefit most from practicing variations arising from this chapter.   Let's go! }
4. Nc3
{ This is tied for the most frequent move in this position @@StartBracket@@with Nf3 - developing the other knight@@EndBracket@@, but it's actually already an inaccuracy!  In this pawn structure with pawns on d4 and d5, the knight rarely belongs on c3 blocking its own pawn on c2. The c-pawn really wants to move! For this reason, White has far fewer chances for active play. }
4... Nc6
{ Our knight, by contrast, sits beautifully on c6 since it's not in the way of anything. }
5. Nf3
{ By far the most popular setup at this level, regardless of which knight developed first. }
5... Bg4
{ Pin it to win it!   The bully bishop is satisfied with its duties pinning and restricting the f3-knight which would someday love to hop into our territory on e5. }
6. Be2
{ This is the most popular way for White to play the Exchange Variation at the amateur level, but it's totally harmless.   Both the light-squared bishop and c3-knight are on the wrong squares. }
6... e6 7. O-O Bd6
{ SPARRING POSITION   The best square for the bishop, and staying flexible with the king's knight! Since this is the most common setup, I think it would be worth your while to spar against a friend or engine from here. }
8. h3 Bh5
{ g4 is not a threat anymore since White has castled and there is no Ne5. Therefore, we keep the bishop pair! }
9. Bg5 Nge7
{ A very nice setup for Black. The pin is temporary and the bishop is likely misplaced on g5. }
10. Nb5
{ This is another case of a most popular variation featuring aggressive-looking moves that aren't actually doing much. }
10... Bb8 { The bishop looks passive for now, but just wait a few moves... }
11. Ne5 { White only knows how to come forwards. } 11... Bxe2 12. Qxe2 a6
{ It's time to start asking White's pieces what they're doing in our house. }
13. Nxc6
{ Necessary to save the d-pawn.  13.Nc3  would drop a pawn with tempo to  Nxd4  . }
13... bxc6 14. Nc3 Qd6
{ Black has a strong pawn centre and a strong bishop-queenbattery to boot.   What's better than threatening mate in 1? }
15. g3 Nf5
{ Black is better and after castling, can go for either the ...f6, ...e5 break or the ...c5 break. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Elizabeth Hazim Gonzalez vs. Jovanka Houska, Tromso Olympiad, 2014"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8
{ This was my game against Elizabeth Hazim Gonzalez of the Dominican Republic from the 2014 Olympiad.  Here, I played my alternative recommendation in the course with this move, which minimizes exchanges and keeps the game alive. I've found this is a good approach against lower rated players.   This game is a great example of a successfulminority attack.   7...Na5  is the move I recommend in the course which can easily tempt White into getting overzealous on the queenside. }
8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 Be7 10. O-O Bh5
{ This is a standard maneuver in the Exchange Variation, trading off White's best piece. }
11. Rfe1 Bg6 12. Bxg6 hxg6
{ 95% of the time, it's best to recapture on g6 with the h-pawn, towards the centre! }
13. Ne5 O-O 14. Re2 Nd7
{ A good idea in principle, challenging White's central knight.   14...Nxe5  15.dxe5  Nd7  would have been better, not allowing White's other knight to fight for the e5-square. }
15. Rae1
{ 15.Nxd7  Qxd7  16.Nf3  was better for White, after which White's f3-knight has slightly more active prospects than our c6-knight. }
15... a6 16. Ndf3 b5
{ The minority attack is being launched!  The idea is to push both the a and b-pawns forward and create a weakness in White's pawn arrow! }
17. Qc2 Ncxe5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Bxe5
{ Usually exchanging both pairs of knights eliminates most of the attacking danger from the position, making it easier to focus on the minority attack. }
19... Qc4 { An active move, asking White how she wants to defend the pawn. }
20. b3
{ The wrong way to defend. Now, the c-pawn is a much easier target.   20.a3  would have been much more solid. Now we will need to work much harder to create a weakness. }
20... Qc6 21. Rc1 Rfc8
{ The correct rook to bring to c8, after which both rooks participate in the queenside initiative! }
22. Qd3 a5
{ I wanted to advance the a-pawn down the board in order to activate the a8-rook. }
23. h3 a4 24. c4
{ A pretty serious mistake, since we have 4 attackers on the c4-square to White's 3 defenders.  But, it's hard to sit and wait patiently while your position comes under further pressure. }
24... axb3 25. axb3
{ 25.c5  giving up the a-pawn would have been better, after which  25...bxa2  26.Ra1  White would win back the a-pawn and at least we have a bit less activity on the queenside. }
25... bxc4 26. bxc4 dxc4 27. Qe3 Qd5 28. Kh2 Ra3
{ Now, the position kind of plays itself as my queen sits on a beautiful central square and the other pieces flood into White's position, not to mention the dangerous passed c-pawn. }
29. Rc3 Rca8 30. Rb2 Ra2 31. Rb1 Bh4 32. g3 Bg5 33. Bf4 Bf6 34. Be5 Bg5 35. Bf4
Be7 36. h4 Ra1 37. Rcc1 Rxb1 38. Rxb1 Ra3 39. Qe5 Qf3 40. Be3 Ra2
{ with a nasty threat. } 41. Kg1
{ If White does nothing, the plan was   41.Rc1  Bd6  removing the defender of the bishop on e3.  42.Qxd6  Qxe3  Making use of the rook's pin on the f2-pawn and now ...Rxf2+ coming next is decisive. }
41... c3 { Passed pawns are meant to be pushed! } 42. Qb8+ Kh7 43. Qb3 Ra3 44.
Qc2 Bd6 45. Bc1 Ra6 46. Rb3 Rc6 47. Be3 Bxg3
{ White's defenses are stretched, and I was able to crash through with a tactical breakthrough as the f2-pawn isoverworked. }
48. h5 e5 49. h6 gxh6 50. dxe5 Bxe5
{ My opponent resigned here, down 3 pawns and with many ideas to involve the rook, threatening checkmate ideas. }
