[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance Variation Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 16% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@    Welcome to the Advance Variation. It's the most critical variation at most levels because White is given the opportunity to grab more central space. Having more space can be advantageous because it provides more room on the battlefield for the pieces to move around.  But we embrace the challenge of finding cozy squares for all our pieces, and that's exactly what we will do with the setup I've chosen. We will eventually counterattack in the center, freeing our game.    Because of Black's typical plans here, I actually really like Black's chances at the amateur level in the Advance Variation, and believe it is far less critical than at higher levels of play. Nonetheless, this is the biggest chapter in the course because White has many ways to play it, and we need to be ready. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle. }
4. Nf3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 32%@@EndBracket@@   4.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: less than 1%@@EndBracket@@   4...e6  5.Nb3  White wants to discourage our usual ...c5 break.  5...Nd7  6.Nf3  c5  ...But they can't prevent it.   4.Ne2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 1%@@EndBracket@@    The knight deploys itself to an unusual square from which it intends to harass the bishop with a further Ng3 and h4.  4...e6  5.Ng3  Bg6  6.h4  h5  Again, we meet h4 with h5. White thinks they're clever for luring the pawn out to h5 so they can target it. But it's not clear who's luring who when our central counterplay comes.   4.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: less than 1%@@EndBracket@@   The Shirov Attack. A dangerous but exceedingly rare option at the amateur level.  4...e6  5.g4  Bg6  6.Nge2  c5  White aims to harass the bishop and even win a pawn on the kingside, our central and queenside counterplay will more than suffice.   4.g4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 4%@@EndBracket@@   The Bayonnet Attack - aggressive but not as good as the related Shirov Attack  4...Bd7  Since ...e6 hasn't been played, we safely drop back.  5.c4  e6  White is claiming they have forced our bishop to live inside our pawn triangle, but I actually think it's kind of cozy in there, and we will aim to show g4 is a silly looking pawn.   4.c4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 4%@@EndBracket@@   An aggressive central push, but not as critical as waiting for Black to commit to ...c5 before doing so.  4...e6  5.Nc3  Ne7  6.Nf3  Nd7  We can simply keep things closed, develop the pieces this way and at the right moment take on c4 and secure the d5-outpost for a knight.   4.h4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 6%@@EndBracket@@   The Tal Variation Quick kingside expansion, threatening to trap the bishop if we now play the usual ...e6.  4...h5  Our response! Taking our share of kingside space, and securing the bishop by preventing any b4 pushes.  5.Bd3  The modern mainline.  5...Bxd3  6.Qxd3  e6  7.Bg5  The best move, but not the most common at lower levels.  7...Qd7  A solid move, maintaining control over the important d5 square in case White plays c4 and Nc3. World Champion, Ding Liren has played this before, so I'm calling it Ding d7.   4.f4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 9%@@EndBracket@@   Some strong players have tried this, but honestly I don't see the point. Later on, they're hoping for a kingside attack, but we will control the light-squares and that attack will never come.  4...e6  5.Nf3  c5  Simple counterplay featuring Old Faithful, ...Nc6 & ...Qb6 is enough to steer play away from the kingside.   4.Bd3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 21%@@EndBracket@@   There's no name for this one because it puts no pressure on Black, but it's the second most common at lower levels @@StartBracket@@the most common if you count starting with Nf3 and following it up with Bd3@@EndBracket@@  4...Bxd3  5.Qxd3  e6  Our pawn triangle is finished and White's best minor piece has already been traded. A successful opening already! }
4... e6 5. Be2
{ The Mainline ...even though the inferior  5.Bd3  is more common.  White wants to simply develop the kingside without trading pieces, quickly castle, and take it from there. }
5... Ne7 { Phase one of our plan in The Mainline. } 6. O-O c5
{ Phase two - deploying Old Faithful @@StartBracket@@the ...c5 break@@EndBracket@@. Phase Three is normally ...Nec6, opening our dark-squared bishop and following up with ...Nd7, ...Be7, ...O-O when all of our pieces have comfy squares.    My Five Lifelines:   A@@EndBracket@@ Don't let White secure a knight on d6.   B@@EndBracket@@ Don't land in a position where you are forced to recapture on d5 with the e-pawn.   C@@EndBracket@@ Try to pressurize the centre- specifically d4, and direct play towards the centre and queenside.   D@@EndBracket@@ Treat all your pieces with respect and find them all ideal homes.   E@@EndBracket@@ Exchanges are good! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Jacques Mieses vs. Marcus Kann"]
[Result "*"]

{ Let's start off with a little inspiration, and for our model game in the Advance Variation, who better to feature than one of the founders of the opening himself, Marcus Kann of Austria?   This is one of the only games of his we have on record, but with it's quite the little gem. It's a beautiful demonstration of our typical strategy against the Advance, and features some tantalizing tactics in the end featuring the concept of anoverworked piece. Kann's opponent was a strong and well-respected British-German master, so this game really sent waves through the European chess world and helped put our beloved opening on the map.   This left a big impression on me when I first saw it, and I hope it will for you too. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Bd3
{ The most popular square for the bishop at amateur level. But even at master-level, back in the day, they didn't know any better! }
4... Bxd3 5. Qxd3 e6
{ As we learn in the theory section, this variation is completely harmless because White's valuable light-squared bishop has already traded itself for our own, arguably less valuable bishop. Not only that, but trades usually favour Black since we have less space. }
6. f4
{ Another suboptimal decision. White wants to attack later on the kingside, but in reality it only weakens the light squares, and Black will be able to maintain firm control of the important f5-square. }
6... c5 { Here comes Old Faithful! } 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Qb6
{ Take a mental snapshot.   The pawn, knight, and queen work together to pressurize White's centre, and the queen also reminds White they have the b-pawn to worry about. As we learn in the theory section, pretty much all of these variations when White defends the centre with c3 are suboptimal, allowing Black an easy game. }
9. O-O Nh6
{ 9... Ne7 would be inferior since it blocks the bishop's view of the c-pawn, and prevents the bishop from developing.  In these f4 lines, this is usually the better square to develop the knight on since there is no longer the Bxh6 option, and our knight and bishop no longer need to fight for the e7-square. }
10. b3
{ A dreadfully common approach to defend the b2 pawn from capture is to push it one square ahead. It prepares further defense for the d4-square via Bb2, but this is hopelessly passive. }
10... cxd4 11. cxd4 Nf5
{ First, Kann took on d4 to cement a weakness before leaping into the most active square for the knight. Here we are threatening to capture the pawn and White is forced into further passivity. }
12. Bb2 Rc8
{ Let's pause to evaluate the position now that the central structure is defined:   Piece development is about equal, but the quality of development for Black is far superior. Both knights and queen work together to attack a weakness while Black has no such weakness to be seen. Meanwhile, all of White's developed pieces are passively defending that weakness.    After the cooperative Bd3, followed by the slow and weakening f4 and b3, it stands to reason that Black should have such activity.  ...Rc8 develops a new piece to a square it definitely belongs on since the c-file is free of pawns. Good pieces lead to good tactics!   This is about to go downhill fast for White. }
13. a3
{ Mieses didn't want to deal with ...Nb4 coming in, but White couldn't afford to make yet another slow pawn move.   White should have developed a piece with  13.Nbd2  when after  13...Nb4  14.Qb1  it's not super obvious how Black should continue. }
13... Ncxd4
{ Because of that silly f4 move, White's king is exposed along the g1-a7 diagonal and is about to feel the consequences.  But doesn't White have enough defenders on d4? If you go by the numbers alone, yes. But because of the weakened diagonal, Black will involve another attacker in the bishop! }
14. Nxd4
{ 14.Bxd4  will transpose to the game.  14...Nxd4  15.Nxd4   15.Qxd4  Bc5  would immediately win the queen and the game.  Bc5  16.Rd1  when again, it looks as if White is defending, but...  16...Bxd4+  17.Qxd4  Rc1  with the same position as in the game. }
14... Bc5
{ Adding another attacker to the weak d4 square with a devastating pin. } 15.
Rd1 Nxd4
{ It may look like Black is simplifying into an equal endgame, but not so. }
16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Rc1
{ BOOM! Kann had this all worked out at least before he decided to capture on d4. A deadly double threat!  If Black had another move, both ...Rxd1+ and ...Qxd4+ would win the game since both of White's pieces are pinned and cannot recapture.   Because of the added feature of White's exposed king, It's impossible for White to defend against both threats. }
18. Kf2
{ 18.Qxb6  would allow the lovelyzwischenzug,  18...Rxd1+  with check!  19.Kf2  axb6  and would lead to a similarly hopeless position as in the game.   18.Rxc1  would leave the queen undefended and after  18...Qxd4+  19.Kf1  Qxa1  Black could even pick up the rook in the corner with a winning endgame. }
18... Rxd1 19. Qxb6 axb6
{ Let's count material.    Because Black gave up a piece for a pawn on d4 to initiate these tactics, and given we just won a rook, the net result is that we've won an exchange and a pawn @@StartBracket@@3 points@@EndBracket@@ - more than enough to win the game, especially from such a dominating position. There's no way for White to escape the knight pin. }
20. Ke2 Rc1 21. Kd2 Rg1 { Maintaining the pin. } 22. g3 Kd7
{ Preparing to bring the other rook to c1 in order to win the pinned piece. }
23. a4 Rc8 24. b4 Rcc1
{ Due to the pin, White loses further material. Finally, White resigned.   A beautifully thematic example of punishing slow and weakening moves in the Advance Variation. Remember that good pieces lead to good tactics! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.Nd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Nd2
{ As with each chapter in the course, we will start our coverage with rare lines, not frequently seen at lower levels according to the online database.    It's a major question for White what to do with the b1 knight in the Advance Variation, and in this line, their idea is to plonk it on b3 and discourage our favourite ...c5break! How dare they? While incredibly rare at amateur level, this idea is championed by many top players such as Wesley So, Leinier Dominguez Perez, and Nodirbek Abdusattorov.   But don't worry, ...c5 is coming whether White likes it or not. }
4... e6
{ This will usually be our move only after developing the bishop outside of thepawn chain . Our light squared bishop, as a result, is much happier about life than it would be in the French @@StartBracket@@where it would still be sitting on c8@@EndBracket@@. }
5. Nb3 Nd7
{ In the mainlines of the Advance Variation, as we will see in a little bit, our main idea is to first develop the other knight to e7 and wait on the development of this one. However, we really want to play ...c5 as quickly as possible, so here we make an exception. }
6. Nf3 c5
{ Woohoo! This is the first, but most definitely not the last time we will be seeing our favourite break, ...c5!    In chess, in order to activate your pieces, often times you need to push a pawn forward in conflict with one of your opponents' in order to open lines.    The ...c5-break acheives slightly different things in different variations, and I will explain the differences when we get there in each case. Here, Since we have a bit less central space, the ...c5-break aims to free our position and start queenside counterplay. In this specific position, if White does nothing, we may even push it one square forward and make the knight question its existence on b3. When I am able to play the ...c5-break on the board, and I'm not blundering anything, I'm usually smiling to myself and feeling good, and you should too! From now on, I will refer to the ...c5-break as Old Faithful, since it's always there for us. }
7. dxc5
{ White usually takes, not to allow our pawn to advance further. But this plays into our hands. }
7... Bxc5
{ We take by developing a piece, not concerned about losing the bishop pair since the position is relatively closed. }
8. Nxc5 Nxc5 9. Bb5+ Nd7
{ Of course we would prefer to block the check with a piece instead of giving up castling rights by moving the king! Remember, king safety is the most important consideration and the king is usually not safe in the middle.  The position is more or lessbalanced.
White has the bishop pair, but all of our pieces have found perfect squares. Next we will play ...Ne7, ...O-O, probably ...Rc8 and try to expand on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "🧨 Advance: 4.Ne2 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Ne2
{ A very rare idea at all levels, but I've seen it before.  White says, If you're going to bring your bishop out into the light of day, I'm going to harass it!    Not very nice, is it? But again, it's not that scary. But then again, Dutch phenom, Jordan Van Forrest has been playing it lately, so let's have a look. }
4... e6
{ Normal stuff, opening a square for ...Ne7 and preparing Old Faithful @@StartBracket@@...c5@@EndBracket@@ }
5. Ng3 Bg6
{ Our bishop is under attack. We could defend it with  5...Ne7  ,  but we normally don't want to give up thebishop pair without a fight, so we simply drop back. }
6. h4
{ More bad intentions from the White side against our poor bishop. If we allow White to push one more time with 7. h5, we would be in a lot of trouble. }
6... h5
{ So, let's stop it in its tracks.    Yes but isn't this pawn a sitting duck for White to target?   Yes, but while White is messing around on the kingside, our centralcounterplay is going to be more relevant!   Ok, show me! }
7. Be2
{ True, it's impossible to defend this pawn, as White has three attackers vs. our two, but If White thinks they're getting something for nothing, they're sorely mistaken. }
7... c5 { Watch as Old Faithful guides the way! } 8. Nxh5
{ 8.Bxh5  Capturing this way is no better for White...  8...Bxh5  9.Nxh5  cxd4  The white queen isoverloaded - the d4-pawn cannot be recaptured due to the hanging knight on h5.   The trade of our h-pawn for the strong central d-pawn is heavily in Black's favour! }
8... cxd4
{ An eye for an eye, but we got the better trade as our h-pawn was not nearly as valuable as White's strong central d-pawn. Furthermore, the d4-pawn cannot be recaptured because of the pressure on the h5-knight. White has gotten themselves in a pickle. }
9. Nf4 Be4
{ No need to give White what they want from this variation and part with our bishop. }
10. f3 Rxh4
{ A beautiful move, pointing out that all White achieved from this variation was opening the h-file for our pieces! Clearly, Black cannot capture the bishop since they drop the h1-rook. }
11. Bb5+
{ A desperate check that achieves nothing for White.  11.Rxh4  Qxh4+  12.Kf1  Bf5  White's king is forever exposed.   There's some work to do, but it's a long, painful road ahead for White. }
11... Nc6 12. O-O Bf5
{ White tries to find safety for the king, but Black has everything in this position - an extra pawn, easy moves , and the h-file for attacking! }
