[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "🧨 Advance: 4.Nc3 (Shirov) #1 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Nc3
{ The Shirov Attack! Named after the Latvian legend, Grandmaster Alexei Shirov, this is one of the most aggressive ways to fight the Caro-Kann.   If we take this move in isolation, it looks pretty stupid because normally White wants to use the c-pawn, and here the knight sits in the way of it. But there is venom, and I've marked this as a Dynamite line for a reason, so pay attention because White wants blood! }
4... e6
{ One of the clever points of 4. Nc3 is that they would like to play g4, but only after Black commits to ...e6 so that the retreat square on d7 is no longer available.   We are going to end up sacrificing a pawn in this line, but fear not - as always, our central and queenside play is going tocompensate! }
5. g4 Bg6 { Our bishop was hit, so we move it back. No problem. } 6. Nge2
{ 6.h4  immediately is an inaccurate move-order and if your opponent plays this way it means they aren't familiar with the idea behind the Shirov Attack!  6...h5  The same move we play in the mainline, but now White doesn't have Nf5, the move they were counting on.  7.g5  Ne7  Whenever you see this pawn construction on the kingside, it usually means Black has brilliant control over the light-squares.   All of White's pawns are on dark squares, which means they're not controlling the light-squares, which means our pieces can comfortably sit on them!  8.Nf3  c5  Just like in the mainline of the Advance Variation @@StartBracket@@with 4. Nf3 and 5. Be2@@EndBracket@@, we are able to achieve our normal plan of ...Ne7 and ...c5, but because of our light-squared control, it's an even better version! }
6... c5
{ White is clearly up to no good on the kingside, so we need to drum up our typical central counterplay.    By the way, we don't call it counterplay because it's inferior to White's play, only because it's the usual convention when referring to Black's play out of the opening. }
7. Nf4
{ White could opt for the immediate Nf4, but this doesn't seem to achieve much. }
7... Nc6 { We continue to put pressure on the centre. } 8. Be3
{ White defends the centre, but we have a trick up our sleeve.  8.Nxg6  Only does Black a favour by activating our dormant rook along the h-file!  8...hxg6  This is a clear case of getting something great in return for the bishop pair. }
8... cxd4 9. Bxd4 Bxc2
{ Whoops. White could easily miss thisdeflection tactic. We grab a pawn and if White recaptures... }
10. Qxc2 Nxd4
{ Black emerges a clear pawn up. It's not over, but this clearly wasn't what White had bargained for in the Shirov Attack. But it serves them right for going after our bishop the wrong way and then not even taking it! }
