[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.g4 (Bayonet Attack) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack!   White lashes out immediately against the newly-developed bishop. It's related to the Shirov Attack, this is a much more popular variation at amateur level, which is good because this line is even less dangerous. }
4... Bd7
{ Remember how in the Shirov Attack we had to drop our bishop back to g6? Well here it's even safer on d7, so we don't need to enter such complications on the kingside. We will comfortably continue our central plan with Old Faithful in mind. }
5. f4
{ A popular move at lower levels as it seems to gain all the central space, but really it's more of a weakening move, and one which we immediately take advantage of. }
5... h5
{ White's pawn has to budge, but given how push-happy White has been up to now, maybe they won't be upset about this and walk willingly into an inferior position. }
6. g5
{ White cannot support this pawn with  6.h3  as  hxg4  7.hxg4  Rxh1  would win for Black! This is an extremely thematic tactic, and one that highlights how weakening pawn moves on the side of the board such as g4 can turn out to be. }
6... Bf5
{ It may come as a surprise, but moving the bishop again to make sure it ends up outside the pawn chain is actually the best idea here! We are told not to move the same piece in the opening twice, but here we have an exception.   White has made ONLY pawn moves, and weakening ones at that, so we are at full liberty to do this. }
7. Nf3 e6
{ Due to White's ill-advised pawn advances, Black is left with excellent light-square control, and likely will be for the rest of the game. This means White will have no clear plan on the kingside which they sometimes do. So, we can now continue with our normal ... Ne7 combined with Old Faithful @@StartBracket@@...c5@@EndBracket@@, ...Qb6, a knight to c6, and all the typical moves which pressurize White's centre.   In short, it's another example of a superior version of the mainlines we will see later. }
