1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. g4
{ The Bayonet Attack!   White lashes out immediately against the newly-developed bishop. It's related to the Shirov Attack, this is a much more popular variation at amateur level, which is good because this line is even less dangerous. }
4... Bd7
{ Remember how in the Shirov Attack we had to drop our bishop back to g6? Well here it's even safer on d7, so we don't need to enter such complications on the kingside. We will comfortably continue our central plan with Old Faithful in mind. }
5. c4
{ A typical move, trying to break down Black's solid centre. But honestly combined with g4,  it doesn't make a lot of sense.  5.Nf3  Bxg4  would be a whoopsie for White. }
5... e6
{ With a pawn on g4, it's clear the bishop won't be getting out this time, but it's ok. It's cozy there and the g4-pawn doesn't make a good impression. }
6. Nc3
{ A weird version of the Shirov Attack where Black's bishop is out of harm's way on d7.  6.c5  A lot of beginners like to push pawns as far as they can go with no regard for their pieces. Let's see what can happen.  6...b6  A thematic way to break down White's pawns, and open lines. White has no good way to keep this structure in tact.  7.b4  would be the desired reaction, but after  7...a5  8.a3  axb4  9.axb4  Rxa1  We can clearly see how misguided the c5 push was in the first place.   7.cxb6  Qxb6  is simply excellent for Black, with ...c5 coming and superior development. }
6... c5
{ Old Faithful! This break makes a lot of sense because it highlights the fact that the pawn on g4 is doing nothing, and we would like to direct play towards the centre! }
7. cxd5
{ In any variation where we allow White to capture our d5-pawn after we've already played ...c5, we will need to be aware of potentialdynamics. Sometimes our d5-pawn is loose, and the nature of the positions tend to be quite tactical, which makes sense the more lines open in the centre.   Remember, when the center starts to open, you need to start spending more time and calculating, and you can't always rely on typical plans anymore. }
7... exd5 8. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Our central pawn is falling, but we have superior development and plenty of active counterplay. Also, White's pawns are no great shakes themselves. }
9. Nxd5
{ This capture on d5 makes less sense because it allows an uncomfortable pin along the a8-h1 diagonal. }
9... Bc6 { White will have to squirm to get out of this one. } 10. Bg2 Ne7
{ We continue to pile pressure on the knight. Perhaps at this point, White is starting to feel regrets for taking our d5-pawn!  10...Bxd5  A common beginner mistake is to trade pieces unnecessarily. After  11.Qxd5  Qxd5  12.Bxd5  It's White who has the upper hand with the bishop pair and extra pawn. }
11. Ne3 { The only move to save the piece. } 11... Qxd1+
{ But this time we can favourably simplify the position. } 12. Kxd1
{ 12.Nxd1  would hang not only the bishop, but the h1-rook after  Bxg2  . }
12... O-O
{ Black's b8-knight will come to c6, other knight to g6, rooks to the centre with beautifully harmonious piece play and White will struggle to hold onto that e5-pawn. }
