[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.c4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. c4
{ Here, White attempts to undermine our pawn centre right away, and intends to follow up with Nc3 when it will be ideally placed behind its pawn @@StartBracket@@not blocking it as in the Shirov Attack, for example@@EndBracket@@.    You will hardly ever see this one because amateurs are taught to develop their pieces before making too many pawn moves, but any variation including c4 tends to be critical in the Advance Variation. After all, Magnus has played this one a few times, so let's have a look. }
4... e6 { Our usual move, stabilising the centre. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.cxd5  cxd5  In 95% of cases, if White captures on d5, we want to recapture with the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@or a knight, once our knight lands on e7@@EndBracket@@. This is because the c-file can be useful for queenside counterplay, and its a safer structure. With a pawn on e6, it's much harder for White to attack us. }
5... Ne7
{ We play the same move we do in the mainline, but for different reasons.  Here, the knight is playing a very important role in supporting the critical d5-point. Now we even have the option of recapturing on d5 with a knight, which will usually be our choice. Either that, or we can eventually capture on c4 ourselves, which will also give us that beautiful d5outpost for the knight. }
6. Nf3 Nd7
{ But for now, we just develop normally, and see what White has in mind.  What I like about this variation for Black is that while White looks aggressively postured, they have no way to add further pressure to our centre, and will likely end up resolving thetension in the centre in our favour just because they will run out of useful moves.   So, patience is key in this variation. We don't want to rush in with Old Faithful in this line. }
7. Bg5
{ A common move, pinning the e7-knight. Maybe White would like to capture on d5 next move when we would be unable to recapture with the knight.   Let's avoid that. }
7... Qb6
{ Stepping out of the pin with a threat on the b2-pawn.  In the opening, it's always best to play multipurposed moves! }
8. b3 Bg4
{ A nice idea, pinning knight and threatening to take it and ruin White's pawn structure. Further, we free the f5-square for the knight one day.    One drawback of playing c4 for White is that the d4-pawn can become weak! }
9. Na4
{ 9.h3  Bxf3  10.gxf3  Taking with the queen would drop the d4-pawn.  10...Nf5  Black is already strategically winning with a permanent outpost on f5 for the knight, putting pressure on the centre. }
9... Qc7
{ White says they'd rather not have the queen pressurizing d4 anymore, but not to worry, the queen sits comfortably on c7 and soon the queenside will open in Black's favour. }
10. Be2 Bxf3
{ It may seem counterintuitive, but there's a method to this madness! We don't normally capture a knight with a bishop without being provoked, but it achieves two purposes:    A@@EndBracket@@ We loosen the defense of the d4-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ More importantly, we draw the e2-bishop away from the queenside so we can push ...b5! }
11. Bxf3 b5
{ The perfect moment for the ...b5 break. It may not be obvious at first why it is superior to Old Faithful, so let's discuss.  The ...b5 break opens the queenside only, not the centre. White has two bishops @@StartBracket@@and bishops enjoy open positions@@EndBracket@@ on the kingside. If the centre is opened with ...c5, they would be contributing to the fight.    As they stand after ...b5, they look lonely and meanwhile we continue play on the queenside where we have more active prospects. }
