{ But for now, we just develop normally, and see what White has in mind.  What I like about this variation for Black is that while White looks aggressively postured, they have no way to add further pressure to our centre, and will likely end up resolving thetension in the centre in our favour just because they will run out of useful moves.   So, patience is key in this variation. We don't want to rush in with Old Faithful in this line. }
7. cxd5
{ Many players will take your d-pawn and hand you a beautiful knight outpost on a silver platter. You should accept it gratefully. }
7... Nxd5
{ This is considered an outpost for the knight since it can never be kicked away by a pawn! Also note thebackward pawn on d4 vulnerable to attack later on. }
8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Be7 10. O-O O-O
{ The position is balanced.   White has space, and Black has a central outpost. It's not so easy for either side to make progress without weakening their positions, but we have easy moves to make from here including ...Qa5, ...Rfd8 and ...Nf8 @@StartBracket@@Lending some support to the kingside and unblocking the view of the rook@@EndBracket@@. Instead of our usual ...c5 plan, which would take need to be arranged carefully @@StartBracket@@to avoid having our e-pawn displaced or being attacked in the centre@@EndBracket@@, simpler is to maneuver and add pressure to the d4-point.   To summarize this early c4 variation, while it looks imposing, after we bring our trusty knight to e7, supporting d5, White quickly runs out of steam. Our middlegame plans are:   A@@EndBracket@@ If the pawn stays on c4, eventually open the queenside with the ...b5 break. Remember the ...Bg4/ Bxf3 plan to misplace the bishop.   B@@EndBracket@@ If White takes on d5, recapture with the knight, or the c-pawn if needed.    C@@EndBracket@@ Later you may be able to capture on c4 yourself to secure the d5-outpost and familiar structure. }
