[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "🧨 Advance: 4.h4 (Tal Variation) #1 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. h4
{ The Tal Variation!  This one is named after the former World Champion, Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@also of Latvia@@EndBracket@@. It's kind of funny that two adjacent, aggressive pawn moves in the same position are named after two Latvian Grandmasters.  It's another way to harass the f5-bishop, but we're used to it by now. First and foremost, White has set a little trap.  Do you see it? }
4... h5
{ Just as in the Shirov Attack, we meet h4 with ...h5. Only this time, there is no pawn on g4, so the position is quite different. While White can go after that h5-pawn here too, the usual plan is to try to attack us on the kingside, but the system I've chosen, as in the Shirov, will usually redirect play towards the centre and queenside. Let's see.  4...e6  would be a fatal blunder as after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  The bishop has run out of squares. Whoops! Do NOT fall for this one and play ...e6 on autopilot! }
5. c4
{ The old mainline, and one of the most aggressive approaches to the Advance Variation. White wants to develop the knight quickly on c3 where it works together with the c4-pawn to pressurize our centre. }
5... e6 { Finishing our pawn triangle, as always. } 6. Nc3 Ne7
{ Our normal response when White opts for an early c4 - adding support to the d5-square. }
7. Nge2
{ An indication that White wants to hit our bishop with Ng3, putting pressure on our h5-pawn. As we saw in theearly Ne2 line for example, going pawn-grabbing on h5 is too slow, neglecting the centre. }
7... Nd7 8. Ng3 Bg6
{ The precise retreat square, not giving up on h5 so easily. } 9. Bg5
{ Indirectly pressurizing d5 by pinning the knight.  9.Be2  Kingside pawn-hunting doesn't mix well with this c4 plan so well since the bishop can't both target h5 and guard c4.  9...dxc4  If White wants to recapture on c4, an extra tempo will need to be spent by the bishop.    Now with the d5 outpost for our knights and the centre opening, we are completely fine! }
9... Qb6
{ Sidestepping the pin since, as we know, we'd like to recapture on d5 with a piece. We also attack the b2-pawn. }
10. Rc1
{ If White decides to hold onto that pawn, taking their foot off the gas, any initiative they hoped for immediately dissolves.  10.Qd2  dxc4  11.Bxc4  O-O-O  Our king is lovely on the queenside, and we can continue with ...Kb8 and move our queen somewhere cozy so we can go ...Nb6, dominating the light squares. }
10... Qxb2
{ It's a little risky to move your queen so far behind enemy lines, but sometimes you gotta take up the gauntlet and go for it! }
11. Bd3 Bxd3 12. Qxd3 dxc4 { It's a good moment to take on c4 with tempo. } 13.
Qxc4 Nb6
{ Another tempo, eyeing the central light-squares. In this structure after an exchange of d-pawn for c-pawn, remember this knight loves the b6-square! }
14. Qd3 Ned5 { Jumping in the hole! } 15. O-O Qa3
{ Mission accomplished - we got away with the b-pawn scott-free!  This is a nice move to pin the knight and sidestep any rook attacks in the future. Now, ...Bb4 is a threat, which is quite tricky for White to meet. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "🧨 Advance: 4.h4 (Tal Variation) #2 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. h4
{ The Tal Variation!  This one is named after the former World Champion, Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@also of Latvia@@EndBracket@@. It's kind of funny that two adjacent, aggressive pawn moves in the same position are named after two Latvian Grandmasters.  It's another way to harass the f5-bishop, but we're used to it by now. First and foremost, White has set a little trap.   Do you see it? }
4... h5
{ Just as in the Shirov Attack, we meet h4 with ...h5. Only this time, there is no pawn on g4, so the position is quite different. While White can go after that h5-pawn here too, the usual plan is to try to attack us on the kingside, but the system I've chosen, as in the Shirov, will usually redirect play towards the centre and queenside. Let's see.  4...e6  would be a fatal blunder as after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  The bishop has run out of squares. Whoops! Do NOT fall for this one and play ...e6 on autopilot! }
5. Bd3
{ The main move.  5.Nf3  is possible but after  e6  6.Bd3  Bg4  We start to understand why White prefers Bd3 immediately. White would rather trade the bishop and not allow this pin when since h4 has been played, it's not easy to deal with that bishop.   Black is extremely comfortable here.   5.Bg5  can be a tricky move order, but since we aren't playing the mainlines, White doesn't seem to have a very meaningful way to continue without transposing via: 5...Qd7 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6  . }
5... Bxd3
{ When a bishop lands on d3, we usually take it because White's light-squared bishop is usually the strong one in all variations of the Caro-Kann.   Time out!   Why is that, you might ask?   There are good bishops and bad bishops. The good bishop is on the opposite colour complex as the friendly central pawns, and the bad bishop is on the same colour as the friendly central pawns @@StartBracket@@because the pawns tend to block the bishop's vision@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Qxd3 e6 { Solidifying our centre the usual way. } 7. Nf3
{ Most amateurs are taught to develop their knights before their bishops but this allows the immediate ...c5. }
7... c5
{ As a general rule in the Advance Variation, we wheel out Old Faithful at the earliest opportunity. If we continue developing and allow White to do the same before striking back in the centre, it might be too late! }
8. dxc5
{ If White takes on c5 and allows us to recapture and develop a piece, we should generally be very happy! But beware of potential Qb5 forks. }
8... Bxc5 9. Qb5+ Nd7
{ The only move to save the bishop. Just make sure you don't lose a piece on c5 @@StartBracket@@for example, in some cases where the knight has been traded or something@@EndBracket@@. Moving on, White can win the b7-pawn, but at the price of a lot of activity! }
10. Qxb7 Rb8 { Developing the rook with atempo. } 11. Qa6 Ne7
{ Finishing development and preparing ...Nf5, a great outpost for the knight. }
12. O-O Rb6 13. Qe2
{ 13.Qxa7  would fail to  13...Rxb2  with adiscovered attack. } 13... Nf5
{ Yes, White is up a pawn, but Black has pressure on both sides of the board. Sometimes it's worth giving up a pawn to open a file for the rook. }
