4. h4
{ The Tal Variation!  This one is named after the former World Champion, Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@also of Latvia@@EndBracket@@. It's kind of funny that two adjacent, aggressive pawn moves in the same position are named after two Latvian Grandmasters.  It's another way to harass the f5-bishop, but we're used to it by now. White has set a little trap.  Do you see it? }
4... h5
{ Just as in the Shirov Attack, we meet h4 with ...h5. Only this time, there is no pawn on g4, so the position is quite different. While White can go after that h5-pawn here too, the usual plan is to try to attack us on the kingside, but the system I've chosen, as in the Shirov, will usually redirect play towards the centre and queenside. Let's see.  4...e6  would be a fatal blunder as after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  The bishop has run out of squares. Whoops! Do NOT fall for this one and play ...e6 on autopilot! }
5. Bd3
{ The main move.  5.Nf3  is possible but after  e6  6.Bd3  Bg4  We start to understand why White prefers Bd3 immediately. White would rather trade the bishop and not allow this pin when since h4 has been played, it's not easy to deal with that bishop.   Black is extremely comfortable here.   5.Bg5  can be a tricky move order, but since we aren't playing the mainlines, White doesn't seem to have a very meaningful way to continue without transposing via: 5...Qd7 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6  . }
5... Bxd3
{ When a bishop lands on d3, we usually take it because White's light-squared bishop is usually the strong one in all variations of the Caro-Kann.   Time out!   Why is that, you might ask?   There are good bishops and bad bishops. The good bishop is on the opposite colour complex as the friendly central pawns, and the bad bishop is on the same colour as the friendly central pawns @@StartBracket@@because the pawns tend to block the bishop's vision@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Qxd3 e6 { Solidifying our centre the usual way. } 7. Nf3
{ Most amateurs are taught to develop their knights before their bishops but this allows the immediate ...c5. }
7... c5
{ As a general rule in the Advance Variation, we wheel out Old Faithful at the earliest opportunity. If we continue developing and allow White to do the same before striking back in the centre, it might be too late! }
8. Bg5 Qb6
{ This is an improved version of the line with @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp3pp1/2p1p3/3pP2p/3P3P/3Q4/PPP2PP1/RNB1K1NR w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Bg5  Qb6  because in this variation  8.Nf3  is not the most useful move. Better is  8.Nd2  preparing c4.   Here, Black's central counterplay comes quickly, especially as most amateurs will want to defend the b-pawn by pushing it one square forward, which is usually not a good idea. }
9. c4
{ Probably the most testing move. As in all cases when White pushes c4 after we've already pushed ...c5, we need to be a little careful.  9.Nbd2  c4  Anytime White allows us to press forward with ...c4 with tempo against the queen, it is generally good. White doesn't have enough play on the kingside to form a serious attack.  10.Qc3  White tries to keep hold of the b-pawn, but in vain.  Bb4  The start of a forcing sequence when Black wins the b-pawn by force.  11.Qe3  Bxd2+  12.Qxd2  Qxb2  And now without the knight on d2, there is no Rb1.  13.O-O  Qa3  Stepping out of any Rb1 threats. Now we can calmly meet  14.Rfb1  with  14...b6  .   9.b3  Provoking such a pawn move should give you a nice boost of confidence because    A@@EndBracket@@ It's not a developing move.   B@@EndBracket@@ The dark-squares have been weakened.  cxd4  With this move, we prepare to bring out the dark-squared bishop, exerting influence on the dark squares, and only then the knight goes to e7.  10.Nxd4  Bc5  We extra enjoy such developing moves when they come with an attack on a piece!  Note there's also an indirect attack on f2 if the knight were to move away.  11.Be3  Defending the knight.  Ne7  Black is much better because of the extra central pawn, and because White has been forced to make slow moves such as b3 and Be3.    We will continue with normal moves such as ... Nbc6, ...Rc8, ...Ng6, and White will struggle to keep hold of the e5-pawn without further weaknesses. }
9... dxc4
{ In this case, we have a comfortable way to minimize any risk in the position and go into an equal endgame. I think if your opponent plays this way, it means they want a sharp, tactical skirmish so let's not give them what they want! }
10. Qxc4 Qb4+ { Forcing the exchange of queens. } 11. Nbd2 Qxc4 12. Nxc4 Nc6
{ Developing the knight to its most natural square, pressurizing d4. } 13. dxc5
Bxc5
{ Next is ...Nge7 where it can either go to f5 or d5 depending on the circumstances, ...O-O and rooks to the centre! }
