4. h4
{ The Tal Variation!  This one is named after the former World Champion, Mikhail Tal @@StartBracket@@also of Latvia@@EndBracket@@. It's kind of funny that two adjacent, aggressive pawn moves in the same position are named after two Latvian Grandmasters.  It's another way to harass the f5-bishop, but we're used to it by now. White has set a little trap.  Do you see it? }
4... h5
{ Just as in the Shirov Attack, we meet h4 with ...h5. Only this time, there is no pawn on g4, so the position is quite different. While White can go after that h5-pawn here too, the usual plan is to try to attack us on the kingside, but the system I've chosen, as in the Shirov, will usually redirect play towards the centre and queenside. Let's see.  4...e6  would be a fatal blunder as after  5.g4  Be4  6.f3  Bg6  7.h5  The bishop has run out of squares. Whoops! Do NOT fall for this one and play ...e6 on autopilot! }
5. Bd3
{ The main move.  5.Nf3  is possible but after  e6  6.Bd3  Bg4  We start to understand why White prefers Bd3 immediately. White would rather trade the bishop and not allow this pin when since h4 has been played, it's not easy to deal with that bishop.   Black is extremely comfortable here.   5.Bg5  can be a tricky move order, but since we aren't playing the mainlines, White doesn't seem to have a very meaningful way to continue without transposing via: 5...Qd7 6. Bd3 Bxd3 7. Qxd3 e6  . }
5... Bxd3
{ When a bishop lands on d3, we usually take it because White's light-squared bishop is usually the strong one in all variations of the Caro-Kann.   Time out!   Why is that, you might ask?   There are good bishops and bad bishops. The good bishop is on the opposite colour complex as the friendly central pawns, and the bad bishop is on the same colour as the friendly central pawns @@StartBracket@@because the pawns tend to block the bishop's vision@@EndBracket@@. }
6. Qxd3 e6 { Solidifying our centre the usual way. } 7. Bg5
{ This is the most critical variation, but not the most popular.   The benefit is that White hits the queen and simultaneously prepares Nd2 when the bishop is already developed. }
7... Qd7
{ Black has many options including  7...Qa5  and  7...Qb6  @@StartBracket@@which I seriously considered for this course@@EndBracket@@ but I went with the modest, and solid ...Qd7, which is the current World Champion, Ding Liren's move of choice when he plays the Caro-Kann.   I hereby dub the variation beginning with this move, Ding d7. I like it because it is a bit less dynamic and risky than the other options, the queen continues to support the d5 pawn, and next we are unleashing Old Faithful, which hasn't let us down yet! }
8. Nf3
{ The main move, since it doesn't make as much sense to strike in the centre right away with the queen on d7.  8.Nc3  This is a strange move, blocking the c-pawn.  c5  After a move like this, ... c5 is a safe choice.  9.Nf3  cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nc6  Black has an easy game and it's still not clear why White would prefer the knight in front of its c-pawn.   We will continue with ...Nge7, taking on d4, ...Nf5, and take it from there. }
8... Ne7
{ Although this wasn't Ding's preference @@StartBracket@@he went for the immediate 8... c5@@EndBracket@@, I think some patience is called for.    This is definitely one of the most critical variations in the entire course, so I think it's better not to initiate a sharp, tactical skirmish unless you're well prepared!  Furthermore, White's c4 advance is much less scary if our c-pawn is still on c6, lending support to our centre. We can always open things later with ...c5 when the moment is right. For now, let's focus on developing! }
9. c4
{ The way I see it, White has two stylistic options - to play c4, or to continue developing. Let's see what happens if they go straight in for c4. }
9... dxc4
{ In this line, when you see the pawn land on c4, just keep it simple and snap it off. }
10. Qxc4 Na6
{ Since our queen is in the way of the usual d7 square, this knight finds another way into the game. From here, it can later use the c7-square to pivot to d5. You can also start with  10...Nf5  . Both moves are necessary so it doesn't really make a difference. However, when faced with such decisions, I'm always opting to develop a new piece. }
11. Nc3 Nf5
{ The perfect square for the knight where it puts pressure on White'sbackward d-pawn. }
12. O-O Be7
{ Developing the last piece. Although White has half-opened the c- and d-files, the position is still pretty closed and there are plenty of chances to outplay your opponent given the imbalanced pawn structure.    Warning: If you can help it, do NOT allow a white knight to land on d6 - at least without getting something in return. Here, we can exchange dark-squared bishops because the f5-knight is watching over this square. Meanwhile, the d5-square is a much easier outpost for Black to make use of.    This kind of rich and imbalanced position, where a long maneuvering game lies ahead, is one of the things that really excites me about chess.  SPARRING POSITION:  This is the kind of thing I expect you will see a lot in the Tal Variation. }
*

