[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. f4
{ You will be excited to hear that this is the least threatening move of all of the fourth move kingside pawn pushes we've seen, and also the most popular by some margin! Most recently it was played a couple times in blitz by Norwegian superstar, Aryan Tari, and then amusingly, a few months later, Caruana played it in a blitz game with the White pieces against Tari and took him down!    White wants to develop the knight to f3 only after pushing the f-pawn. They are hoping for a kingside attack one day, but if we stick to our normal plans, that attack will never come. }
4... e6
{ The bishop is in no danger of getting trapped, so we are free to continue as normal. }
5. Nf3 c5
{ White has already spent a move @@StartBracket@@f4@@EndBracket@@ on the kingside, so we might as well start our counterplay! }
6. c3
{ This is overwhelmingly the most common move, supporting the centre. But as usual when I see this move, my eyes light up as this gives Black an easy game.  6.c4  dxc4  is quite harmless for Black, and we will follow up with the normal ...Nc6 and maybe even ...Qa5+ in some cases. }
6... Nc6
{ The knight goes grazing, and this time even the queen can go grazing! } 7.
Be3 Qb6
{ White's position is already a little precarious, with pressure on b2 and d4. Meanwhile, the f4-pawn is pressurizing zip. }
8. Qd2
{ Perhaps a more natural way to defend b2, but this interferes with the poor b1-knight's development! The queen doesn't belong on d2, so Black is doing very well!  8.b3  This move is as sad now as it was in the early c4, and Tal Variation, not contributing to development and weakening the dark squares.  8...Nh6  In lines with the pawn on f4, I like putting the knight on h6 instead of e7 for a few reasons:   A@@EndBracket@@ It can't be captured by a bishop since the pawn blocks it.   B@@EndBracket@@ It doesn't get in the way of f8-bishop.   C@@EndBracket@@ We have the extra option of playing ...Ng4. }
8... h5
{ Not the only good move, but a good one to remember. This pawn could push further one day for attacking purposes, but it also cements the f5 outpost for one of our pieces.    Next we would like to play ...Nh6, and why not let the pawn loose ahead of the knight's development? }
9. Be2
{ 9.dxc5  We are never worried about such a capture as the trades occuring after  Bxc5  10.Bxc5  Qxc5  Only help Black to develop.    Remember, exchanges in the Advance Variation tend to favour Black as we have less space! The side with more central space tends to prefer to keep pieces on the board because they have more room on their side of the board to maneuver, while the other side feels cramped. }
9... Nh6
{ As advertised! Again, from h6 this knight could easily hop to g5 and cause devastation. }
10. O-O Be4
{ We've seen this move before, and a similar move in spirit - ...Bg4. It aims to trade itself off for the knight in order to increase pressure on d4. }
11. Ng5 Bg6
{ We aren't bothered at all by this knight hop. In fact, it plays into our hands as the knight from g5 no longer plays a role in defending the centre. Next our knight can hop to f5 and White's position is close to falling apart.   To summarize the 4. f4 variation: It's really nothing to be afraid of. Play Old Faithful at the earliest opportunity, put your pieces on normal squares, and Black is more likely to control the kingside light squares than White is to starting an attack there. }
