[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.Bd3 #1 (Most Popular)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Bd3
{ At amateur level, this is the second most popular variation because they see our active bishop, and their first instinct is to trade it off. This is super good news for us, since it's quite harmless. White doesn't even try to harass our bishop, but invites the immediate trade. In a way it's flexible, since it doesn't commit any pawns @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@, but by the same token, it's unambitious.   This may need the title, the Demchenko Variation since Anton Demchenko has played it dozens of times in online rapid and blitz tournaments such as Titled Tuesday. }
4... Bxd3
{ As in most cases when the trade of light-squared bishops is offered, we accept. }
5. Qxd3 e6
{ By this point in the chapter you should be making this move in your sleep. }
6. Nf3 c5
{ Let's take a moment to cover the most popular line seen in this 4. Bd3 variation.  Of course we stick with our tried and true ...c5. }
7. c3
{ With Bd3, White has already shown they're not in the mood for a fight, so this move shouldn't come as a great surprise. }
7... Nd7
{ This time, we will start with ...Nd7 to support c5 ahead of ...Ne7.   In the mainline we will soon see, we will be playing ...Ne7 followed by ...c5, but we probably shouldn't try it here, since White's pawn on c3 allows White to take on c5 and hold onto the pawn.  7...Ne7  8.dxc5  Nec6  9.b4  You can play this way with ...a5 next, but why bother when you have a simpler option? }
8. O-O Ne7 { We will go ...Nf5 and ...h5 next if allowed. } 9. Bg5
{ The most common move, but another one of those misguided pins, since the bishop can be kicked away immediately. }
9... h6
{ Now White actually has to watch out. If they try to maintain the pin, they'll soon regret it. }
10. Bh4
{ 10.Be3  is an improvement for White, but we can still go ...Nf5 and ...Be7 with a great game. }
10... g5 11. Bg3 Nf5 { The knight finds itself on f5 after all. } 12. Nbd2 h5
{ This time, it is White's bishop who is under fire. ...h4 next move would trap it! We would rather have our knight on c6 in this position, but White's passive bishop and our kingside space more than make up for it! And honestly, I don't see a good plan for White.   The following moves will depend on how White deals with the threat on their bishop. }
