[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Bd3
{ At amateur level, this is the second most popular variation because they see our active bishop, and their first instinct is to trade it off. This is super good news for us, since it's quite harmless. White doesn't even try to harass our bishop, but invites the immediate trade. In a way it's flexible, since it doesn't commit any pawns @@StartBracket@@for example@@EndBracket@@, but by the same token, it's unambitious.   This may need the title, the Demchenko Variation since Anton Demchenko has played it dozens of times in online rapid and blitz tournaments such as Titled Tuesday. }
4... Bxd3
{ As in most cases when the trade of light-squared bishops is offered, we accept. }
5. Qxd3 e6
{ By this point in the chapter you should be making this move in your sleep. }
6. f4 { The most common independent try from the Nf3 variation. } 6... Nh6
{ The ideas here are pretty much the same as the 4. f4 variation:    A@@EndBracket@@ Control the kingside light squares and    B@@EndBracket@@ Play an early ...c5 and direct play in the centre and on the queenside. As we learned in the 4. f4variation, when the pawn is on f4, ...Nh6 becomes more appetizing. Why not do it immediately? }
7. Nf3 c5
{ You knew what was coming. Our good friend makes another appearance. } 8. c3
{ A common and logical reaction, albeit passive. } 8... Nc6
{ If it ain't broken, don't fix it. } 9. O-O Qb6
{ The best move in the position.    You might wonder, I was told not to bring out the queen too early. Why is this queen move being recommended over and over?   Firstly, it's true you should generally prioritize piece development, but the centre is closed and in this sort of pawn structure, the queen is much less likely to become a target. Furthermore, if we compare other possible useful moves,  9...Be7  comes to mind, but perhaps we want to stay flexible for the moment with that bishop in case it needs to capture on c5. }
10. Nbd2
{ The most common move, but here the knights are stepping on each other's toes and neither one knows exactly where it wants to go in this position. Meanwhile, our knights are are soon to be both putting pressure on White's d4 point.  10.b3  b3, as always, is ill-advised for White, and we can continue by opening lines with  cxd4  11.cxd4  Nf5  when White is passive to the defense of d4 with a more difficult position. }
10... cxd4
{ We can now take the pawn because we have a good follow-up to either recapture. Luckily for us, it's the same one! }
11. Nxd4
{ 11.cxd4  White chooses to capture with the pawn and not exchanging a pair of knights.   This probably only favours Black as play will likely take place on the queenside and not the kingside, where the f3-knight remains.  Nf5  Whenever you can play ...Nf5 with tempo on the d4-pawn, it's usually the right move.  12.Nb3  The only sensible defense.  h5  A move to remember! We want to ensure we don't get hit with g4, kicking our knight away which is doing a good job of pressurizing White's centre.  13.Bd2  One flank pawn followed by the other! We are threatening to continue with ...a4 and then take on d4. }
11... Nf5
{ This time we pressurize the knight and it can't move due to the pin. } 12.
Nb3 { Defending and also preventing ...Bc5. } 12... Ncxd4
{ While we're on the subject, let me give you a word of advice about central pawn structure: You almost never want to allow a capture on f5 when you have to recapture with the pawn...  12...Be7  13.Kh1  O-O  14.Nxf5  exf5  In a position like this, Black has super weak pawns on f5 and d5. For this reason, it's usually ideal to keep a pawn on e6. Of course there are exceptions, as we saw in some of the early c4 lines for example, but this is a position we want to avoid. }
13. Nxd4
{ 13.cxd4  similar to what we've already seen, we can maintain the pressure with the strong move, h5 followed by ...a5. }
13... Bc5
{ Pressure, pressure, pressure. White has a hard time defending d4 and nothing quite seems to work. I recommend practicing this position against a friend or a computer to try to see how far your advantage can take you! In this 4. Bd3 variation, there's nothing to worry about.   Remember ...Nh6 possibility when the pawn goes to f4, and Remember not to trade too early as  13...Nxd4  14.cxd4  would let the advantage slip. }
