2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Nf3
{ White's most natural move, played on occasion by innumerable top Grandmasters. White simply develops a piece and bringing themselves one move closer to castling.  It's the mainline and you will see it in roughly a third of your games in the Advance Variation.   Here, I have a new @@StartBracket@@but thematic@@EndBracket@@ three-part idea not shown in any course that I know of which will ideally lead toequality. }
4... e6 { The routine move, setting up our favouritepawn-triangle! } 5. Be2
{ This move marks the start of the Mainline.   You won't see this nearly as often as Bd3 either on this move or the last, but I've decided to make it the mainline of this chapter anyway because it's a much better try for an advantage for White. This is because White keeps the light-squared bishops on the board and from e2, the bishop has some influence on the queenside, where we normally like to play.   5.Bd3  is the most common move, but it transposes to the 4.Bd3 / 6. Nf3move order.  Bxd3 }
5... Ne7
{ Let me tell you a secret about the Advance Variation: If you find good squares for all of yourminor pieces, you are doing great!    Often times, Black runs into issues finishing kingside development because both the knight and bishop want to sit on the e7-square. In the Mainline, the e7-knight needs a stable home so the bishop can get out.  Here's the plan:    A@@EndBracket@@ The knight first goes to e7.   B@@EndBracket@@ We break with Old Faithful.   C@@EndBracket@@ The e7-knight continues its journey to the c6-square!   Then, broadly, the b8-knight can go to d7, ...Be7, ...O-O and Voilà! All of our pieces have found a home, we've found counterplay in the centre, and our opponents will gracefully resign on move 19! @@StartBracket@@Okay, maybe not, but that would be nice, huh?@@EndBracket@@  Of course there will be exceptions depending what White does, so unfortunately you can't turn off your brain and slam down these moves willy nilly, but such is chess!  5...c5  is the main recommendation in Erwin L'Ami's Lifetime Repertoire, but I thought it was a bit too sharp to recommend to beginners. But if you're looking for a dynamic fight right out of the gate, you can look into this one. I prefer to play it a bit slower with an emphasis on harmonious piece development. }
6. Nh4
{ A logical move, going for the bishop pair since our knight on e7 now blocks the queen's vision of the h4-square. However, since this knight will have moved 3 times just to trade itself off, it doesn't bother us very much. }
6... c5
{ Phase two of our plan! If White plays slowly, we respond quickly in the centre. }
7. c3
{ Believe it or not, not only is this a passive move, this time it's actually a small mistake, allowing us to make fun of White's h4-knight. }
7... Be4
{ Let's hold onto the bishop whenever possible! Our bishop can now trade itself for the b1-knight if needed, and the white knight will owe us a tempo when we move our e7-knight. }
8. Nd2
{ White didn't like the look of  8.f3  ,  so instead they insist on being the ones to capture that wayward bishop! 8. f3 In chess sometimes mistakes come in pairs. This move blocks the h4-knight's normal retreat square!  Bxb1  We don't mind giving up the bishop on our own terms, especially now that we are winning material! We can continue normally with ...Nec6 and ...Qb6, putting typical pressure on d4. The inclusion of f3 with the knight sidelined is massively in Black's favour. }
8... cxd4
{ Let's just continue putting pressure in the centre, as if nothing is happening. In this position, we don't mind a pawn on e4 since it controls the h4-knight's natural retreat square and it's not easy at all to target. }
9. Nxe4
{ White has gone to a lot of trouble to eliminate the bishop, but unfortunately for White, it's backfiring! }
9... dxe4 10. Qxd4
{ It's necessary for White to try to trade queens in order to minimize the damage. White shouldn't consider taking with the pawn as that allows a nasty discovery against the knight...  10.cxd4  Nec6  11.g3  Nxd4  Black has won a pawn, and will very likely win the e5-pawn as well. Meanwhile, the e4-pawn is more of an attacking force than a weakness.   Black's position is overwhelming. }
10... Qxd4 11. cxd4 Nbc6
{ Even in these slightly obscure variations, notice we are still playing normal moves.  Here we don't play ...Nec6 because d5 is an even greener pasture for that knight. }
12. Be3 Nd5
{ Now White has an unpleasant choice to spend a tempo with  13.g3  saving the knight, or to castle the king  13.O-O  and avoid getting hit with ...Bb4+, but in that case the pawn structure would be ruined after  13...Be7  14.g3  Bxh4  15.gxh4  . They can't stop both. }
