[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Advance Variation "]
[Black "Advance: 4.Nf3 (Mainline) / 6.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. e5
{ The Advance Variation.  White takes the opportunity to gain a central space advantage. This is said to be the mostcritical way to play against the Caro-Kann. }
3... Bf5
{ The most reliable and the main move, developing the bishop to an active square before constructing my favourite structure in the Caro-Kann - the central pawn triangle.  There are a lot of ways to play the Advance Variation for White, so in the theory, we will go through them roughly in order of rarest to most popular on the amateur level.   3...c5  is a variation I've promoted in previous works, a favourite of esteemed British Grandmaster, Keith Arkell. It's also recommended in each other Caro-Kann course on Chessable at the time of writing this. However, these variations can be tricky to handle if White knows how to properly respond. Besides, I wanted to offer you something new! }
4. Nf3
{ White's most natural move, played on occasion by innumerable top Grandmasters. White simply develops a piece and bringing themselves one move closer to castling.  It's the mainline and you will see it in roughly a third of your games in the Advance Variation.   Here, I have a new @@StartBracket@@but thematic@@EndBracket@@ three-part idea not shown in any course that I know of which will ideally lead toequality. }
4... e6 { The routine move, setting up our favouritepawn-triangle! } 5. Be2
{ This move marks the start of the Mainline.   You won't see this nearly as often as Bd3 either on this move or the last, but I've decided to make it the mainline of this chapter anyway because it's a much better try for an advantage for White. This is because White keeps the light-squared bishops on the board and from e2, the bishop has some influence on the queenside, where we normally like to play.   5.Bd3  is the most common move, but it transposes to the 4.Bd3 / 6. Nf3move order.  Bxd3 }
5... Ne7
{ Let me tell you a secret about the Advance Variation: If you find good squares for all of yourminor pieces, you are doing great!    Oftentimes, Black runs into issues finishing kingside development because both the knight and bishop want to sit on the e7-square. In the Mainline, the e7-knight needs a stable home so the bishop can get out.  Here's the plan:    A@@EndBracket@@ The knight first goes to e7.   B@@EndBracket@@ We break with Old Faithful.   C@@EndBracket@@ The e7-knight continues its journey to the c6-square!   Then, broadly, the b8-knight can go to d7, ...Be7, ...O-O and Voilà! All of our pieces have found a home, we've found counterplay in the centre, and our opponents will gracefully resign on move 19! @@StartBracket@@Okay, maybe not, but that would be nice, huh?@@EndBracket@@  Of course there will be exceptions depending what White does, so unfortunately you can't turn off your brain and slam down these moves willy nilly, but such is chess!  5...c5  is the main recommendation in Erwin L'Ami's Lifetime Repertoire, but I thought it was a bit too sharp to recommend to beginners. But if you're looking for a dynamic fight right out of the gate, you can look into this one. I prefer to play it a bit slower with an emphasis on harmonious piece development. }
6. O-O
{ The main move. White knows they want to castle, and they're staying flexible with the rest of their pieces. }
6... c5 { Phase two of our plan! } 7. c3
{ A better version than the one where White lost a bunch of time in the Nh4 variations, but this still puts no pressure on our position. }
7... Nec6 { Phase three complete! } 8. Be3
{ White would like to activate the bishop before developing Nbd2, but this arrangement of the pieces is a little awkward and cramped for White. }
8... Nd7
{ Simply defending the pawn and developing. You can also take on d4 first - it doesn't really matter. }
9. Nbd2 Be7
{ Do note that after you play ...Nd7, you can no longer bring this knight to c6 in case that square is freed up by an exchange of knights. Therefore, once the knight is committed to d7, it's best to avoid taking on d4 unless there's a goodconcrete reason to.  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  Nxd4  11.cxd4  After this exchange, Black is okay, but you would prefer your knight on c6, not d7, so just try to remember to keep a knight on c6 to maintain pressure. }
10. Nb3
{ White is fully developed but it's not clear where their pieces should go next. This is an example of a move White could play if they're having trouble coming up with a plan. }
10... c4
{ Since White is solid in the centre, why not take the opportunity to gain queenside space? }
11. Nbd2 O-O
{ After shooing the knight away, Black has easy plans with queenside expansion and an eventual ... b5-b4 break, or simply ...f6.    Note: I have deliberately avoided positions where the ...f6 break is strictly necessary, in favor of emphasizing the power of Old Faithful, and this is no exception. It's not necessary, but you should know it's a weapon in your arsenal, especially in such cases when Black's backward e-pawn will not be too much of a liability. Here, two white pieces clog the e-file, and it's well-defended so we aren't too worried. }
