[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Classical / Two Knights Overview"]
[Result "*"]

{ Because I suggest the same way of challenging both, this chapter combines the Classical Variation with the Two Knights Variation. This will cut down the work needed for you to be able to meet both with full confidence. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4
{ 2.Nf3  d5  3.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 4.5% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@    The Two Knights Variation, a principled approach, favouring quick piece activity rather than achieving the central pawn duo right away.  The way I'm recommending to face both the Two Knights and the Classical Variation is slightly uncommon these days, but super solid and with clear and consistent developmental and middlegame schemes.    In the Two Knights, because of White's quick piece play, you need to be careful not to fall into any quick kingside attacks. But at a certain point in the middlegame, if you follow my lines, these threats will be diffused and we can start the queenside initiative we're so fond of.  3...dxe4  4.Nxe4  Nd7  This is the start of the setup I'm recommending, preparing ...Ngf6 when if White captures, we can recapture with our knight and avoid doubled pawns. This isn't the only way to play by any means, but I find it consistent, solid and reliable.  5.Bc4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 32%@@EndBracket@@   The main move, bringing out another piece and taking aim at our vulnerable f7 square. Precautions must be taken!   5.Qe2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 13%@@EndBracket@@   A tricky, but suboptimal move. White threatens smothered mate in one!  5...Ndf6  The correct knight with which to challenge White's powerful central knight.  6.Nxf6+   6.d4  allows us to develop with tempo after  6...Nxe4  7.Qxe4  Nf6  when our bishop can develop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. Whenever we can acheive this in the Two Knights Variation it normally means White is not challenging us much at all.  Nxf6  Black should have no problems here since the light-squared bishop has trouble coming out to its best square on c4. For example, in this chapter we take a look at a harmless setup where White fianchettos both bishops.  5...Ngf6  There's no immediate tactical threat, so let's develop as intended.  6.Neg5  The main move at top level from here, threatening checkmate with Bxf7#!   6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  doesn't put any pressure on Black's position, but don't play ...Bg4 in view of the Bxf7 tactic!  6...e6  This is one of those times when we need to play ...e6 with the light-squared bishop still inside the pawn chain. That's ok because once we stop White's threats and push back the knight, we can develop this bishop on the queenside. }
2... d5 3. Nc3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 7%@@EndBracket@@    The starting position of the Classical Variation. After taking the full centre, White chooses not to try anything fancy, but simply develops a piece. It's popular at most levels of competitive chess, but it's the least popular of our Big Three, probably because amateurs find it difficult or uncomfortable to maintain pawn tension. }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4
{ 4.f3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 5%@@EndBracket@@   A Gambit related to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit that is unique to the Classical as a pawn sits on f3 instead of a knight.  White is offering a pawn in exchange for rapid development and a half-open f-file.  4...exf3  I think we can both accept the Gambit and stay up a pawn while taking most of the sting out of White's chances.  5.Nxf3  Bg4  Pinning the knight right away. We put our bishop here in all other variations when possible and here is no exception. }
4... Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! I'm recommending this to you as perhaps the most solid way to meet the Classical Variation. After all, we play the Caro-Kann to be solid in the first place. :@@EndBracket@@  The idea is to support our other knight developing to f6 when if White takes it, we can recapture with the d7-knight, salvaging our pawn structure.   4...Bf5  I recommended this variation in my past works and I still find it a reliable weapon, developing the bishop outside the pawn chain with a tempo on White's central knight.  5.Ng3  Bg6  For my first Chessable course, I wanted to look into a new variation, and who better to emulate than the one and only, Anatoly Karpov? }
5. Nf3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 55%@@EndBracket@@   5.Bc4  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 11%@@EndBracket@@   The most aggressive square for the bishop, eyeing f7. On your toes!  5...Ngf6  6.Ng5  Threatening mate in 1 with Bxf7#!  6...e6  7.Qe2  White comes in with a new threat - Nxf7 Kxf7 Qxe6, with a mating attack.  7...Nb6  Defending against the threat by allowing the bishop to guard e6. Next we will kick out the intruder on g5 with ...h6 and quickly break with ...c5 when White's initiative is over.   5.Qe2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 8%@@EndBracket@@   A common move only because the threat of smothered mate is irresistible. Don't go ...Ngf6 and allow Nd6#!  5...Ndf6  After displacing or trading the e4 pony, our position quickly unravels and the white queen is misplaced as it sits in the way of White's light-squared bishop.   5.Ng5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 2%@@EndBracket@@   An exceedingly rare move at lower levels as there's no immediate threat and moves the same piece twice in a row, but a popular move at top level in the 90s/early 2000s, including by World Champion, Garry Kasparov. The idea is usually to employ a more reserved piece configuration and castle queenside.  5...Ngf6  When there's no threat, we continue with our intended setup.  6.Bd3  An unassuming, but tricky move, eyeing the kingside light-squares when there are sometimes tactics if Black pushes ...h6 too soon.  6...e6  After developing our dark-squared bishop, we will kick out the knight, then develop the light-squared bishop on b7. If White castles long, it's usually best to do the same. }
5... Ngf6
{ Knights before bishops!  Our piece setup and strategy will depend on White's next moves. One way or the other, the e4-knight will be traded or displaced and we can continue developing our pieces, usually with an aim towards the ...c5 break, trading off White's central pawn.    My Five Lifelines:   A@@EndBracket@@ Know your piece setup depending on what White plays. For example, where the light-squared bishop belongs @@StartBracket@@ g4, f5, b7, or even e6!@@EndBracket@@   B@@EndBracket@@ Tactics against f7/e6!!! This chapter is by far the most tricky - like navigating a jungle. But as long as you know all of the tactics White has at their disposal, you'll know how to dodge them and emerge with a fantastic position. Don't get smothered mated by Nd6#! ;@@EndBracket@@   C@@EndBracket@@ Often times we can set up a queen-bishop battery with ...Bd6 and ...Qc7 even if it allows Bxf6, doubling our pawns. Don't feel as if the pin is eternal!   D@@EndBracket@@ Old Faithful is there for you in this chapter. It's an important move in order to start some counterplay and activate your pieces.   E@@EndBracket@@ In this chapter, White has a list of 'assets' and our primary goal is to neutralize them! These include a strong pawn on d4, and a strong knight on e4, and later e5 or even g5, and sometimes a bloodthirsty bishop on c4. You can view many of the moves we play as attempts to confront and neutralize them. }
