[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Two Knights: 5.Qe2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3
{ The starting position of the aptly named Two Knights Variation.   Here, White opts to develop the knights first thing, instead of taking the full centre. It's a serious try, which can sometimes transpose to the Classical Variation if White decides to later play d4. That's why I'm putting them together in the same chapter.   3.exd5  cxd5  is atransposition to the early Nf3line in the Exchange Variation. }
3... dxe4
{ In order to reduce your workload, I want to play the same way we do against the Classical Variation and take off this pawn.   3...Bg4  is the old mainline.  4.h3  Bxf3  5.Qxf3  e6  This is a completely reasonable way to play as well, but my suggestion is more consistent with how we play against the Classical Variation. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Preparing ...Ngf6 when we would recapture on f6 with the knight in order to avoid doubled pawns.   Compared to the Classical Variation in which I also recommend this move, it's the same position, only with a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on d4. Because of White's extra developed piece, there are a couple of tactical opportunities White may have that we need to be aware of. }
5. Qe2
{ The least commonly played at amateur level, since it blocks the light-squared bishops way into the game. But this tricky move already creates a mate in one threat, so we definitely need to stay on our toes. }
5... Ndf6
{ We want to trade off, or at least displace White's strong e4-knight ASAP.   Remember to use this knight, otherwise White's response might give you nightmares.  5...Ngf6  6.Nd6#  Oops! The e-pawn is pinned to the king, who has nowhere to run. Let's take care that this kind of smothered mate exists only in White's fantasies. }
6. Nxf6+
{ An exchange we are quite happy to see, as it helps us develop a new piece! }
6... Nxf6
{ The Two Knights and Classical Variations are no exception to the general rule that piece trades usually help our position. }
7. g3
{ Not a very ambitious setup for White since the light-squared bishop isn't as happy on the long diagonal as it would be on c4. For this reason, we are less worried about a kingside attack here. }
7... Bg4 { The best square for the bishop outside of the pawn chain. } 8. Bg2
e6 9. O-O Bd6
{ The most natural square for the bishop, as usual, exerting control over the important e5-square and preventing any future Bf4 ideas from White. }
10. b3
{ A very rare double fianchetto setup. White has no central pawn presence but instead opts to develop the pieces from afar and wait to see how play develops before initiating any action. The problem is neither white bishop has any real targets. }
10... O-O 11. Bb2 a5
{ A thematic response to the queenside fianchetto structure which gives the a8-rook some breathing room. We intend to keep pushing that pawn if allowed to open the a-file for the rook. }
12. a4
{ Probably not White's best response, but perhaps the one you would see most commonly - stopping our a-pawn in its tracks. }
12... Re8
{ I already prefer Black's position. Here we threaten to push the e-pawn up the board. }
13. d4
{ Once again, likely not best but if White never takes the centre with a pawn, what are they doing? }
13... Qc7
{ Black has many easy improving moves including ...Rad8, ...Bh5 @@StartBracket@@a safer square for the bishop@@EndBracket@@, ...Bf8 and one day likely breaking with ...e5. }
