1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Nf3 d5 3. Nc3
{ The starting position of the aptly named Two Knights Variation.   Here, White opts to develop the knights first thing, instead of taking the full centre. It's a serious try, which can sometimes transpose to the Classical Variation if White decides to later play d4. That's why I'm putting them together in the same chapter.   3.exd5  cxd5  is atransposition to the early Nf3line in the Exchange Variation. }
3... dxe4
{ In order to reduce your workload, I want to play the same way we do against the Classical Variation and take off this pawn.   3...Bg4  is the old mainline.  4.h3  Bxf3  5.Qxf3  e6  This is a completely reasonable way to play as well, but my suggestion is more consistent with how we play against the Classical Variation. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ Preparing ...Ngf6 when we would recapture on f6 with the knight in order to avoid doubled pawns.   Compared to the Classical Variation in which I also recommend this move, it's the same position, only with a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on d4. Because of White's extra developed piece, there are a couple of tactical opportunities White may have that we need to be aware of. }
5. Bc4
{ The most common move, and consistent with White's plan of early piece development. From here, the bishop stares menacingly at our vulnerable f7-pawn, so already we need to start taking care to avoid any devious sacrifices.   5.d4  transposes to the 5. Nf3line of the Classical Variation.  Ngf6 }
5... Ngf6
{ There's no immediate tactical threat, so we can challenge White's powerful central knight by developing a new piece. }
6. Neg5
{ By far, the main move at top level, dodging the trade and immediately going after the vulnerable f7-point. }
6... e6
{ A necessary defense - erecting the pillars of strength on e6 and c6.  We don't mind our Caro-Kann c8-bishop living inside the pawn chain for now. In these lines, it will find a new path into the game. But for now, we need to defend against White's threats. }
7. Qe2
{ White is employing a harmonious attacking setup. All of White's pieces are aggressively postured towards our centre. So it's extra important to play the right moves to avoid getting in trouble. }
7... Nd5
{ Even though we move a developed piece again, this is a nice defensive move in order to block all potential tactics on the a2-g8 diagonal.   The desirable  7...Be7  would work if we had one more move to castle, but as it stands,  8.Nxf7  Kxf7  9.Qxe6+  is leading to mate.  Kg6   @@StartBracket@@Of course,  9...Ke8  would allow Mate in one with  10.Qf7  .@@EndBracket@@  10.Bd3+  Kh6  11.Qe3+  Kh5  12.Qg5#  This is exactly the kind of thing White is hoping for in this variation.   Let's not indulge them! }
8. d4 h6
{ We'd rather not have this knight breathing down our neck all game, so let's send it packing. }
9. Ne4 Be7
{ Now, and only now, we can resume our kingside development. This is one of the rare times the bishop goes to e7, since the knight is still covering the d6-square. }
10. O-O O-O
{ We have successfully avoided any kingside tragedies, but because White is better developed, we still need to take care. If given another move, we would play ...b6 or maybe even ...b5 and fianchetto our light-squared bishop, preparing ...c5.   Let's have a look at a couple of White's options from here just to cover our bases. }
11. Ne5
{ This is an aggressive looking move, but sort of plays into our hands since ...c5, which we want to play anyway, will now undermine the knight's position on e5. }
11... Qc7
{ The best square for the queen, both eyeing the e5-knight and preparing ...c5. }
12. f4
{ A consistent move, supporting the knight in view of our looming ...c5. }
12... b5 { I like this move, which steers play to the queenside. } 13. Bd3 c5
{ It may seem strange not to play @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/ppqnbpp1/2p1p2p/3nN3/2BPNP2/8/PPP1Q1PP/R1B2RK1 b - f3 0 12@@EndFEN@@  12...c5  immediately, but this way, we threaten to trap the bishop with ...c4, forcing White to respond somehow.   Fortunately for us, all of White's responses play into our hands, including capturing on b5. }
14. Bxb5 cxd4
{ We have exchanged our b-pawn for White's important d-pawn. Black is even better now and it's suddenly White's queenside bishop that will have problems entering the game. }
