11. Bd3
{ Since Black has sufficiently cluttered the bishop's favourite diagonal, White thinks it best to reposition it and potentially prepare a c4 advance, gaining more space.  11.c3  would likely be the most common continuation at amateur level, but after  c5  Black has enough time to follow up with ...b6 and ...Bb7, solving the problem of the bishop and we are doing great. }
11... Nb4
{ If White had one more move to spare, a3 would be a good one in order not to allow this exchange. But they're too late. Remember, harassing and exchanging White's bishops is a key strategy many variations of the Caro-Kann, and no exception here. }
12. Rd1
{ I have extreme doubts you will ever see this position, especially as this is a very rare move, but it's the correct way to play, centralising the rook and not wasting time saving the bishop.   12.Bc4  White could also choose to repeat moves rather than giving up their precious bishop, but this will allow us to create some kind of queenside initiative.  b5  13.Bb3  a5  Trying to trap the bishop with ...a4 and if White prevents it with  14.a4  we have  Ba6  placing the bishop on quite a dangerous diagonal for White. We can always retreat the knight to d5 when needed. }
12... Qc7
{ Now we can develop a piece and prevent White's dark-squared bishop from making use of its most active square. }
13. Ne5 f5
{ I love this move, activating the f8-rook, gaining some space, and displacing one of White's strong central knights before capturing the knight on e5. }
14. Ng3 Nxe5
{ Now we definitely want to take the knight as Ng6 would be awkward for us to meet. }
15. Bf4
{ White could choose to develop a piece with a pin on the queen before recapturing. No biggie. }
15... Bd6
{ Instead of panicking and moving the queen away, it's better to break the pin this way, encouraging more piece trades in case White captures with the bishop. }
16. dxe5 Be7
{ White didn't want to trade bishops, but now the centre is locked, our king is safe, and we can take the d3-bishop at any moment and bring our light-squared bishop into the game via d7-e8, covering some kingside light-squares.   White may have a slight pull because of our bad bishop, but it's the type of 3-result game @@StartBracket@@when the game could plausibly end in a win for either side, or a draw@@EndBracket@@ I really enjoy with plenty of chances to outplay your opponent from a super-imbalanced position. }
