{ Remember, it's ok to defend these early f7 attacks with ...e6, after which the light-squared bishop will find another way into the game.   Here, White can either castle, or choose a different move. The way we continue will depend which White chooses. }
8. d4 Bd6 { Castling as quickly as possible. } 9. O-O O-O 10. Bg5 Qc7
{ I wanted to show at least one variation where you can simply move out of the pin and allow your pawns to be doubled. }
11. Bxf6 gxf6
{ Here, since the knight is operating alone and there have been multiple exchanges, there's nothing to worry about. }
12. Ng4 f5 { Defending the f6-pawn by moving it ahead one square. } 13. Nf6+
Kg7 14. Nh5+ Kh8
{ Our sideways pawn triangle is actually very solid and we're quite happy with the bishop pair and half-opn g-file to work with!   I think White needs to play some good moves not to get in a lot of trouble once a rook and bishop work together to target White's g2-square. }
