{ Preparing ...Ngf6 when we would recapture on f6 with the knight in order to avoid doubled pawns.   Compared to the Classical Variation in which I also recommend this move, it's the same position, only with a knight on f3 instead of a pawn on d4. Because of White's extra developed piece, there are a couple of tactical opportunities White may have that we need to be aware of. }
5. Bc4
{ The most common move, and consistent with White's plan of early piece development. From here, the bishop stares menacingly at our vulnerable f7-pawn, so already we need to start taking care to avoid any devious sacrifices.   5.d4  transposes to the 5. Nf3line of the Classical Variation.  Ngf6 }
5... Ngf6
{ There's no immediate tactical threat, so we can challenge White's powerful central knight by developing a new piece. }
6. Nxf6+
{ The most common move at amateur level, but not the most critical. Gotta love when that happens! }
6... Nxf6 7. Ne5
{ A natural attacking move, threatening mate in one with Bxf7! } 7... e6
{ Remember, it's ok to defend these early f7 attacks with ...e6, after which the light-squared bishop will find another way into the game.   Here, White can either castle, or choose a different move. The way we continue will depend which White chooses. }
8. O-O b5
{ Here I like developing our light-squared bishop as quickly as possible. Additionally, we are able to make the bishop find a new home before White has the chance to play Re1, creating the ideal f1 retreat square. }
9. Bb3 Bb7
{ After a future ...c5, this bishop may be the strongest piece on the board - a far cry from just a few moves ago! }
10. Qe2 { Red alert!   White has a threat! } 10... Qc7
{ We would like to play ...Bd6,  but it's necessary to first protect f7 to extinguish White's threat.  10...Bd6  11.Nxf7  Kxf7  12.Qxe6+  is a version of the same sacrifice we've seen before, and is exactly what we want to avoid. Black's king is getting ushered out into the open and will be unceremoniously checkmated. }
11. d4 Bd6
{ The bishop comes out to its best square with pressure on the e5-knight. } 12.
Bf4 { A natural move, supporting the e5-square. } 12... O-O 13. c3 a6
{ A nice little move to remember in positions like this when we have time, protecting the b5-pawn before launching ahead with Old Faithful. }
14. Rfe1 c5
{ SPARRING POSITION  Take a mental snapshot because this is a very thematic type of position to expect from this opening. We are safe from any kingside attacks for now and our next moves can be to bring the rooks to the centre, post our knight on d5, or even push ahead with ...c4 and aim for the ...a5 / ...b4 break.    I recommend sparring from here to see which plan suits you the best. Some concluding words about the Two Knights Variation: Because White's strategy involves quick piece activity, you need to watch out for tactics, usually involving the f7-square. Check for tactics every move. Eventually, once the coast is clear, you can drum up your own queenside play with either ...c5 or ...b5, depending on the circumstances. }
