[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "🤺🧨 Classical: 4.f3 (Gambit) #1 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason.   White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. f3
{ White offers a pawn in exchange for rapid development. It's highly related to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit which occurs after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  d5  2.e4  dxe4  3.f3  .   While it's rare at amateur level, I've definitely seen it before as gambits like this have quite a cult following. }
4... exf3
{ However, I don't buy it. We can treat it the same way a grandmaster would, accepting thegambit. It would be rude to turn down a free pawn as early as move 4, right? }
5. Nxf3 Bg4
{ I think pinning the knight immediately is conveniently both the objectively best treatment of this line as well as the easiest to understand. }
6. h3
{ I'm marking this a dynamite variation because it's important to remember to take the knight and because in my opinion, it's more difficult to meet than any other continuation. }
6... Bxf3
{ The best, snapping off the defender of the d4-pawn and losing no time for development! Similar to a variation we saw in the Exchange Variation, trying to maintain the pin can sometimes get us into trouble.  6...Bh5  7.g4  Bg6  8.h4  Black is already already busted under the weight of White's initiative. Let's see a few more moves to drive the point home:  h6  Other options are equally bad, but the point is Black is losing time in development just to save the bishop.  9.Ne5  Bh7  10.Bc4  e6  11.Qe2  You may recognize the tactical threat of Nxf7 from the Two Knights lines. On top of that, Black is woefully behind in development. }
7. Qxf3
{ Giving up the d-pawn but continuing to develop quickly. Recapturing with the pawn  7.gxf3  doesn't bother us in the slightest.  e6  8.Be3  Be7  Black is threatening to give an inconvenient check with ...Bh4. Furthermore, playing this way puts no pressure on us since White's development advantage has evaporated, and their kingside pawn structure is terrible. }
7... Qxd4
{ Yes, we've won a second pawn, but we need to be careful since our queen is the only developed piece. }
8. Be3 Qh4+
{ Before offering a queen exchange I like giving this check in order to provoke g3, when after the queen is deprived of this nice square.   8...Qf6  right away makes sense, but it turns out  9.Qg3  is a great square for the queen from where it's very difficult to trade off. For example after  Qg6  10.Qc7  White has dual threats of Qxb7 and Qc8#. }
9. g3 Qf6
{ SPARRING POSITION   White still has plenty of compensation for the two pawns, so some care going forward is required. We would very much like to trade queens because simplifications favour the side ahead material. I've marked this a sparring position so you can gain experience handling positions with this specific kind of material for initiative imbalance. }
10. Qe2
{ One of the more likely moves you'd see, respectfully declining the queen exchange. }
10... Nd7 11. O-O-O Qe5
{ We are a little bit in the weeds here and I can almost guarantee you will never see this position, but nonetheless it's instructive to know how to handle it.    This move makes way for ...Ngf6 and encourages a queen exchange if the bishop ever moves. Our next priority is castling kingside as fast as possible! }
