[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "🧨 Classical: 5.Ng5 #1 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason. White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece. Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering or attempting to counter the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights,  we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4
{ White offers a pawn in exchange for rapid development. It's highly related to the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit which occurs after d4   4.d5  e4 dxe4 f3 . While it's rare at amateur level, I've definitely seen it before as gambits like this have quite a cult following. }
4... Nd7 5. Ng5
{ White is moving the knight further into our position, nibbling at our tender f7-square before it's even attacked, but is not developing a new piece. }
5... Ngf6
{ As a rule, the best way to punish your opponent's lack of development is... more development!   5...h6  is tempting but unfortunately White has the cunning  6.Ne6  when taking is impossible in view of  6...fxe6  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qxg6# }
6. Bd3
{ This was a very topical setup among top players in the 90s and early 2000s including World Champions, Garry Kasparov and Viswanathan Anand, as well as Top English player, Michael Adams. The idea is to employ a more modest piece configuration and castle long. In itself, Bd3 is a seemingly nonchalant developing move, but there's a trap. }
6... e6
{ I know it's tempting, but don't touch the h-pawn please!   6...h6  7.Ne6  Oh my.   7...fxe6  8.Bg6  Checkmate on move 8! Let this be a cautionary tale for weakening your kingside light-squares too soon!  7...Qb6  keeps the game going but after  8.Nxf8  White has the bishop pair and we are way out of our comfort zone. }
7. N1f3 Bd6
{ The best square for the bishop! In this chapter, as well as in the Exchange Variation chapter, we need a good reason not to put the bishop here. However, for the moment, this bishop is unprotected and there is a tactic to watch out for. }
8. Qe2 h6
{ Now that our kingside is developed, it's time to kick out the intruder on g5. Provoking this move is one of the key ideas behind putting the knight on g5. Either we have to live with a knight there, or slightly weaken our kingside with h6 when castling short will be super risky. Therefore, in this line, we have other plans for the king.  After the natural   8...O-O  White can crash through on the light-squares from the other direction!  9.Nxe6  fxe6  10.Qxe6+  White is forking the king and bishop, regaining the piece.  10...Kh8  11.Qxd6  White emerges ahead two pawns with a completely winning position. }
9. Ne4
{ 9.Nxe6  this time isn't working. After  9...fxe6  10.Qxe6+  the difference is we can defend our d6-bishop with  10...Qe7  and Black would be ahead a piece for two pawns with a big advantage. }
9... Nxe4
{ We kicked the intruder out of our house and now we can kick it off the board! }
10. Qxe4 Nf6
{ 10...Qc7  is also viable, keeping the knight on d7 and preparing ...b6 and ...Bb7, but I like keeping a knight on f6 because the resulting positions are easier to handle. We chase the queen back and one day the knight can make use of the d5-square. }
11. Qh4
{ This is a more aggressive move, keeping the queen in the area of the kingside. The point that it makes it hard for us to castle. }
11... Rg8
{ The important thing to remember is not to castle short with the queen in our neighborhood.  So if we´re not castling short, we might as well expand there, which explains ...Rg8. Believe it or not, White only has one move not to be worse, and your amateur opponents will not be playing it.   11...O-O  falls into White's trap:  12.Bxh6  gxh6  13.Qxh6  when White's mating attack is impossible to parry without losing material. For example, g4-g5 is a big threat as well as the slow plan of Ng5, castling, and swinging a rook to h3. }
12. Nd2
{ If White knew they had to make such a retreating move in order to avoid material loss, they wouldn't have gone for Qh4 in the first place. This move avoids the g5-g4 fork idea when the knight is on a safe square.   12.O-O  This falls into our trap.  12...g5  13.Qxh6  Bf8  This time, we're not only winning the d-pawn, but a full piece.  14.Qh3  The only remaining safe square.  14...g4   Another pitfall for White is  12.Ne5  after which  Bxe5  13.dxe5  Qa5+  14.Bd2  Qxe5+  wins a central pawn, though White has some compensation. }
12... g5 { Even if White avoids the trap, we still push ahead. } 13. Qxh6 Bf8
{ Here's the point behind giving up the h-pawn. Our king doesn't belong on the kingside anyway, so we are happy trading our flank pawn for White's central pawn. }
14. Qh3 Qxd4
{ It's a dynamically balanced position where we will likely castle queenside after some preparatory moves, ...Be7, ...g5 and fianchettoing the light-squared bishop. }
