3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov. He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  .   Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Ng5
{ White is moving the knight further into our position, nibbling at our tender f7-square before it's even attacked, but is not developing a new piece. }
5... Ngf6
{ As a rule, the best way to punish your opponent's lack of development is... more development!   5...h6  is tempting but unfortunately White has the cunning  6.Ne6  when taking is impossible in view of  6...fxe6  7.Qh5+  g6  8.Qxg6# }
6. Bd3
{ This was a very topical setup among top players in the 90s and early 2000s including World Champions, Garry Kasparov and Viswanathan Anand, as well as Top English player, Michael Adams. The idea is to employ a more modest piece configuration and castle long.    In itself, Bd3 is a seemingly nonchalant developing move, but there's a trap.   6.Bc4  e6  would transpose to the 5. Bc4move-order. }
6... e6
{ I know it's tempting, but don't touch the h-pawn please!   6...h6  7.Ne6  Oh my.   7...fxe6  8.Bg6  Checkmate on move 8! Let this be a cautionary tale for weakening your kingside light-squares too soon!  7...Qb6  keeps the game going but after  8.Nxf8  White has the bishop pair and we are way out of our comfort zone. }
7. N1f3 Bd6
{ The best square for the bishop! In this chapter, as well as in the Exchange Variation chapter, we need a good reason not to put the bishop here. However, for the moment, this bishop is unprotected and there is a tactic to watch out for. }
8. Qe2 h6
{ Now that our kingside is developed, it's time to kick out the intruder on g5.  Provoking this move is one of the key ideas behind putting the knight on g5. Either we have to live with a knight there, or slightly weaken our kingside with h6 when castling short will be super risky. Therefore, in this line, we have other plans for the king.   After the natural  8...O-O  White can crash through on the light-squares from the other direction!  9.Nxe6  fxe6  10.Qxe6+  White is forking the king and bishop, regaining the piece.  Kh8  11.Qxd6  White emerges ahead two pawns with a completely winning position. }
9. Ne4
{ 9.Nxe6  this time isn't working. After  fxe6  10.Qxe6+  the difference is we can defend our d6-bishop with  Qe7  and Black would be ahead a piece for two pawns with a big advantage. }
9... Nxe4
{ We kicked the intruder out of our house and now we can kick it off the board! }
10. Qxe4 Nf6
{ 10...Qc7  is also viable, keeping the knight on d7 and preparing ...b6 and ...Bb7, but I like keeping a knight on f6 because the resulting positions are easier to handle.  We chase the queen back and one day the knight can make use of the d5-square. }
11. Qe2 Qc7
{ The best square for the queen.  It may be tempting to castle, but then White would quickly castle the other direction and start to attack us by bringing the rooks to the kingside and pushing g4-g5, opening lines against our king. This is far too risky.    In this variation, only castle short if White does the same. }
12. Bd2 { This move makes White's intentions crystal clear. } 12... b6 13.
O-O-O Bb7
{ On a good day once ...c5 has played, this bishop will not only be a great piece along the long diagonal, but act as a defender for our king. }
14. Kb1
{ A standard move when castling queenside to protect the a-pawn and bringing the king to a safer square in case White wants to push the c-pawn. }
14... O-O-O
{ White may be slightly better here, but the position is so rich with dynamic potential that I don't think it matters, even at the master level.    Next, we should tuck our king to safety on b8 and deploy Old Faithful at the right moment. We can also prepare it by doubling rooks on the d-file. I will re-iterate that you will likely never face this variation with an early Ng5 and queenside castling, but at least now you know to avoid castling in opposite directions if possible. }
