[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Classical: 5.Qe2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason.   White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov. He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  .   Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Qe2
{ We have another dynamite variation because White has the immediate threat of smothered mate in one move! }
5... Ndf6
{ It's important to remember to use this knight, giving our king some breathing room on d7. After 5... Ngf6  6. Nd6# the e-pawn is pinned and cannot capture the knight. Don't let this happen to you! }
6. c3
{ This is the most commonly played move at master level, not committing with Nf3 and allowing our favourite ...Bg4 pin.   But we don't need an invitation from an f3-knight to employ this setup.  6.Nxf6+  Nxf6  7.Nf3  Bg4  An awkward pin for White to meet, also threatening to take and either ruin White's pawn structure or win the d-pawn!  8.c3  If White defends the pawn,  Qd5  asks the question, 'How are you going to develop your light-squared bishop and castle?!' g3 isn't possible because we have too much pressure on f3, and for now, the queen is misplaced. White can't avoid an eventual capture on f3 and doubled pawns.   Black is better. }
6... Nxe4 { We take this knight whenever we can. } 7. Qxe4 Nf6 8. Qc2 Bg4
{ This is a better version for White since the knight is better off at home for now, but there's still nothing wrong with us playing this way. }
9. Bd3
{ Waiting with the knight has allowed White to be more active with this bishop, and now the knight belongs on e2. But it's still unclear how White will put pressure on our position. }
9... e6 10. Ne2 Bd6 { The most active square! } 11. O-O Qc7
{ This move sets up a thematic battery between the queen and bishop, threatening the h2-pawn and asking White the question, 'How will you defend it?'. }
12. Ng3
{ Blocking the threat on h2 and attempting to strand our g4-bishop in some lines. In addition to slightly weakening the kingside,  12.h3  only helps us towards our mission of exchanging the light-squared bishops with  ...Bh5  and next ...Bg6. }
12... h5
{ I love this move - immediately threatening to push further, kicking the knight away so we can take on h2. Black seems to have a small initiative and easier play at most levels. If White does nothing, we can even consider castling queenside and throwing everything at the white king!   After the tempting  13.h3  though, we can , and should, shut down the game with style with  Bxh3  demolishing the king's shelter.  14.gxh3  Bxg3  15.fxg3  Qxg3+  16.Kh1  Qxh3+  17.Kg1  Qg3+  with a repetition going back and forth between g3 and h3. }
*

