[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "🧨 Classical: 5.Bc4 #1 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason.   White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov. He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  .   Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Bc4
{ Probably the most dangerous move, developing a piece and taking aim at f7.   Remember, with a bishop on c4, your tactical senses should be on high alert. }
5... Ngf6
{ There's no immediate threat, so we continue our development as intended, challenging the steed on e4. }
6. Ng5
{ This line shares a lot of similarities with itscounterpart in the Two Knights Variation featuring the c4-bishop, g5-knight, and likely the e2-queen.   White is putting their pieces in the most aggressive squares, targeting our kingside light squares. Checkmate in 1 is already a threat, for heaven's sake! As long as we're vigilant, just like before, we will kick out the g5-intruder and carry on with our day. }
6... e6
{ When White plays this way, we need to play ... e6 earlier than usual, with the bishop at home on c8.   Later, after securing the kingside, we will expand on the queenside and our bishop will find life along a different diagonal. }
7. Qe2
{ The only consistent move, piling up on e6.   Red Alert! Nxf7 followed by Qxe6 is a threat. We've seen it before, so I hope you're starting to recognize it instinctively!   7.N1f3  This is a common move at lower levels, but is a mistake since it takes away the g5-knight's best retreat square!  h6  8.Nh3  g5  The knight that started the game on b1, on move 8, is already all the way over on h3, tangled up with the other knight.   We are threatening a fork after ...g4 in view of which White will continue to lose time finding new homes for the knights. }
7... Nb6
{ Remember this move! The knight attacks the bishop and at the same time, reveals our c8-bishop's defense of the e-pawn.  If you remember everything to this point, you're pretty much home-free and ready to kick out the knight and finish developing.   7...h6  DON'T DO IT!  8.Nxf7  Kxf7  9.Qxe6+  Kg6  10.Bd3+  Kh5  11.Qh3#  We've seen this mate before, highlighting the potency of White's attacking setup.   7...Be7  DON'T DO IT!  8.Nxf7  leads to the same exact checkmate. }
8. Bd3
{ 8.Bb3  I would argue the bishop really doesn't belong on the a2-g8 diagonal anymore. We can play the exact same way as if the bishop had gone back to d3...  h6  With the light-squares under lock and key, we can kick out the intruder, just as before.  9.N5f3  c5  Black is very comfortable and will continue with ...Qc7 @@StartBracket@@threatening ...c4@@EndBracket@@, ...Be7, . ..O-O and then we can determine how to involve our light-squared bishop.    We have 3 ways to do this:   A@@EndBracket@@ ...Bd7-c6   B@@EndBracket@@ ...b6 and ... Bb7   C@@EndBracket@@ ...e5, opening the h3-c8 diagonal.  In themodel game Shabalov - Karpov, Karpov demonstrated absolute middlegame expertise by using the d5-square as a pivot point for several different pieces, eventually achieving ...Bd5, trading off the light-squared bishops, and later by a knight.   You won't want to miss that game! }
8... h6
{ With the bishop no longer staring down at our king, we can kick out the intruder.   8...Qxd4  isn't as free as it might look. Here's a sample line:  9.N1f3  Qc5  an attempt to stay active with the queen.  10.Ne5  and the f7-pawn is doomed, which is much more important for our king safety than White's d-pawn. A bad trade for us. }
9. N5f3
{ 9.Ne4  would be nice, but unfortunately for White,  Qxd4  picks up a free pawn. }
9... c5
{ I like unleashing Old Faithful early in this line, giving White a chance to capture and help us develop our bishop. Additionally, since White has difficulty castling short here, opening the c-file will give us good counterplay against the queenside-castled king.  White likes to put a knight on e5 and keep it there as long as possible. Your task is to trade it off if possible with a move like ...Nbd7. If we can achieve amajor piece endgame, we will be very happy!   We will analyse amodel game that continues from here played by none other than Karpov himself! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Shabalov, Alexander vs. Karpov, Anatoly, Tilburg, 1994"]
[Result "*"]

{ In this game, it's the many-time US Champion, Alexander Shabalov with the White pieces against World Champion Anatoly Karpov himself! Karpov played dozens and dozens of games in this setup with extremely solid results. By that I mean the vast majority of games ended in a draw.  Generally, Karpov was happy to acheive a draw with the Black pieces as a tournament strategy and he was a tough nut to crack with his pet system. However, this game is a cool example of the queenside counterplay we can get.    There are a few things to pay attention to as we go through this game:   A@@EndBracket@@ Karpov understands very well the correct order of operations in the opening - evacuating the intruder and striking with ...c5.   B@@EndBracket@@ After development is basically finished, the next phase is harassing White's active pieces - namely the bishops, including exchanging the light-squared bishops.    C@@EndBracket@@ Karpov masterfully uses the d5 square as a pivot point for activating his pieces.  As a side-note, I was blown away how accurately Karpov played this game. Some people think of him as a boring positional player, but the way in which he outplayed Shabalov in a dynamic, opposite-side castling position is evidence to the contrary.    Enjoy! }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ The Classical Variation follows classical principles - taking the centre and developing pieces! }
3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 { The Karpov Variation. } 5. Bc4 Ngf6 6. Ng5
{ Shabalov is a fearsome attacking player, and true to his brand, he's going for one of the most aggressive setups. }
6... e6 { 6...h6  would blunder  7.Bxf7 } 7. Qe2
{ White has the threat of Nxf7 followed by Qxe6 with a mating attack. } 7...
Nb6
{ The move to remember!  The bishop watches over e6 and we gain a tempo on the bishop.   7...Be7  is played in about 1 out of every 5 games online at amateur level, overlooking White's threat.  8.Nxf7  Kxf7  9.Qxe6+  Kg6  Black's king is flushed out and will not survive.  10.Bd3+  Kh5  11.Qh3  Don't fall for it! }
8. Bb3 h6
{ Now that the coast is clear on the light-squares, Karpov sends the knight on its way. }
9. N5f3 c5
{ The move I'm recommending in the theory section - immediately deploying Old Faithful. So nice of Karpov to help promote my course. ;@@EndBracket@@ }
10. Bf4
{ The main move, developing the bishop to an active square. But as is so often the case, this gives us a chance to chase it! }
10... Nbd5 11. Be5 Qa5+
{ It may look strange that Karpov is making moves that don't bring him closer to castling, but he has the time because White is also several moves from castling himself.  This move prepares the ...b5 advance, threatening ...c4 trapping the bishop and fianchettoing our light-squared bishop. }
12. Nd2 b5 13. dxc5 Bxc5
{ The point behind the early ...c5 is revealed - Karpov has saved a tempo by waiting to develop the bishop. Here, it comes into the game in one move. }
14. O-O-O
{ Maybe the first inaccuracy, which Karpov expertly exploits from here until the end of the game.   14.Ngf3  is the main theoretical move, simply finishing development and castling kingside.  14...O-O  15.O-O  Ba6  Black is fine here with active squares for every piece. But this is not Shabalov's style. }
14... Bb7 15. Ne4 Be7
{ When I first saw this move, it took me by surprise because it involves giving up the dark-squared bishop for White's knight.  Karpov's understanding of the resulting position is truly next-level.   15...Nxe4  16.Qxe4  Qb4  is another good way to play, and perhaps more natural, not parting with the bishop pair. }
16. Nd6+ Bxd6 17. Bxd6 Rd8 18. Be5 O-O
{ Now that both sides have castled, let's take stock of the position.  White has the bishop pair, but how good are White's bishops? While they are active, I would argue they are not so dangerous since our knights are working very well together and we have great control of the d5-square.    Pay attention to the d5-square going forward as much of Karpov's strategy involves using this square to maneuver. Since the kings are on opposite sides of the board, we need to ask the question, whose king is safer?. It's hard to say, but I like Black's chances because although we have ahook on h6, White's g4-g5 advance will take time to arrange. Meanwhile, Black can gather more forces on the queenside like a stormcloud.    I would certainly take Black here! }
19. Nf3 Nd7 { Harass those bishops! } 20. Bd6
{ Karpov was hoping for  20.Bg3  which would misplace the bishop and allow  20...Nc5  trading off a key defender of the white kingside. }
20... Rfe8 21. Nd4 a6 { Simply defending the b-pawn. } 22. Qf3 Qb6 23. Qg3 Rc8
{ Both sides have a major piece staring down a file at the enemy king, but Black's attack is clearly stronger at this point since the white queen has no companions. }
24. Rhe1 N5f6
{ A beautiful move, both adding some defense to the kingside and vacating the d5 square in preparation of ...Bd5, trading off White's key queenside defender.   24...N7f6  would appear the more active choice, but after  25.Be5  Black's position is suddenly precarious since there's no more ...Nd7 in view of Qg7#, and Bxd5 followed by Bxf6 is a big threat. }
25. f3
{ Shabalov understandably wanted to stop the threat of ...Ne4, but the weakened e3-square can one day be used by a black knight. }
25... Bd5 26. Bxd5 Nxd5
{ 26...exd5  27.Nf5  Of course Karpov doesn't allow the knight to find activity on the kingside. }
27. Re4 Kh7
{ A greatprophylactic move, preparing to defend the g-pawn with the rook.   27...a5  28.Rg4  g6  29.Rxg6+  fxg6  30.Qxg6+  Kh8  31.Qxh6+  Kg8  32.Qg6+  Kh8  33.Qh6+ }
28. Rh4
{ Since White didn't manage to push any of his kingside pawns, it feels like he is struggling to find meaningful attacking ideas against Black's king. Therook lift was definitely the wrong direction and White's position is on the brink.   28.Rg4  Rg8 }
28... Rc4 { The knight is essentially pinned. } 29. b3
{ A move like  29.Nb3  would allow Karpov to show the tactical point of ...Rc4.  29...Rxh4  Deflecting the queen from the defense of the bishop.  30.Qxh4  Qxd6 }
29... Rc3 30. Bf4
{ A kind of desperate move, preventing Ne3, but since Karpov has two knights, he doesn't mind exchanging one of them.   30.Ba3  Ne3  31.Bb2  Qc5  32.Bxc3  Qxc3  33.Re1   33.Rd2  Qa1  Nxg2 }
30... Nxf4 31. Qxf4 Nf6
{ The other knight is coming to that e3-square with pressure on c2, and there's not much White can do about it. }
32. Re1 Rd8 33. Re5
{ White does have a threat of Rg5 with sacrificial ideas, but Karpov had }
33... Qc7
{ in his back pocket. A move that:   A@@EndBracket@@ attacks White's king   B@@EndBracket@@ defends f7   C@@EndBracket@@ pins White's rook. }
34. Kb1 Nd5 35. Qg3 Ne3
{ A knight has found its way to the promise land with overwhelming pressure against White's king. }
36. Qe1 Nxg2
{ Karpov opts to keep the knights on the board, and trusts his calculation.   36...Nxc2  37.Nxc2  Rxc2  is also game over as there is no defense to the dual threats of ...Rc8 and ...Rdd2. }
37. Qe4+ Kg8
{ Karpov saw the check, allowing White to save the exchange, but... } 38. Rg4
{ White is still losing material even after  38.Rhh5  because  38...Qd6  Black's pieces are too active along the d-file.  39.Ne2  Re3  40.Qg4  Rxe5  This is just one example how Black could win material. }
38... Re3 { Oops! The queen is trapped! } 39. Rxg7+
{ Whtie is forced to give up a rook to save the queen, but after } 39... Kxg7
40. Qg4+ Kf8
{ There is no more attack, and Shabalov threw in the towel. An astonishingly and methodical game by Karpov, exploiting White's inferior kingside attack. }
