{ Probably the most dangerous move, developing a piece and taking aim at f7.   Remember, with a bishop on c4, your tactical senses should be on high alert. }
5... Ngf6
{ There's no immediate threat, so we continue our development as intended, challenging the steed on e4. }
6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. c3
{ I've decided to add a line here to address what happens if you're not allowed to comfortably develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain. }
7... Qc7 8. Ne2 e6
{ Fear not - the bishop will enjoy the sunlight later on via ...b6, ...Bb7 and ...c5! Note our response would be the same after something like 8. Qb3 and if 8. Nf3, of course we would simply pin the knight. }
9. Bf4 Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Qd2 c5
{ Old faithful to the rescue! Next is ...b6 and ...Bb7 with equality. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Classical / Two Knights Variation"]
[Black "Classical: 5.Nf3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason.   White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov. He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  .   Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Nf3
{ The main move at all levels, highlighting an unfortunate side-effect of Black's last move. Black would love to be able to leapfrog the knight and pin the knight with ...Bg4, but that's not allowed!   However, I'm always happy to see it since it's also probably the least tricky. }
5... Ngf6
{ Our intended follow up, when the knights are working well together. } 6. Ng3
{ Instead of allowing the exchange, here White prefers to keep all the pieces on the board for the time being. }
6... e6
{ As a general rule, we play e6 before developing the light-squared bishop when a pair of knights are not exchanged @@StartBracket@@as in the Ng5lines, for instance@@EndBracket@@. If we are left with both knights, we don't have time to untangle ourselves and develop the bishop. We need to castle. }
7. Bd3 c5
{ I prefer to make the break before developing the dark-squared bishop. If they take, we can develop in one go.    Another benefit of this move is vacating the long diagonal so that when we fianchetto our light-squared bishop, it will have a nice, sunny view. }
8. c3
{ 8.dxc5  Nxc5  It's an interesting question which piece to recpature with on c5, and it always depends on the position. Here, both are playable but I would prefer taking with the knight in order to encourage further trades along the d-file.   Let's take a brief pause to see what that could look like:  9.O-O   @@StartBracket@@  9.Bb5+  Bd7  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  11.Qxd7+  Ncxd7  We certainly have no problems here, and White's g3-knight is looking funny.@@EndBracket@@  9...Nxd3  10.Qxd3  Qxd3  11.cxd3  If we are allowed to win the bishop pair and saddle White with an isolated pawn, they've done something wrong. }
8... Be7
{ 8...Bd6  is playable as well, but White has an extra piece on the kingside, so I prefer to be as solid as possible in this variation. }
9. O-O b6
{ Inviting the light-squared bishop to the party! I prefer this move to castling for a concrete reason.  9...O-O  would allow  10.Ne5  when we don't have time to go ...Bb7, protecting the c6 square. After  b6  White would have  11.Nc6  winning the bishop pair with a good position.   I want to avoid this. Luckily, this is the sort of subtlety MoveTrainer is perfectly suited to help you cement in your memory. Not only that, but exposure to circumstances when move-orders matter will improve your accuracy in your games. }
10. Ne5 { White's favourite attacking post for the knight. } 10... Bb7
{ The perfect square for the bishop. In fact, it's so good that White's best course of action is probably to set about exchanging it! }
11. Bb5 a6 { If White wants to exchange the bishops, I say we encourage it. }
12. Bc6
{ 12.Nc6  would not be wise as after  Qc7  both the white knight and bishop are under attack.  13.Nxe7  axb5  White's knight isn't getting out of there alive! }
12... Qc7
{ An important move, defending our bishop and simultaneously forcing a decision from White. }
13. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ We have a super healthy setup with a lot of game to go.  Next we can castle, bring our rooks to the centre and look for the right time to trade on e5. If we did it now, our knight would be displaced, the only defender of the kingside. }
