1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
{ This line is called the Classical Variation and for good reason.   White takes the centre, and instead of releasing the central tension by pushing further with e5 or taking on d5, White defends the pawn by developing a piece.  Because it follows the rules of development and central control, the Classical Variation is one of the big 3 methods of countering @@StartBracket@@or attempting to counter@@EndBracket@@ the Caro-Kann. }
3... dxe4
{ Just like in the Two Knights, we are going to snap off the e-pawn at the earliest opportunity. Here, we deny White of their central pawn duo. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The Karpov Variation! named after the legendary Soviet World Champion, Anatoly Karpov. He fancied this solid approach to the opening, accepting no weaknesses after the more trendy  4...Nf6  5.Nxf6  exf6  .   Next, our other knight will join the party, challenging White's strong central knight. }
5. Nf3
{ The main move at all levels, highlighting an unfortunate side-effect of Black's last move. Black would love to be able to leapfrog the knight and pin the knight with ...Bg4, but that's not allowed!   However, I'm always happy to see it since it's also probably the least tricky. }
5... Ngf6
{ Our intended follow up, when the knights are working well together. } 6.
Nxf6+ Nxf6
{ We're always happy when White helps us untangle, allowing the bishop to come out next. White can opt for the same aggressive piece setup we saw in the Two Knights, only this time there's a pawn on d4. This doesn't change much. }
7. Bc4
{ 7.Bg5  The amateur's favourite way to develop the bishop. White has already foregone their attacking chances, and besides, the bishop isn't better here than it was on c1 since White never wants to exchange it for our knight.  Bg4  We can handle this one the same way we handle the rest.   Pin it to win it! }
7... Bf5
{ The correct square in this specific case with the bishop on c4 and knight on f3.   Please don't fall into the  7...Bg4  trap.  8.Bxf7+  Kxf7  9.Ne5+  Remember this one?  Kg8  10.Nxg4  After losing a pawn and castling rights, Black is busted. }
8. O-O e6 9. c3 Bd6
{ A lovely, harmonious piece setup featuring our pillars of strength on e6 and c6. }
10. Ne5
{ We could check other moves, but when faced with a choice, I think it's most useful to check White's most active moves. Ne5 is one that will usually be played sooner or later. }
10... O-O 11. Re1 Qc7
{ Putting pressure on the knight andx-raying the h2-square. Oh yeah, and our development is finished! }
12. Bf4 c5
{ Striking at White's centre, and this time it comes with the added benefit of undermining the e4-knight. White's c4-bishop is starting to look a bit shaky as well.    Next we could capture on d4, play ...Rad8 and we could even consider ...Ng4, since the f4-bishop is undefended.   In conclusion: The Classical Variation, like the Two Knights Variation, has some venom, but as long as you understand when to choose which piece setup, dodging any tactics against your king, you'll be good to go!    You may be wondering what happens after a position such as this one, after Old Faithful has been deployed and the pieces have found good homes. Well, that's what playing and looking at games is for! In all of your openings, I recommend finding a player who often plays your systems and making them your role model by studying their games and trying to understand their middlegame ideas.    See you in the next chapter! }
*

