[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Fantasy Variation Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 1% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@    Welcome to a fun little chapter on the Fantasy Variation,  where White's wildest dreams involve us capturing on e4, turning their f-pawn into an e-pawn when White's double pawn-centre lives side by side, happily ever after. The f3-push weakens White's king a little bit, which will come back to bite them in some variations.    Your amateur opponent playing the Fantasy Variation is like spotting a unicorn in the wild, but learning how to fight it can help teach us valuable lessons about how to fight against the central pawn duo. Besides, as you rise through the ranks, it will become more prevalent. }
3... e6
{ When I had the idea for this course, it was never in doubt which antidote I would prescribe. As you're well aware by now, finding a good way to develop our light-squared bishop is one of the perennial positional considerations of the Caro-Kann. In the Advance Variation, since the pawn pushed to e5, our bishop could come out to the cozy f5-square.   Here. because White's pawns rudely control the active squares for our light-squared bishop to develop, for now it can stay on c8. Later we can bring it out on the queenside, similar to some lines in the Classical & Two Knights Variation. In the meantime, we construct our impenetrable Pawn-Triangle, thwarting White's fantasies of an open, sharp battle! }
4. Nc3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 35%@@EndBracket@@   The main move at all levels. White would like to develop the other knight to f3, but alas, a pawn clogs that square. This often causes confused development.   4.e5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 19%@@EndBracket@@   Surprisingly common at lower levels, taking the game into Advance Variation territory, but with a pawn on f3. In the Advance Variation, the f3 move is completely useless, and even blocks White's development, so that's why we our completely within our right to push forward with  4...c5  and initiate the central counterplay we're familiar with from the Advance Variation chapter. After moves like ...Nc6 and ...Qb6, White will find themselves under pressure. }
4... Bb4
{ We want to castle as soon as possible, so it's best to develop the bishop to its most active square before bringing the knight to its ideal e7-square. }
5. Bf4
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 3%@@EndBracket@@    The best move and the start of the mainline at higher levels of play, bringing White one step closer to castling queenside and dodging all of Black's tactics for now. The fact that it's played so infrequently is a ringing endorsement for our setup!   5.a3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 13%@@EndBracket@@   This is an example of one of the more common ways White could blunder a pawn. You will learn them all in the main chapter.  5...Bxc3+  6.bxc3  dxe4  7.fxe4  Qh4+  Forking the king and e4-pawn.  8.g3  The greater of two evils. White should have bit the bullet and moved the king, relinquishing castling rights. But now after  8...Qxe4+  We have our second fork, this time winning a rook.  9.Qe2  Qxh1  White can resign. It's super easy for White to stumble into something like this.   5.Bd2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 47%@@EndBracket@@   The most popular move, and the best alternative to the mainline, Bf4. White reactively unpins the knight.  5...Ne7  We are about to castle and complete kingside development, then proceed with operation: free the light-squared bishop with ...b6. }
5... Ne7
{ From here, the knight watches over the centre and won't get kicked around by any of White's pawns or pieces.  In this setup, we want our d5-square as solid as possible while we go about our business on the queenside. }
6. Qd3
{ White wants to castle long, which makes sense since the f3-pawn makes it more difficult to develop the kingside. }
6... b6
{ This move gives me the warm fuzzies. The c8-bishop sees the light of day as the a6-square calls its name. The queen will need to move again, and one day we can trade off that bishop and look forward to a beautifully flowing queenside attack with no bad pieces! Remember, your attack is more likely to be successful the fewer weaknesses you have, and in this structure, the c8-bishop can be considered a weakness that needs to be resolved.   My Five Lifelines:   A@@EndBracket@@ Stay solid on the d5-square. You normally don't want to move that pawn since it represents our share of the center.   B@@EndBracket@@ The White player is tiptoeing through a tactical minefield. Memorize White's possible mistakes in the opening and take advantage when they blunder!   C@@EndBracket@@ Solve the problem of the light-squared bishop, most often with ...b6 / ...Ba6. In rare cases, Black can consider the ...e5 break to activate it along the h3-c8 diagonal.   D@@EndBracket@@ Understand when to take the knight on c3, and when not to.   E@@EndBracket@@ After an eventual ...c5, you can choose between ...cxd4 trading our light-squared bishop off along the f1-a6 diagonal before pushing ahead with ...c4 with a queenside pawn-storm. Which plan you go for will depend on the specific position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Fantasy: 4.e5 (Advance)"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. f3
{ They call this one the Fantasy Variation because White has a 'fantasy' of keeping two pawns in the centre for as long as possible. But of course, it comes with the price of playing the move f3, which undeniably weakens White's kingside. Since White maintains the tension in the centre, it has the tendency to become quite sharp in many lines.   That being said, I'm happy to inform you that White will not be getting what they want against our repertoire. On the contrary, similar to the Panov-Botvinnik Attack*, my setup of choice is full of pitfalls for White. }
3... e6
{ Against the Fantasy, I like to expedite the construction of mypawn triangle.  Yes, the bishop is inside the pawn-chain this time, but since we aren't taking on e4, the f3-pawn is looking a little clumsy!  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  is the variation Erwin recommends in his Lifetime Repertoire, which is a great way to meet the Fantasy head-on.  But, a line like this that involves taking on e4 showcases another of White's ambitions - castling and using the half-open f-file for the rook. Objectively, it's nothing to fear, but I don't like to play the opening on White's terms. }
4. e5
{ White is going into a version of the Advance Variation where Black has an undeveloped bishop on c8 and White has wasted a tempo with f3.    The verdict is clear that these factors are in Black's favour - the f3-pawn not only without purpose, it blocks White's development. }
4... c5
{ As a rule of thumb, whenever we are able to achieve Old Faithful, we haveequalised.    Well, even on move 4, this is no exception. White can't bring a knight to it's normal square on f3 to defend the centre.   What's wrong with the plan I recommended in the Advance Variation?  4...Ne7  Nothing at all!  5.f4  c5  6.Nf3  Nf5  If you prefer waiting a move or two to prepare ...c5, go for it. But I prefer playing it as soon as it's comfortable, in order to put pressure on White's centre right away. }
5. c3
{ White finishes their connect 4 pawn-structure, but we will aim to tear it down. }
5... Nc6
{ In contrast with my recommendation against the Advance Variation, we have already played c5, and there's no need to delay putting pressure on White's centre. }
6. Be3
{ Perhaps the most natural move to defend the centre. If given another move, White could take, and hold onto, our c5-pawn.  6.f4  just like in most lines of the Advance Variation proper, is simply poor.  Nh6  It's tempting to gain the extra space, but this pawn spent two moves moving to f3, then f4, and weakening light-squares along the way. }
6... Qb6
{ Very typical, developing a new piece with more pressure on the centre, and pointing out White has left the b2-undefended. }
7. Qd2
{ White would like to defend the pawn with a piece and avoid creating weaknesses.  7.b3  cxd4  8.cxd4  Nxe5 }
7... Bd7
{ Simple development, possibly preparing ...Rc8 in order to put extra pressure on the queenside. Don't bring out the knight too early when after  7...Nge7  8.dxc5  White gets a free pawn. }
8. f4
{ White needs to push the f-pawn again sooner or later if they want to pretend to have kingside counterplay, and to develop the knight on its ideal f3-square. }
8... cxd4
{ Now, that b4-square is looking awfully juicy for our bishop, so it's time to force a change in White's pawn-structure. }
9. cxd4
{ Of course, if they take with the bishop, we will take it, but White normally doesn't want to exchange pieces. }
9... Bb4
{ Voila! the b4-square is perfect for our bishop before deploying the g8-knight. }
10. Nc3 Nge7
{ We could end the variation here since we've found cozy squares for everyone, but our next moves are instructive: }
11. Nf3 { Developing a piece, supporting the centre. } 11... Rc8
{ ...Rc8 is rarely a bad move in any Advance Variation line since we like to direct play towards the queenside. Here, it takes aim at the pinned piece on c3. }
12. Bd3 Na5
{ Because of the way White handed us the initiative in the opening, Black's developing moves have had purpose while White's have not. We have a lot of pressure on c3, and at the right moment we can capture the knight after which the pawn on c3 will be forever weak. Our next moves can be ...Nc4, ...O-O, and possibly doubling rooks on the c-file.   Small disclaimer:  This is one of those variations I'm including in the course to demonstrate how to take advantage of inferior play in general, not because I think your opponents will often mix ideas from the Fantasy and Advance Variation. }
*

