[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "🧨 Fantasy: 5.a3 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. f3
{ They call this one the Fantasy Variation because White has a 'fantasy' of keeping two pawns in the centre for as long as possible. But of course, it comes with the price of playing the move f3, which undeniably weakens White's kingside. Since White maintains the tension in the centre, it has the tendency to become quite sharp in many lines.   That being said, I'm happy to inform you that White will not be getting what they want against our repertoire. On the contrary, similar to the Panov-Botvinnik Attack*, my setup of choice is full of pitfalls for White. }
3... e6
{ Against the Fantasy, I like to expedite the construction of mypawn triangle.  Yes, the bishop is inside the pawn-chain this time, but since we aren't taking on e4, the f3-pawn is looking a little clumsy!  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  is the variation Erwin recommends in his Lifetime Repertoire, which is a great way to meet the Fantasy head-on.  But, a line like this that involves taking on e4 showcases another of White's ambitions - castling and using the half-open f-file for the rook. Objectively, it's nothing to fear, but I don't like to play the opening on White's terms. }
4. Nc3
{ Since Nf3 is an impossibility, White likes to bring out the other knight. }
4... Bb4
{ Pin it to win it!   In this variation, we like our knight coming to e7 quickly to support the centre, so we first make sure the bishop gets involved. Now... White has many possible moves in this position, but it turns out most of them are blunders! That's one of the major reasons I'm recommending this setup for beginners - White's centre-hoarding ambitions can easily backfire!    A@@EndBracket@@ Black's queen is indirectly attacking the d4-pawn, so White constantly has to dodge tactics involving ... dxe4 and winning the d-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ White's f3 move opens the e1-h4 diagonal towards the king, which gives us some cool tactical opportunities.   4...Bd6  would encourage White to push  5.e5  taking the game into an Advance Variation when the bishop needs to move again.   We can do better. }
5. a3
{ When an amateur plays this move, it's likely a blunder, but when experienced players have used this as a pawn sacrifice line. }
5... Bxc3+
{ We take the knight, just so we have time to also take the e4-pawn! } 6. bxc3
dxe4 7. Qe2
{ The best try, since recapturing is off the table. White is trying to control the e4-square, defending against ...Qh4 tactics, and hoping we will take another pawn on f3 to help them develop.   It's quite an advanced idea which you will encounter rarely, if ever.   7.fxe4  is a very common mistake at amateur levels, disregarding the nasty check,  Qh4+  when White must either move the king up the board, or allow  8.g3  Qxe4+  9.Qe2  Qxh1  . }
7... c5
{ I'm not a fan of accepting the gambit with  7...exf3  8.Nxf3  when White has the bishop pair and open files and diagonals to use for attack.   That's not to say we are afraid of an open position. The devil is in the details. With this move, we encourage the position to open under circumstances when it's hard for White to develop their kingside. For instance, they are a million moves from castling, and we have good squares for all of our pieces to come out to. }
8. Qe3
{ Another subtle move I doubt you will encounter, vacating the e2-square to aid in kingside development and defending d4. The tempting alternatives are inferior:   A.  8.fxe4  drops the d-pawn after  8...cxd4  9.cxd4  Qxd4   B.  8.Qxe4  gets hit by  8...Nf6  9.Qh4  and now we can open everything up with  9...cxd4  10.cxd4  Nc6  11.c3  e5  12.dxe5  Nxe5  13.Qd4  Qe7  14.Ne2  Bf5  and in a position like this, Black is much better with the superior structure and piece activity. }
8... cxd4 9. cxd4 Nc6 { Adding more pressure to the weak d4-pawn. } 10. Bb2 Nf6
{ Still refusing to take the extra pawn on f3 and help White develop, which is White's true fantasy. }
11. fxe4 O-O 12. Nf3 Qb6
{ The position is equal and it's not clear whether White's center is a strength or a liability. Pretty much all of White's pawns could be targets in the long run.   If White can't open things up and make use of the bishop pair and Black is allowed to bring in the rest of the pieces, Black might be strategically better. }
