4. Nc3 { The main move. So far, so good. } 4... Bb4
{ Pin it to win it!   In this variation, we like our knight coming to e7 quickly to support the centre, so we first make sure the bishop gets involved. Now... White has many possible moves in this position, but it turns out most of them are blunders! That's one of the major reasons I'm recommending this setup for beginners - White's centre-hoarding ambitions can easily backfire!    A@@EndBracket@@ Black's queen is indirectly attacking the d4-pawn, so White constantly has to dodge tactics involving ... dxe4 and winning the d-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ White's f3 move opens the e1-h4 diagonal towards the king, which gives us some cool tactical opportunities. In this position, Black is already threatening to win material with ...dxe4 followed by ...Qh4, forking the king and e4-pawn.   4...Bd6  would encourage White to push  5.e5  taking the game into an Advance Variation when the bishop needs to move again.   We can do better. }
5. Bd2
{ A modest move - the mainline is the more active 5.Bf4, but no mistakes so far. }
5... Ne7 { The knight goes on e7 in this setup! } 6. a3
{ Makes sense, asking a question to our bishop. Will we trade it, or move it away? }
6... Ba5
{ We like our bishops. In this chapter, sometimes we will take on c3, sometimes we won't. I'll try to explain in the theory. }
7. b4
{ White has gone too far. We've established amateurs like pushing our active pieces away, even at the cost of creating weaknesses. }
7... Bc7
{ We don't mind retreating the bishop whatsoever because with ...Bb4, we didn't want to trade it for the knight, we simply didn't have a better place to develop it. Now White is overextended and our bishop has a great square on c7! }
8. Bd3
{ Mistakes tend to come in pairs! I'm happy we get to see an example of one of the tactical pitfalls that the White player can fall into in the Fantasy. Even happier that it's the most popular line! }
8... dxe4 9. fxe4 Qxd4
{ Already we're able to win an important central pawn for free! And as we know, the Fantasy player loves their central pawns. There are many such tactical opportunities against the d4-pawn if it becomes undefended. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Fantasy: 5.Bf4 (Mainline) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. f3
{ They call this one the Fantasy Variation because White has a 'fantasy' of keeping two pawns in the centre for as long as possible. But of course, it comes with the price of playing the move f3, which undeniably weakens White's kingside. Since White maintains the tension in the centre, it has the tendency to become quite sharp in many lines.   That being said, I'm happy to inform you that White will not be getting what they want against our repertoire. On the contrary, similar to the Panov-Botvinnik Attack*, my setup of choice is full of pitfalls for White. }
3... e6
{ Against the Fantasy, I like to expedite the construction of mypawn triangle.  Yes, the bishop is inside the pawn-chain this time, but since we aren't taking on e4, the f3-pawn is looking a little clumsy!  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  is the variation Erwin recommends in his Lifetime Repertoire, which is a great way to meet the Fantasy head-on.  But, a line like this that involves taking on e4 showcases another of White's ambitions - castling and using the half-open f-file for the rook. Objectively, it's nothing to fear, but I don't like to play the opening on White's terms. }
4. Nc3
{ Since Nf3 is an impossibility, White likes to bring out the other knight. }
4... Bb4
{ Pin it to win it!   In this variation, we like our knight coming to e7 quickly to support the centre, so we first make sure the bishop gets involved. Now... White has many possible moves in this position, but it turns out most of them are blunders! That's one of the major reasons I'm recommending this setup for beginners - White's centre-hoarding ambitions can easily backfire!    A@@EndBracket@@ Black's queen is indirectly attacking the d4-pawn, so White constantly has to dodge tactics involving ... dxe4 and winning the d-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ White's f3 move opens the e1-h4 diagonal towards the king, which gives us some cool tactical opportunities. In this position, Black is already threatening to win material with ...dxe4 followed by ...Qh4, forking the king and e4-pawn.   4...Bd6  would encourage White to push  5.e5  taking the game into an Advance Variation when the bishop needs to move again.   We can do better. }
5. Bf4
{ Of all the possible moves in this position, this move @@StartBracket@@the correct one@@EndBracket@@ is played a mere 3% of the time - basically never! Amazing.  The bishop is developed to an active square and simultaneously defends against our ...Qh4+ idea. }
5... Ne7
{ This knight belongs on e7 in the Fantasy. We don't want it being kicked away from f6 with tempo at any moment by an e5 push.    As you can see, our development scheme has revolved around quick castling. Then we can start play in the centre or on the queenside. }
6. Bd3
{ White isn't giving up on castling kingside even with a pawn on f3. Unfortunately, White is losing material similar to the 5. Bd3line. }
6... dxe4 { Exposing an attack on on the d4-pawn. } 7. Bxe4
{ White thinks the pawn is safe...  7.fxe4  would immediately drop the pawn to  Qxd4  . }
7... f5 { The cold shower move. } 8. Bd3 Qxd4
{ We've won a pawn for very little compensation. } *

