[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "🤺🧨 Fantasy: 5.Bf4 (Mainline) #3 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. f3
{ They call this one the Fantasy Variation because White has a 'fantasy' of keeping two pawns in the centre for as long as possible. But of course, it comes with the price of playing the move f3, which undeniably weakens White's kingside. Since White maintains the tension in the centre, it has the tendency to become quite sharp in many lines.   That being said, I'm happy to inform you that White will not be getting what they want against our repertoire. On the contrary, similar to the Panov-Botvinnik Attack*, my setup of choice is full of pitfalls for White. }
3... e6
{ Against the Fantasy, I like to expedite the construction of mypawn triangle.  Yes, the bishop is inside the pawn-chain this time, but since we aren't taking on e4, the f3-pawn is looking a little clumsy!  3...dxe4  4.fxe4  e5  is the variation Erwin recommends in his Lifetime Repertoire, which is a great way to meet the Fantasy head-on.  But, a line like this that involves taking on e4 showcases another of White's ambitions - castling and using the half-open f-file for the rook. Objectively, it's nothing to fear, but I don't like to play the opening on White's terms. }
4. Nc3
{ Since Nf3 is an impossibility, White likes to bring out the other knight. }
4... Bb4
{ Pin it to win it!   In this variation, we like our knight coming to e7 quickly to support the centre, so we first make sure the bishop gets involved. Now... White has many possible moves in this position, but it turns out most of them are blunders! That's one of the major reasons I'm recommending this setup for beginners - White's centre-hoarding ambitions can easily backfire!    A@@EndBracket@@ Black's queen is indirectly attacking the d4-pawn, so White constantly has to dodge tactics involving ... dxe4 and winning the d-pawn.   B@@EndBracket@@ White's f3 move opens the e1-h4 diagonal towards the king, which gives us some cool tactical opportunities. In this position, Black is already threatening to win material with ...dxe4 followed by ...Qh4, forking the king and e4-pawn.   4...Bd6  would encourage White to push  5.e5  taking the game into an Advance Variation when the bishop needs to move again.   We can do better. }
5. Bf4
{ Of all the possible moves in this position, this move @@StartBracket@@the correct one@@EndBracket@@ is played a mere 3% of the time - basically never! Amazing.  The bishop is developed to an active square and simultaneously defends against our ...Qh4+ idea. }
5... Ne7
{ This knight belongs on e7 in the Fantasy. We don't want it being kicked away from f6 with tempo at any moment by an e5 push.    As you can see, our development scheme has revolved around quick castling. Then we can start play in the centre or on the queenside. }
6. Qd3
{ The main move, preparing queenside castling. White would rather not castle kingside since f3 pawn leaves a poor impression on that side of the board. Even though there's nothing overly complicated in this variation, I'm marking it a dynamite line because it's White's most testing way of playing and I want you to get the best position possible. :@@EndBracket@@ }
6... b6
{ We could also castle, but ...b6 is a move we equally know that we want to play, preparing the unorthodox deployment of our light-squared bishop on a6.    From there, it will nibble the queen, and we may even get to trade light-squared bishops, which would delight us since it became our worst piece after playing ....e6. }
7. Ne2 Ba6 8. Qe3 O-O
{ Our king is snug as a bug in a rug here and we can now look to break things open with Old Faithful. }
9. O-O-O
{ The addresses of both kings have been confirmed and the battleground is set. }
9... c5
{ A move I'm always excited to make! White has adopted a relatively tame setup compared to the chaos they were after, and now it's us controlling the tempo of the game! If White captures on c5, capturing with the pawn or bishop is really a matter of taste, but either way, a file will be opened towards White's king. So, that's likely not going to happen - which gives me the chance to teach you a little lesson on pawn tension: Whenever a set of pawns can capture each other, the side whom can @@StartBracket@@at some moment@@EndBracket@@ favourably release that tension @@StartBracket@@be it by capturing or pushing ahead@@EndBracket@@ has the edge.   Although White almost never wants to capture on c5, we could easily imagine a scenario where we improve our pieces and one day decide to capture on d4 to open the c-file for an attack.  On the other hand, the tension between the d5-pawn and the e4-pawn may be favouring White, since we almost never want to capture on e4, allowing the f3-pawn to fulfill its destiny. However, White may someday profit from opening the e-file. }
10. a3 { Putting the question to the bishop. } 10... Bxc3
{ Our response is forced, else we drop the c5-pawn.  That's ok, when we developed the bishop to b4, we are content with the reality that often this bishop will trade itself for the knight. }
11. Qxc3 { Preserving the pawn structure. } 11... Nd7
{ SPARRING POSITION   Although the engine says the position is equal, I see some red flags in White's position.    A@@EndBracket@@ The king and queen both sit on the c-file which could open at any time.   B@@EndBracket@@ It's not clear what White's plan should be. An attack on Black's king takes much longer than ours since the files are closed.    C@@EndBracket@@ Black has multiple attractive continuations. We could open the c-file at any time, but also if we are allowed to trade light-squared bishops, ...c4 becomes an attractive option, followed by a queenside pawnstorm.    For these reasons, I think even very experienced players would find the White side of this position quite practically difficult to manage.  That being said, I recommend having a play around with this position to see what sort of attacks you can come up with. Do check out the model game which continues from this line where Andreikin totally outplayed Nepomniachtchi from this position, demonstrating what a dangerous queenside attack can look like.  In conclusion, the Fantasy Variation is a serious, dynamic weapon, but I feel our triangle pawn setup takes out a lot of its punch. I think you'll have a lot of fun grabbing pawns and checkmating the white king on the queenside!    The most important thing to understand about playing these positions is when and how to resolve the central pawn tension. Unfortunately, it's a bit out of the scope of this course, but it's a good topic to chat to a strong player about to help you understand. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Ian Nepomniachtchi vs. Dmitry Andreikin, Rus. Ch. U20, 2010"]
[Result "*"]

{ This game was played between two Russian heavyweights - Ian Nepomniachtchi, the multi-time Chess World Championship Challenger with the white pieces vs. two-time Russian Champion, Dmitry Andreikin with the Black pieces. I love how Andreikin displayed a paradigmatic queenside attack after White castled queenside.   Notice how few counterchances White seemed to have as Black was thoroughly in control for the entire middlegame. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3
{ This was when both players were a bit younger and Nepo was more explorative with his openings. }
3... e6
{ Andreikin opts for the pawn triangle setup I advocate for.  Looks solid, but it has venom! }
4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bf4 Ne7
{ Our kingside development is perfectly sorted with optimal control of the d5-square, and ready to castle. }
6. Qd3 { The main move, intending queenside castling. } 6... b6 7. Ne2 Ba6 8.
Qe3 O-O 9. O-O-O c5
{ Andreikin has been following the manual to the tee.  After setting up the pawn triangle, he's castled, solved the problem of the light-squared bishop, and now initiates his queenside attack via Old Faithful. }
10. a3 Bxc3 11. Qxc3 Nd7 12. Kb1 Bxe2
{ Now that development is finished, Andreikin decides to take concrete actions on the queenside. He wants to start a queenside pawnstorm starting with ...c4, but first it's best to trade off the light-squared bishop.  It's much better off the board than stuck behind a wall of our own pawns. }
13. Bxe2 c4 14. h4 b5
{ As you can see, both sides are pushing their flank pawns towards the other's king. The difference is White has played a3 which acts as a hook for Black to use to pry open the queenside with.  It's much harder for White to open the black king.  Starting with   14...a5  and only then pushing ...bg5-b4 would have been more precise, keeping White's queen at bay. }
15. Qb4 a6
{ The queen on b4 controls lots of weak dark squares in Black's camp, making it more difficult to arrange the queenside attack. Andreikin calmly defends the pawn and ...Nc6 will eventually dislodge the queen. }
16. h5
{ Nepo is a brilliant and creative attacker, but in this case, doesn't know what else to do besides push the pawns forward and hope something sticks. }
16... Rc8
{ Reinforcing a potential ...c3 push, and   16...Nc6  is the most natural move, but sometimes the most natural moves are not the best. Chess can be a cruel game.  After  17.Qd6  White has a lot of pressure on our d5-square. As we know, if we lose control of this square, our game can fall apart quite quickly. We would also generally prefer not to exchange queens and go into an endgame when White's bishop pair could become useful. }
17. g4
{ If White is given a few moves in a row, g5-g6 would eventually force the opening of Black's kingside.   17.Qd6  unprovoked can now be met by  17...Rc6 }
17... Nc6 18. Qe1
{ Nepo probably underestimated Black's queenside initiative after this passive move.   Nepo should have definitely preferred  18.Qd6  when Black would have nothing better than to allow the exchange of queens.  18...Nb6  19.h6  g6  20.Qxd8  Rfxd8  In a position like this where White has the centre and bishop pair, combined with the fact that our attacking chances have greatly diminished, White must have a slight edge. }
18... Qb6
{ A difficult move for White to meet. Now the d4-pawn is under fire, but more importantly, ...b4 is coming quick and with force! }
19. Bf1 { A slow move, allowing Andreikin to steam ahead! } 19... b4
{ 19...Nxd4  20.Be3  would be a very uncomfortable pin to deal with. } 20. axb4
{ Basically forced since Black can't be allowed to take on a3.   20.a4  would strand the a-pawn after  20...b3  21.c3  Qa5 }
20... a5
{ The strongest move - offering a pawn to open another queenside file! } 21. b5
{ 21.bxa5  Accepting the gift would not end well after  21...Nxa5  22.Qc3  White must prevent the ...c3 push.  22...Ra8  when moves like ...Rfc8 and ...Nb3 would surround the white king. }
21... Qxb5 { Nepo tried to minimize the damage by keepign the a-file closed. }
22. Rh2 Nb4 { Preparing to enter with the queen on the a2-square if allowed. }
23. g5
{ Unfortunately it's a bit too late for White's attack...   It's instructive to understand that moving yet another pawn around White's king is simply not possible.  23.c3  Qa4  Black can even sacrifice a piece because after  24.cxb4  axb4  Black's queen, rooks, and c and b-pawns are all potent attackers and neither of White's bishops are contributing to the game in any meaningful way.  25.Bd6  c3  This is just a sample line, but it demonstrates the potency of Black's attack, even when a knight is replaced by a pawn in the attack. }
23... Qa4 24. Qc3 Na2
{ A very nice move, forcing through the ...c3 push.   24...Qa2+  would be imprecise, allowing the king to escape via the d2-square.  25.Kc1 }
25. Qa3
{ Not a bad practical decision, forcing the queen trade and hoping to survive an endgame down material.   Allowing the queens to stay on the board would lead to disaster:  25.Qe3  c3  26.b3   26.bxc3  Opening the b-file is never an option for White.  26...Rb8+  27.Bb5  Rxb5+  28.Ka1  Nc1  Discovered Checkmate!  Qa3  Mate on b2 is unstoppable. }
25... Qxa3 26. bxa3 Nc3+ 27. Kc1 Nxd1 28. Kxd1
{ It's time to take stock of the situation. Black just won an exchange, but White has compensation in the form of the bishop pair and a little extra space.  Nepo went on to outplay his esteemed opponent from here after several mistakes from both sides, so we won't scrutinize the remaining moves. Achei  ving an arguably winning position like this with the black pieces is a huge success, even if it doesn't end with a flashy checkmate. }
28... Rfd8 29. exd5 Nb6 { A nice in-between move, activating the d8-rook. } 30.
dxe6 Rxd4+ 31. Rd2 Rxd2+ 32. Bxd2 fxe6 33. Bxa5 Nd5 34. Bd2 Kf7
{ 34...c3  would have been the final nail in White's coffin, discombobulating White's pieces when after  35.Bc1  Rb8  The threat of ...Rb1 putting White in an eternal pin, is decisive. }
35. c3 Ke7 36. Kc2 Kd6 37. Bc1 Rf8 38. Bxc4 Rxf3 39. Bd3 Rh3 40. h6 gxh6 41.
gxh6 Ne3+ 42. Kb3 Nf5 43. Kc2 Nxh6 44. Bxh7 Nf5 45. Bg6 Kd5 46. a4 Kc4 47. Bd2
Ne3+ 48. Kc1 Kb3 49. Bxe3 Rxe3 50. Kd2 Re5 51. Bc2+ Kb2 52. c4 Rh5 53. Bd1 Rh4
54. Kd3 e5 55. Be2 Kb3 56. a5 Kb4 57. a6 Rxc4 58. a7 Rc3+ 59. Ke4 Ra3 60. Kxe5
Rxa7 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) Fantasy Variation"]
[Black "Mobina Alinasab vs. Jovanka Houska, Chennai Olympiad, 2022"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. f3 e6 4. Nc3 Bb4 5. Bd2 b6
{ This was a recent game played only last year at the Chennai Olympiad! My opponent was a strong WGM from Iran. Here my opponent chose a more passive square for her bishop on d2. The mainline is  5.Bc4  ,  but here White wants to break the pin immediately.   5...Ne7  is the move recommended in the course, quickly getting castled... but it can easily transpose. }
6. a3 Be7
{ I preferred holding onto the bishop pair for a rainy day.   In a similar line in the course I recommend taking the knight when after  6...Bxc3  7.Bxc3  Ne7  White's bishop pair is quite ineffectual and the e7-square belongs to the knight. }
7. e5
{ My opponent decides to transition into an Advance Variation, which is always valid, but the pawn on f3 doesn't make a good impression. On the other hand, our c8-bishop is behind a wall of pawns when it's usually out in the fresh air on f5.   When your opponent takes the game from the territory of one opening to another, it's important to mentally switch gears and take a fresh look at the position objectively. }
7... c5 { The standard break in the Advance. } 8. Nce2 Nc6 9. c3 a5 10. f4
{ A common move to vacate the f3-square for the knight and start a kingside initiative. }
10... Ba6
{ I was already feeling very content with my position as I've solved the problem of developing my light-squared bishop, and have plenty of play on the queenside. }
11. Nf3
{ My opponent should have taken the opportunity to push through  11.f5  exf5  White can't be allowed to take on e6, when our e6-pawn would be weak for the rest of the game.  12.Nf3 }
11... Nh6
{ A great square for the knight, and one we've seen in one of the Advance Variation sidelines after f4 had been played. The knight controls the kingside light squares and prevents the f5-push. }
12. Be3 O-O 13. g3 a4 14. Bh3
{ Unorthodox development of that bishop. White wants to prepare the f5 break. Better late than never.   14.Qxa4  Bxe2  would win material after  15.Qxc6  Bxf3 }
14... Na5
{ The c4-square is a beautiful outpost for the knight where, because of our ...a5-a4 move, it can't be kicked away easily. }
15. Qc2
{ I remember calculating  15.Qxa4  Nc4  16.Bc1  which is still great for Black after  16...Nxb2  and if White grabs the knight, again we win material after  17.Bxb2  Bxe2 }
15... Qd7 16. g4
{ White is trying desperately to force the f5 break through, but White isn't quite in time, and with a king in the centre, isn't ready to open lines. }
16... Nc4 17. Bc1 f6
{ It may seem like a counterintuitive move, encouraging the opening of the kingside, but it goes to show how uncoordinated White's pieces are.   As long as your pieces are more active and effectively placed than your opponents, opening lines usually benefits you. Also, White's structure is under heavy fire from both angles! }
18. exf6 gxf6
{ Now that I have a new pawn on f6, my plan is to slide the king to safety with ...Kh8, to bring the knight back via f7, and support a central ...e5 break at the right moment.  Once the centre opens up, although my king looks a bit airy, White's king will be equally exposed. }
19. f5 Nf7 20. Nf4 e5 21. Ne6 e4
{ White has a pretty-looking knight on e6, but it's not coordinating with any friendly forces to create any threats! Meanwhile, it's Black who suddenly has the central space advantage and an incredibly powerful protected passed e-pawn.   Yes, it's an exchange sacrifice, but well-worth it! White would need to exchange their only active piece, which my opponent wasn't ready to do. }
22. Nh4
{ 22.Nxf8  Bxf8  23.Nh4  cxd4  24.cxd4  Rc8  is an example of what the position could look like if White accepts the exchange. Black has a dominating position, White isn't finished developing, the king is out in the open, and with control of the c-file I would be able to crash through eventually. }
22... cxd4 23. cxd4 { 23.Nxf8  Bxf8 } 23... Rfc8
{ I was able to save the rook, and grab control of the important c-file, which I was able to use to enter White's position. }
24. Qg2 Ng5 25. O-O Na5 26. Be3
{ This time White offers an exchange, but the alternative looks just as hopeless.   Holding onto the exchange with something like  26.Rd1  would allow a sequence where after a series of exchanges,  26...Nb3  27.Rb1  Nxc1  28.Rbxc1  Rxc1  29.Rxc1  Rc8  Black owns the c-file, and combined with the dominant centre and impenetrable kingside blockade, Black is strategically winning. }
26... Bxf1 27. Rxf1 Nc4 28. Bf4 { 28.Bxg5  fxg5  would trap the knight on h4. }
28... Rc6 29. Qg3 Rac8 30. Ng2 Bd6 31. Bxd6 Qxd6 32. Ngf4 Nd2 33. Rf2 Ndf3+ 34.
Kh1 Rc1+ 35. Bf1 R8c2 36. Rxc2 Rxc2 37. Be2 Nxe6 38. fxe6
{ Besides dropping a piece,  38.Nxe6  would allow a mating attack after  38...Qxg3  39.hxg3  Rxe2  with inevitable mate on h2. }
38... Nxd4 39. g5 Nxe2 40. Nxe2 Qxg3
{ And here, down too much material, my opponent resigned. I think this is a nice example of playing for the centre, and how our modest pawn triangle from the Fantasy Variation can sometimes pack a powerful punch later on. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Panov-Botvinnik Attack Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: ~1.5% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@   Here is the starting position of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, a favourite of lovers of sharp and open positions. However, I like closed positions and the good news is in the variation I'm recommending, White's best option is to close the centre again!   With this pawn lunge, White takes on some strategic risk since the d-pawn is often weak, but in exchange, they're getting immediate pressure on our centre. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 56%@@EndBracket@@   The mainline, which you might call the Four Knights Variation.   6.Bg5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 13%@@EndBracket@@   A logical continuation, indirectly adding pressure to d5 since at any moment White could choose to capture the f6-knight.  6...Be6  The key move of our setup! Instead of playing ...e6, locking in this bishop, we put it to work defending the centre.  7.Be2  When you see this combination of bishop moves, alarm bells should go off. White wants to quickly put the bishop on f3, hitting our d5-square yet again.  This variation, in my opinion, represents the maximum pressure White can put on our setup, so we need to adapt appropriately.   7.Bxf6  White can choose to take the knight immediately when we have the choice of which way to recapture.  7...exf6  I prefer to maintain a safe haven for our king on the kingside.   7.Nf3  g6  Here we will check what happens if White doesn't capture on f6, giving us doubled f-pawns. We will calmly fianchetto the dark-squared bishop, castle, and sooner or later, White will be forced to resolve the tension either by taking on d5 or pushing ahead. You will learn how to deal with both.   7.Nge2  White wants to quickly take aim at our busy bishop on e6, but...  7...dxc4  Oops - the c-pawn is hanging. Nf4 is not working because it drops another pawn on d4, and all tactics favour us.  7...Qa5  The move to remember - pinning the knight and clearing the d8-square for extra defense of d5.  the d5-square is our share of the centre and cannot be neglected! Play can get sharp from here, but with plenty ofimbalances with which to outplay your opponent. }
6... Be6
{ The starting position of my favourite setup starring the busy light-squared bishop! }
7. cxd5
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 32%@@EndBracket@@   7.Ng5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 3%@@EndBracket@@   This one is too feisty - the bishop can simply move to safety and the knight can later be kicked back.  7...Bg4  8.f3  Bc8  White's position is significantly compromised by the f3 push.   7.c5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 20%@@EndBracket@@   White gains a little bit of space and resolves the central tension, which is probably the best way to play. After they finish developing, White wants to expand on the queenside and eventually try to create a strong passed pawn with their queensidemajority.  7...g6  Meanwhile, we are going for central counterplay with thematic moves such as ...Bg7, ...O-O. ...Bg4, ...Ne4, and later, ...e5. Take a mental snapshot of this position as it represents the basic setup both sides are likely aiming for. }
7... Bxd5
{ Here, White has released the pressure they had on our centre and now their weakness on d4 sticks out like a sore thumb.    My Five Lifelines:   A@@EndBracket@@ Listen to your busy bishop @@StartBracket@@the light-squared bishop@@EndBracket@@. It's the star of the show and although it starts on e6, depending what White does, it might be needed on other squares!   B@@EndBracket@@ Target White's d-pawn! This is true in all lines whether White captures on d5 @@StartBracket@@in which case, it's an isolated pawn@@EndBracket@@, or pushes ahead with c5 @@StartBracket@@in which case, the d-pawn is a backwards pawn@@EndBracket@@.   C@@EndBracket@@ Remember in lines where White maintains central pressure, the d5 square needs extra support - for example, in the 6. Bg5 / 7. Be2 variation when ...Qa5 is necessary.   D@@EndBracket@@ In the mainlines where White pushes ahead with c5, White likes to expand on the queenside later in the middlegame. In response, your typical counterplay is in the centre, preparing a well-timed ...e5 break.   E@@EndBracket@@ As usual, exchanges benefit Black in most lines since reduced material highlights pawn weaknesses, and by definition, White has at least one pawn weakness in the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. }
