[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Panov: Premature 6.c5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ You may recognize this position from the Exchange Variation, but White has another option on move four that we haven't covered. }
4. c4
{ When White takes in the centre then immediately strikes against our centre, it's called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, named after two Grandmasters who championed this line in the mid-20th century.    The Panov, as we will henceforth refer to it, is one of the most aggressive and ambitious options for White against the Caro-Kann because of the early pressure against the pawn centre we've built with our first moves. It's a rare guest at amateur level because we're not taught to make so many pawn moves right away. It's much more popular at club-level and beyond. Forget about pawn triangles and long, maneuvering games - White wants to party. But I know exactly how to crash White's party, and even encourage the central structure to close so that we have time to put all our pieces on great squares.   Let's get started. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@ The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6 6. c5
{ White takes the bread out of the oven before it's baked and closes things down prematurely.  It's the right idea, but too soon - White needs to develop a bit first before releasing the tension. }
6... g6
{ For simplicity's sake, I suggest going with the same plan as in the other variations - play it simple and put your pieces on their best squares.   We will fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, and possibly bring the other bishop to g5 in one go instead of two, staying flexible.   6...e5  is another possible direction if you're feeling spicy. Let's see an example of what can happen if your opponent allows us to open the centre, striking against their backward d-pawn so early.  7.dxe5  Ng4  8.Qxd5  Be6  insisting White capture our queen, helping us develop.  9.Qxd8+  Rxd8  10.Bg5  Rd7  11.Nf3  Bxc5  the Swiss army knife of chess moves - developing a new piece, preparing to castle, recapturing a pawn, and hitting the weak f2-square with tempo!  12.Bh4  Ngxe5  Black is doing great here and with superior development in an open position, White will need to play accurately to avoid being much worse. }
7. Nf3
{ Play could transpose to one of the 6. Nf3 lines or one of the 6. Bg5 lines, but with the added benefit for Black that the c8-bishop hasn't moved yet, meaning it could potentially go to g4 in one move instead of two.  As we will see, the reason we put the bishop on e6 in the first place is to put pressure on the c4-square and provoke White to play c5. This move is no longer necessary if c5 has already been committed. }
7... Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Ne4 10. Re1
{ A useful developing move.   10.Nxe4  capturing that central knight usually drops the d-pawn after  10...dxe4  11.Nd2  Qxd4   and  10.Be3  allows a cute tactic:  10...Nxc5  11.dxc5  d4  regaining the piece with a pawn fork and great prospects in the open position since White has lost time trying to close it with the move c5. }
10... Bg4
{ Instead of first playing ...Be6, we get to play the busy bishop out to g5 in one go this time! }
11. h3
{ White wants to win the bishop pair, but this doesn't trouble us. It's our dark-squared bishop that shines in the Panov. }
11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 f5
{ A super instructive move! Normally such a move would weaken the e5-square too much, but since the f3-knight has been exchanged, White can't take advantage of this weakness nearly as easily.   If White captures our central steed, we will recapture with the f-pawn and White will have problems down the f-file and with the d4-pawn.   Meanwhile, we have plans of breaking with a well-timed ...e5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Panov: 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ You may recognize this position from the Exchange Variation, but White has another option on move four that we haven't covered. }
4. c4
{ When White takes in the centre then immediately strikes against our centre, it's called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, named after two Grandmasters who championed this line in the mid-20th century.    The Panov, as we will henceforth refer to it, is one of the most aggressive and ambitious options for White against the Caro-Kann because of the early pressure against the pawn centre we've built with our first moves. It's a rare guest at amateur level because we're not taught to make so many pawn moves right away. It's much more popular at club-level and beyond. Forget about pawn triangles and long, maneuvering games - White wants to party. But I know exactly how to crash White's party, and even encourage the central structure to close so that we have time to put all our pieces on great squares.   Let's get started. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@ The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6
{ Knights before bishops!  5...e6  is another setup, supporting the centre with a pawn at the cost of our light-squared bishop's active development. I find this approach a bit too passive. I think a different piece belongs on the e6-square! }
6. Bg5
{ A rare choice at amateur level, but it's quite a serious, and logical try! White attacks a defender of the e5-square, indirectly adding even more pressure to our centre. }
6... Be6
{ My recommended setup is revealed. Instead of a pawn adding extra protection to the centre, why not develop a piece?!   Depending on what happens in the centre, often the bishop is later free to move to another active square. Therefore, I like calling it our busy bishop. Not only is it guarding d5, but putting extra pressure on White's c4-pawn! This variation is gaining traction at top level, scoring quite well! I can guarantee many of your opponents will be surprised to see this, and will not know how to properly respond, and if they do, they'll need to burn a lot of clock time thinking it over. }
7. Bxf6
{ Another logical response - White is physically removing a defender of our centre from the board. }
7... exf6
{ I prefer taking with the e-pawn when our bishop can quickly come out and the king can safely castle short.   7...gxf6  is also fully playable, but leads to more dynamic play than is necessary.   Now because of the open g-file, neither side's king will know what to do with itself for the rest of the game. There may be variations later in the middlegame when taking with the g-pawn is best, but whenever White captures early in the opening, let's keep our kingside intact. }
8. c5
{ Players with a good positional sense will push the c-pawn ahead, relieving the pressure and taking space.  8.cxd5  The most popular way to play at lower levels - amateurs can't resist taking stuff! Let's take a quick look at what happens if White keeps taking stuff.  Bxd5  To take is a mistake is true now, and it's true in the mainline as well, which we will see later. White is now left with an isolated pawn which can be an target for our pieces.  9.Nxd5  Unsurprisingly once again, the capture is the most common move, and this time it's a losing mistake.  Qxd5  One of the problems with capturing everything in sight is that often it helps the other side bring out their pieces. Here we have two pieces out; White has zero!  10.Nf3  Bb4+  A very disruptive check! Forcing an uncomfortable pin, and now we are winning material by force.  11.Nd2  O-O-O  The d4-pawn is small fish. Since White is lagging in development, let's target the king by preparing a rook check on e8!  12.Be2  The only way for White to even attempt to escape the centre alive!  Qxg2  Not so fast! Now the king is doomed.  13.Bf3  Attacking the queen and defending the rook, but leaving the king wide open...  Rhe8+  The house is falling - time for White to resign. }
8... g6
{ When the pawn pushes ahead to c5, that's your cue to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop. It will sit nicely on g7, eyeing White'sbackward d-pawn. }
9. Bb5 Bg7 10. Nf3
{ White's pieces look active, but it's hard to find something productive to do with them.   This is one of the reasons I love this setup. We have clear plans and often White struggles to find any. }
10... Bg4
{ The busy bishop has done its job on d5, provoking White's c-pawn into coming forward. Now that the tension is released in the centre, suddenly the bishop finds greener pastures. Someday the bishop will trade itself for the knight, removing a defender of d4! This redeployment of the busy bishop is one of the main plans to remember! We could castle here instead, but then maybe White would play h3, preventing this plan. }
11. O-O O-O
{ Now that our pieces are where we want them, we can castle and start thinking about the next phase.   Oh yeah, and because the c6 knight is no longer pinned, we have a little threat of taking on f3, and if Qxf3, ...Nxd4. }
12. Be2
{ White could choose to keep the bishop, but we continue to add pressure...  12.Bxc6  White may also opt to just take the knight, but after  bxc6  our centre is strong, and it's much easier for us to target White's backward d-pawn than it is for White to target our backward c-pawn.   Additionally, we have the open b-file for a rook and the bishop pair. Black couldn't possibly hope for more. }
12... f5
{ We don't need to rush into 12...Bxf3  and taking on d4. Remember, our d-pawn is also weak! Better to keep the pressure for now and improve our other pieces by putting a rook on the e-file, and perhaps we can develop the other one along the b-file via ...Rab8 and ...b6, undermining White's advanced pawn.    Black is a bit better and can dictate the pace of the game. }
