{ A rare choice at amateur level, but it's quite a serious, and logical try! White attacks a defender of the e5-square, indirectly adding even more pressure to our centre. }
6... Be6
{ My recommended setup is revealed. Instead of a pawn adding extra protection to the centre, why not develop a piece?!   Depending on what happens in the centre, often the bishop is later free to move to another active square. Therefore, I like calling it our busy bishop. Not only is it guarding d5, but putting extra pressure on White's c4-pawn! This variation is gaining traction at top level, scoring quite well! I can guarantee many of your opponents will be surprised to see this, and will not know how to properly respond, and if they do, they'll need to burn a lot of clock time thinking it over. }
7. a3
{ This is the old mainline in the 6. Bg5 variation. White makes it clear queenside expansion is on their agenda.    In a galaxy far, far away, White wants to make a passed pawn on the queenside and use it to win in the endgame.  In my mind, while it's something to bear in mind, our central and kingside counterplay is formidable. }
7... g6 { Our fianchetto setup is perfectly adequate. } 8. Bxf6 exf6
{ White prefers taking on f6 before a bishop lands on g7. } 9. c5 Bg7 10. Bb5
{ White needs to develop, and this is the natural developing scheme, followed by Ne2.   10.b4  is premature, as White is completely undeveloped on the kingside. To give you an idea how things could go south, here's one variation:  10...O-O  11.b5  Nxd4  12.Qxd4  f5  The threats of ...Qa5, ...d4, and ...Re8 ideas give Black a crushing attack.  It wouldn't be a bad idea to investigate from here on your own to develop your attacking intuition. }
10... O-O 11. Nge2
{ 11.Nf3  always allows our busy bishop to find a new role on the g4-square.  11...Bg4 }
11... f5 12. O-O Qf6
{ White still hasn't found the time to start their queenside pawn storm. Black threatens to win a pawn, so in all likelihood, the c6-knight will be captured, opening the b-file for a rook, thereby making it even more unlikely for White's pawnstorm to work.   I think Black is slightly better with plans using the kingside pawn majority by pushing ahead with ...f4-f3, and maybe one day, ...g4. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Panov: 6.Bg5 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ You may recognize this position from the Exchange Variation, but White has another option on move four that we haven't covered. }
4. c4
{ When White takes in the centre then immediately strikes against our centre, it's called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, named after two Grandmasters who championed this line in the mid-20th century.    The Panov, as we will henceforth refer to it, is one of the most aggressive and ambitious options for White against the Caro-Kann because of the early pressure against the pawn centre we've built with our first moves. It's a rare guest at amateur level because we're not taught to make so many pawn moves right away. It's much more popular at club-level and beyond. Forget about pawn triangles and long, maneuvering games - White wants to party. But I know exactly how to crash White's party, and even encourage the central structure to close so that we have time to put all our pieces on great squares.   Let's get started. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@ The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6
{ Knights before bishops!  5...e6  is another setup, supporting the centre with a pawn at the cost of our light-squared bishop's active development. I find this approach a bit too passive. I think a different piece belongs on the e6-square! }
6. Bg5
{ A rare choice at amateur level, but it's quite a serious, and logical try! White attacks a defender of the e5-square, indirectly adding even more pressure to our centre. }
6... Be6
{ My recommended setup is revealed. Instead of a pawn adding extra protection to the centre, why not develop a piece?!   Depending on what happens in the centre, often the bishop is later free to move to another active square. Therefore, I like calling it our busy bishop. Not only is it guarding d5, but putting extra pressure on White's c4-pawn! This variation is gaining traction at top level, scoring quite well! I can guarantee many of your opponents will be surprised to see this, and will not know how to properly respond, and if they do, they'll need to burn a lot of clock time thinking it over. }
7. Nf3
{ Let's see what would happen if White decides not to part with the bishop pair right away, and continues developing. }
7... g6
{ Continuing with our usual setup. If you think you're winning a pawn with  7...dxc4  8.Bxf6  will be a cold shower for you, when you no longer have enough defenders of the d5-square to prevent a fork!  exf6  9.d5  Black is losing material. }
8. c5
{ This really is the only way to continue that pretends to claim an advantage. }
8... Bg7
{ White has generously allowed us time to fianchetto. Now anytime White takes the knight, we will recapture with the bishop. I think White is mixing plans here. If the bishop wasn't going to take our knight, why is it on g5?   8...Ne4  is also very strong, and note that it's rarely good for White to take this knight as after  9.Nxe4  dxe4  We are able to remove a defender of the d4-pawn, and in this case, win it!  10.Ne5  Qxd4  However, I'm sticking to my philosophy of developing a new piece when given the choice. }
9. Bb5
{ Get used to White's light-squared bishop coming out to this square; there's not really a more active square for it.  But in reality, it's more of a defensive move since it aims to trade off one of our attackers of the d4-pawn. }
9... O-O
{ Castling the king to safety and unpinning the knight as soon as possible. }
10. O-O Ne4
{ If the knight survives, we love hopping it into the centre, especially in this line when it also comes with an attack on the bishop. }
11. Be3
{ White admits they made a mistake by forgetting to capture our knight on f6, and decides to put the bishop on a more passive square.   11.Nxe4  is always a mistake in view of  dxe4  12.Nd2  Nxd4  dropping an important central pawn. }
11... Bg4
{ This is sort of a 'best-case scenario' for Black. White hasn't blundered, but they've allowed us to achieve everything we want including repositioning both our knight and busy bishop to active posts. }
12. h3 Bxf3 { If we're encouraged to take the knight, we take it! } 13. gxf3
Nxc5
{ A great example of tactics favouring active pieces. We can temporarily sacrifice a piece in order to open the position, which favours us since White's king is so exposed. }
14. dxc5 d4
{ One way or another we will win our piece back, bring our rooks to the centre, and play with confidence that we are much better in any endgame @@StartBracket@@assuming White doesn't get checkmated before then!@@EndBracket@@ }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Simon Williams vs. Jonah Willow, Hastings, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

{ We've got a good one for you here! This is an all-British showdown between my friend, Simon Williams, A.K.A. the Ginger GM, and young and promising master, Jonah Willow who is still climbing the ranks. In this game, Simon finds himself on the wrong side of my recommended system against the Panov-Botvinnik Attack and is checkmated by force in only 25 moves @@StartBracket@@Sorry, Simon!!@@EndBracket@@. }
1. Nf3 c5
{ What is this?! It's certainly not a Caro-Kann.  In chess, we havetranspositions, which means that you can sometimes arrive at the same position from a variety of move-orders, or even from completely different openings! Simon likes to mix it up with the White pieces - his favourites are @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.d4  , @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.c4  @@StartBracket@@as seen in his Chessable course, The Iron English, or even  @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.Nf3  which he chose for this game, keeping it flexible with his pawns. }
2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 g6
{ At this point, it looks like some kind of Symmetrical English, but a few moves later, we will arrive at familiar territory. }
4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 Nc6 7. Bg5 Be6
{ Do you recognize it now? :@@EndBracket@@   The star of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack chapter, our busy bishop makes its initial appearance on the e6-square where it:   A@@EndBracket@@ develops a piece   B@@EndBracket@@ defends the centre   C@@EndBracket@@ puts pressure on White's centre  This position is actually more commonly reached through move-orders similar to the one we see in this game, not from a Caro-Kann. This works in our favour since 1. e4 players will be even less likely to know this position. }
8. c5
{ With Willow's last move, he asked Simon the question, 'How are you going to handle the central tension, because one day I might want to capture that pawn on c4!' Simon, probably caught slightly off guard, answers the question incorrectly by advancing the pawn.    You'll recall the critical mainlines of this chapter involve this pawn advance, but not here! White is mixing plans. The point of Bg5 was to add pressure to Black's centre. Now that the pressure is released, the bishop for knight trade no longer makes sense for White. Willow masterfully takes advantage of this.   Let's see how. }
8... Bg7
{ 8...Ne4  right away is also quite strong, but Jonah follows the move recommended in the course, calmly developing. ...Ne4 is coming in any case. }
9. Bb5
{ If given another move, Simon probably had Ne5 in mind, with pressure on c6, but there's no time for this. }
9... Ne4
{ A well-timed move before castling, preventing Ne5 as the bishop on g5 would hang and unleashing our bishop against d4. Ne4 gains in strength when there's a bishop on g5 and if we're allowed to capture that bishop, I recommend doing so. }
10. O-O
{ Please note that  10.Nxe4  is rarely a viable capture for White because after  10...dxe4  the knight, a key defender of White's center, is kicked away.  11.Nd2  Qxd4  and Black would win a critical pawn. }
10... O-O
{ Although I would have grabbed that bishop, I can't fault Willow for castling!   10...Nxg5  would be my choice, grabbing the bishop pair. After  11.Nxg5  Bd7  White needs to defend d4 somehow and after a move like  12.Nf3  Bg4  We have a dream position with two bishops and sustained pressure on d4. }
11. Be3
{ Simon decides to hold onto the bishop, but has to spend a move doing it! }
11... Bg4
{ This gives his young opponent, who is probably smelling blood right about now, the chance to repurpose the busy bishop with a pin, adding more indirect pressure to d4. If White does nothing about it, we could potentially take that knight and if the queen takes, win the d-pawn. }
12. Bxc6
{ Very logical - decreasing the pressure on d4. You should be starting to get a sense of how logically play flows from both sides in this opening. I want to stress that when you're deciding on your moves, you should be relying less on your memory for the moves, and rather reciting the narrative of the position to yourself @@StartBracket@@silently, or else you might get in trouble in a tournament@@EndBracket@@. }
12... bxc6 13. h3
{ The pin on the knight is uncomfortable, so Simon chooses not to tolerate it any longer, but from this point on, Jonah plays brilliant chess, taking advantage of White's small mistakes.   The all-knowing engine prefers  13.Qa4  which threatens c6, but allows  13...Bxf3  14.gxf3  Nxc3  15.bxc3  and White's pawn structure is ruined, but at least d4 isn't a concern anymore, and White has queenside counterplay. In any case, it's understandable not to go down this route if Simon felt he had another choice. }
13... Bxf3
{ The correct decision, giving back the bishop pair, but suddenly Willow finds himself with an initiative against the white kingside!   You might wonder, why not keep the bishop pair with a move like  13...Be6  But now Black has also spent multiple tempi moving the bishop back and forth which means there's no initiative for Black. When your opponent plays slow moves, or a combination of moves that don't fit the needs of the position, the typical way to exploit it is to play quickly and attack!  14.Bf4 }
14. Qxf3 f5
{ The only move for an advantage, activating the f8-rook where it stands and threatening to push further ahead with ...f4, deflecting the defender of the d4-pawn. Note it was important to capture the knight on the previous move for this idea to work, otherwise White would have another defender on the kingside. }
15. Qd1
{ An understandable move, getting the queen off of the file of our rook and also defending d4. But this allows the f-pawn to march!   15.Rad1  f4  16.Bc1 }
15... f4 16. Bc1 f3
{ Not the engine's top choice, nor second, nor third. But from a practical perspective, I'd argue it may be the best. Black goes for the throat and, in effect, slices the kingside in half when it becomes incredibly difficult to defend the lone king. }
17. g3
{ The most natural move, keeping the kingside closed, but also the losing move.  Even though White's problems started far before now, after this move, the presence of thewedge pawn on f3 means White's king is a sitting duck for Black's pieces.   For the rest of the game, pay attention to how each move is designed to bring pieces closer to the white king and take advantage of the weaknesses left behind by White's pawn moves. If White hadn't pushed h3 earlier, the kingside structure would be more solid, but here the h3-square is critically weak.   17.gxf3  would be equally miserable since after  17...Nf6  To say nothing of the pawn structure and exposed king, the knight can be rerouted via h5-f4 and with ...Qd7 on the agenda, the h3-pawn is hard to defend.   The cold-blooded engine thinks  17.Qe1  targetting the knight on e4 is enough to hold the position, when after  17...fxg2  18.Kxg2  The king seems super exposed, but it's hard for Black to bring any more attacking forces to bear, especially if the e4-knight is traded. But once again, playing this way for a human is incredibly difficult and even here, White would not be out of the woods.   17.Nxe4  would be another attempt to survive the kingside onslaught - removing one of the attackers. But from a positional perspective, nobody wants to allow such pawns after  17...dxe4  when Black seems to have everything - pressure on d4, the open b-file, and even a continued kingside attack.  Still, it was better than the move played. }
17... Qd7 { Developing a piece and attacking the weakness. Simple chess! } 18.
Kh2 Rf5
{ Another 'developing' move - bringing another piece into the attack. Eventually, White will need to make another pawn move in order to defend the king. }
19. h4
{ Necessary, but now the g4-square is available for the knight, and I'm willing to bet from this point @@StartBracket@@and maybe even earlier@@EndBracket@@ Willow had a devious sacrificial mating idea in mind. }
19... Nf6 20. Be3
{ What else? The f3-pawn completely strands the white king - disallowing any forces over to help. }
20... Ng4+ 21. Kg1 Raf8
{ A great move! Involving the last piece in the attack.  Here it serves a defensive purpose. Willow wants to swing the f5-rook over to h5 but first he needs to make sure the f3-pawn is defended. Wonderful teamwork by the pieces - every piece doing its part. }
22. Re1 Rh5 23. Qd3 Rxh4
{ The only thing that stands between Black's army and the white king is the white pawns. A rook is quite valuable, but checkmate ends the game. So naturally, Willow destroys the king's shelter, and after }
24. gxh4 Qc7
{ The threat of Qh2 and forced checkmate is impossible to stop.    The key lessons to take away from this one are:   A@@EndBracket@@ When you're considering which moves to make, it's more important to understand the logical narrative behind moves and what purpose the moves serve in the position than only memorizing moves.    B@@EndBracket@@ If your opponent plays slow moves in the opening, as long as you're developed yourself, you should look for ways to start an initiative, putting more pressure on your opponent's position. In this game, it was the decision to take the knight on f3 with the bishop followed by pushing the f-pawn up the board. Starting an initiative is a great opportunity for creativity in chess, so you should welcome it with excitement!   C@@EndBracket@@ A pawn near the enemy king on the 3rd or 6th ranks can be super dangerous!   D@@EndBracket@@ When attacking the king, you will often need to sacrifice material to break through the king's shelter and deliver checkmate. }
