1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ You may recognize this position from the Exchange Variation, but White has another option on move four that we haven't covered. }
4. c4
{ When White takes in the centre then immediately strikes against our centre, it's called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, named after two Grandmasters who championed this line in the mid-20th century.    The Panov, as we will henceforth refer to it, is one of the most aggressive and ambitious options for White against the Caro-Kann because of the early pressure against the pawn centre we've built with our first moves. It's a rare guest at amateur level because we're not taught to make so many pawn moves right away. It's much more popular at club-level and beyond. Forget about pawn triangles and long, maneuvering games - White wants to party. But I know exactly how to crash White's party, and even encourage the central structure to close so that we have time to put all our pieces on great squares.   Let's get started. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@ The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6
{ Knights before bishops!  5...e6  is another setup, supporting the centre with a pawn at the cost of our light-squared bishop's active development. I find this approach a bit too passive. I think a different piece belongs on the e6-square! }
6. Bg5
{ A rare choice at amateur level, but it's quite a serious, and logical try! White attacks a defender of the e5-square, indirectly adding even more pressure to our centre. }
6... Be6
{ My recommended setup is revealed. Instead of a pawn adding extra protection to the centre, why not develop a piece?!   Depending on what happens in the centre, often the bishop is later free to move to another active square. Therefore, I like calling it our busy bishop. Not only is it guarding d5, but putting extra pressure on White's c4-pawn! This variation is gaining traction at top level, scoring quite well! I can guarantee many of your opponents will be surprised to see this, and will not know how to properly respond, and if they do, they'll need to burn a lot of clock time thinking it over. }
7. Be2
{ White is toying with the idea of putting a bishop on f3 instead of a knight, maximising pressure on d5. It's a serious try, and because of the extra pressure on our centre, forces us to adapt!   7.c5  doesn't make much sense since Bg5 was designed to put pressure on our centre, but now there's none. Suddenly the White bishop doesn't belong on g5 and after  Ne4  Black is completely fine and may even have an initiative as White needs to move the bishop again to avoid losing thebishop pair. }
7... Qa5
{ The move to remember!  We pin the knight and clear the d8-square for our rook to add extra support to d5 if needed.   It's not advisable to follow up with our usual plan.  7...g6  8.Bf3  It's very hard to deal with the pressure on d5.  dxc4  Taking is not an option in view of the fork!  9.d5 }
8. Bf3
{ White has substantial pressure on the centre and can also snap off the f6-knight at any moment. }
8... Rd8
{ So, let's reinforce it further. Now d5 is sufficiently guarded and we are ready to capture the free pawn on c4 if allowed! }
9. Bxf6
{ White ran out of ways to build pressure, so they start to release it. } 9...
exf6 { No need to take with the g-pawn and ruin our king's shelter! } 10. cxd5
Bxd5 11. Bxd5 Rxd5
{ After the dust settles, since White had to release the tension, we are left with better development and a clear target on d4. Black is certainly not worse, a logical outcome in this variation when White spends two moves to bring a bishop to f3. }
