{ The move to remember!  We pin the knight and clear the d8-square for our rook to add extra support to d5 if needed.   It's not advisable to follow up with our usual plan.  7...g6  8.Bf3  It's very hard to deal with the pressure on d5.  dxc4  Taking is not an option in view of the fork!  9.d5 }
8. Nf3
{ White feels like they've accomplished something by coaxing our queen out to the side of the board, so they revert to normal development. }
8... dxc4
{ Since the bishop is no longer able to come to f3, we can safely capture the pawn without worrying about the central fork. }
9. O-O
{ White castles the king to safety and unpins the c3-knight, which means White now may be thinking about capturing on f6 and going for the d5 fork.   Let's not allow any funny business. }
9... Rd8
{ The perfect square for this rook, lining up against the enemy queen and preventing any d5 pushes. }
10. Qc1 { Probably the best move, sidestepping our rook's gaze. } 10... h6
{ Since there's still a bishop on g5, at this point I like to politely ask what it's doing in our house. Nothing is stopping us from further expansion with ...g5 if provoked. }
11. Bxf6 { The bishop came to g5 for a reason! } 11... gxf6
{ SPARRING POSITION   Whether to capture with the g-pawn or e-pawn in this position is a matter of taste. After checking both options, it seems to me our king is perfectly safe behind the three central pawns and the half-open g-file can be a great attacking asset. Whichever direction you prefer, I would suggest sparring in this kind of middlegame position after having sufficiently covered the d5-square.   The way I see this position, White will win back the c-pawn, but has a hard time holding onto the weak d-pawn. So, it feels like White is the side playing with something to prove, or else they may end up down a pawn and/ or on the receiving end of a kingside attack! }
