1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. d4
{ White doesn't need a second invitation to claim the whole center with both pawns. It's the mostprincipled move, and is seen at lower levels with about the same frequency as  2.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@likely transposing to either the Exchange Variation or the Two Knights Variation@@EndBracket@@. }
2... d5
{ Here it is - the point of our first move. We can't let White have all the central fun! }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ You may recognize this position from the Exchange Variation, but White has another option on move four that we haven't covered. }
4. c4
{ When White takes in the centre then immediately strikes against our centre, it's called the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, named after two Grandmasters who championed this line in the mid-20th century.    The Panov, as we will henceforth refer to it, is one of the most aggressive and ambitious options for White against the Caro-Kann because of the early pressure against the pawn centre we've built with our first moves. It's a rare guest at amateur level because we're not taught to make so many pawn moves right away. It's much more popular at club-level and beyond. Forget about pawn triangles and long, maneuvering games - White wants to party. But I know exactly how to crash White's party, and even encourage the central structure to close so that we have time to put all our pieces on great squares.   Let's get started. }
4... Nf6
{ Don't panic! Keep calm and develop. :@@EndBracket@@ The knight supports our central pawn. }
5. Nc3 { White puts even more pressure on our centre. But it's well-defended! }
5... Nc6
{ Knights before bishops!  5...e6  is another setup, supporting the centre with a pawn at the cost of our light-squared bishop's active development. I find this approach a bit too passive. I think a different piece belongs on the e6-square! }
6. Nf3
{ By far the most commonly played move, at all levels. You might call this the four-knights variation.   6.cxd5  Quite a common move at lower levels, releasing the central tension. We're always happy to see White capture a second time on d5!   Note this position can also arise via a Pseudo-Panov move-order, which we will discuss in more depth in thenext chapter. We will take  6...Nxd5  7.Nf3  and now we are careful to put the bishop on f5 instead of g4, after which play could transpose into a super theoretical mainline.  7...Bf5  Black has a healthy position. }
6... Be6
{ I get so excited when it comes time to play this move because of the surprise factor. At lower levels, this move is played a mere 1% of the time!   In this kind of position, you might expect us to pin the knight with  6...Bg4  . That's the most popular way to play, but I like putting it on  e6  here since, compared to the Exchange Variation,  White has more pressure on the centre. This busy bishop is really the star of the show in this chapter. }
7. c5
{ White decides to release the central tension by pushing the pawn one square forward. This is the mainline and probably White's best way to play.  But as we know, we always have that backward d4-pawn to bite on.   7.Ng5  This one is too feisty - the bishop can simply move to safety and the knight can later be kicked back.  7...Bg4  8.f3  Bc8  White's position is significantly compromised by the f3 push. }
7... g6
{ Our standard plan - continuing our kingside development when our bishop belongs on this long diagonal where it eyes the d-pawn. }
8. Bb5
{ 8.Bg5  As we learned in the early Bg5 variations, combining the ideas of Bg5 and c5 doesn't make much sense. The Bishop doesn't belong on g5 if it's not contributing to putting pressure on the centre.  Bg7  On g5, it's only a target to a future ...Ne4, for example. }
8... Bg7 9. Ne5
{ This is an understandable way for White to play since it's a bit difficult to decide what else to do with the pieces. White is trying to make use of the pin on our knight while they still can, but this is one of those cases we learned about in the Exchange Variation chapter where such aggressive, forward moves are arguably only creating the illusion of pressure. }
9... Qc8
{ However, it is important to know how to react. The c6 square needs support, and this is the best way.   We would rather not commit the rook to any particular square yet, while there are concrete problems with ...Qc7.  9...Qc7  would be imprecise in view of  10.Qa4  Bd7  11.Bf4  when it becomes clear the queen has been misplaced. White is now threatening all kinds of nasty discovered attacks such as Nxg6. And we can't meet this threat with  Nh5  because it undefends our central pawn.  12.Nxd5 }
10. Qa4
{ The only logical follow-up if White wants to continue putting pressure on our position @@StartBracket@@even if it is temporary@@EndBracket@@. }
10... Bd7
{ Our busy bishop is needed to defend c6 here. Somebody give this bishop a raise! }
11. O-O O-O
{ SPARRING POSITION   After we castle, the pressure dissolves and we can play ...a6, kicking out a queenside intruder. Of course, White can capture on c6 as many times as they like - it only helps our position as reduced material would only highlight White's d4 weakness.   I like this as a sparring position so that you can practice dealing with multiple white pieces in your house. }
