{ This explains White's decision to take our knight, securing the d4-pawn for now. }
11... bxc6 12. h3 Bxf3
{ Removing a defender of the central dark squares is a noble fate for our hard-working bishop! }
13. Qxf3 e5
{ A super thematic break in this structure, and one you should always look out for, challenging the base of White's central pawn duo. }
14. dxe5
{ 14.Rxe5  is not viable since after  Nd7  the rook must move and  15.Re2  Bxd4  we are able to pick up White's critical d-pawn and likely also the c-pawn. }
14... Nd7
{ Black is comfortably better in this position with a protected passed pawn on d5, open files for both rooks, and recapturing on e5 next. }
