[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Panov-Botvinnik Attack"]
[Black "Claus Seyfried vs. Jovanka Houska, Isle of Man, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Be6 7. c5
{ White decides to release the central tension by pushing the pawn one square forward. This is the mainline and probably White's best way to play.  But as we know, we always have that backward d4-pawn to bite on.   7.Ng5  This one is too feisty - the bishop can simply move to safety and the knight can later be kicked back.  7...Bg4  8.f3  Bc8  White's position is significantly compromised by the f3 push. }
7... g6 8. Bb5 Bg7 9. Ne5 Qc8
{ This is another game played in the same Isle of Man tournament as the one against Jovana Rapport - a triumphant one for the Caro-Kann!   This position can be found in the course as when White piles up pressure on c6, ...Qc8 is an important move to remember.   9...Qc7  10.Qa4  Bd7   10...Rc8  11.Bf4  Nh5  12.Nxc6  Nxf4  13.Nxa7+  11.Bf4  Nh5  12.Nxd5 }
10. Qa4 Bd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 e6 13. b4
{ Better for White would be to develop with  13.Bf4  intending to recapture on e5 with the bishop, and after  13...Nh5  14.Bd2  Black's knight is misplaced, especially if I want to pursue the same idea as in the game:  14...Nxe5  15.dxe5  Here, of course, there's no time for ...a6 since the sidelined knight no longer defends the d7-bishop. }
13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 a6 15. Bxd7
{ 15.exf6  axb5  16.Qb3  Bxf6  would leave Black up a pawn with a strong centre and two bishops! }
15... Nxd7 16. Bb2 a5
{ Now I was able to activate my a8-rook where it stands with tempo on the queen, also undermining White's control of the c5-pawn.   16...Bxe5  would allow a tactical shot.  17.Nxd5  exd5  18.Bxe5  when our centre is destroyed. }
17. bxa5 Nxc5
{ In addition to attacking the queen, ...Nd3 is a pretty serious threat, which explains why my opponent abandoned the a-pawn. }
18. Qd4 Rxa5 19. Rac1 b6
{ A nice consolidating move, defending the knight and White doesn't have compensation for the pawn. You could say that I have the material and the compensation, with great piece activity. }
20. a4 Qa6 21. Ba3 Nb3
{ A fork on the queen and rook. Both sides are giving up an exchange here, but my activity is far superior in the end. }
22. Qd1 Nxc1 23. Bxf8 Bxf8 24. Qxc1 Qc4 25. h3 Rc5
{ White has no good way to save the pinned knight, so he resigned.   This, in my opinion, nicely shows how quickly things can backfire when White plays the most aggressive-looking moves, and the Caro-Kann, like a coiled spring, unleashes its spectacular energy on the opponent. }
