[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pseudo-Panov Attack"]
[Black "Pseudo-Panov Attack Overview"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. c4
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 2% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@    Pseudo-Panov Attack: Naturally, pushing the e and c-pawns so early creates permanent weaknesses, namely the d4-square. Most often, both of these pawns disappear from the board, leaving anIQP behind.   Some players prefer the open positions that result where active piece play reigns supreme.  In this opening, like the Panov-Botvinnik Attack, I'm recommending a kingside fianchetto setup with an emphasis on putting pressure on White's isolated pawn. }
2... d5
{ White's pawns haven't stopped our Caro advance; in fact, they've made it stronger! }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6
{ White's idea is to either try to hold onto the extra d-pawn or make us spend an extra move to capture it. }
5. Nc3
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 64%@@EndBracket@@   The main move, giving back the pawn in favour of rapid development.   5.Qa4+  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 3%@@EndBracket@@   One of two early checks which aims to disrupt our development and hold onto the d-pawn for as long as possible.  5...Nbd7  6.Nc3  g6  If you make sure to block with the knight and quickly castle afterwords, you're in good shape.   5.Bb5+  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 8%@@EndBracket@@ Another check after which White is really banking on us blocking with the bishop.  5...Nbd7  6.Nc3  a6  7.Ba4  b5  Most often, the bishop ends up misplaced on b5, helping us expand on the queenside and surround the d-pawn. }
5... Nxd5 6. Nf3
{ Maybe the most critical way to play - giving back the pawn for rapid development.   6.Bb5+  A check that arguably comes a move too late.  6...Bd7  This time, we can block with the bishop.   6.d4  g6  White can, at any time, push the pawn to d4, when it will be a target for our fianchettoed bishop.   6.Nxd5  Qxd5  The most popular variation at the amateur level, but it helps us develop. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5
{ 7.Bc4  Active development.  7...Nb6  We will follow up with our usual kingside fianchetto and White will most likely need to push d4 in order to finish development, where it is an easier target. }
7... g6 8. Qa4 Qd6
{ White can pile up on the pinned c6-knight, but we can defend with the queen. Most likely we White will capture on c6, giving up the bishop pair in order to give us an isolated c-pawn.   My Five Lifelines:   A@@EndBracket@@ We will almost invariably fianchetto on the kingside and quickly castle short.   B@@EndBracket@@ In the Qa4+ and Bb5+ variations, remember to block the check with the knight.   C@@EndBracket@@ Sometimes it's possible to win the isolated pawn on d4 by removing the defender, most often the knight on f3. Otherwise, try to maintain control of the blockading d5-square and put pressure on the pawn.  D@@EndBracket@@ In the open positions that result after all central pawns have come off the board, be especially tactically astute!    E@@EndBracket@@ If White's pawn advances to d5, a further d6 push could be dangerous. It's important to calculate in this circumstance. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pseudo-Panov Attack"]
[Black "🤺 Pseudo-Panov: 5.Qa4+ #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with 2. d4, and only later pushes the c-pawn. If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!    In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a sound gambit, but for simplicity's sake, I recommend cxd5, playing the same way regardless. }
3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Qa4+
{ Bringing out the queen before any other piece violates the rules we're taught as beginners, which probably explains why this move is played only 3% of the time in this position. But, there is a method to White's madness.   GM Baadur Jobava enjoys this specific way of playing against the Caro-Kann and it seems to be a favourite weapon of blitz specialist, GM Alexander Bortnyk. They want to:   A@@EndBracket@@ slow down our development by luring our knight to d7 and   B@@EndBracket@@ hold on to the d-pawn for as long as possible. }
5... Nbd7
{ Remember to block with the knight! Yes, it temporarily hems in our light-squared bishop, but it turns out to be the most flexible move. After we castle, it can move out of the way to b6, or the bishop can be fianchettoed on b7 with pressure on d5.   5...Bd7  is known to be an inferior way to block the check since after  6.Qb3  White holds onto the d-pawn and claims the d7-bishop is misplaced. It's instructive to note that the engine's favourite continuation for Black would be to gambit a pawn with  e6  when after something like  7.dxe6  Bxe6  8.Bc4  Bxc4  9.Qxc4  White is up a clean pawn.   Ok, that pawn happens to be the weak d-pawn, so a draw is still the most likely result, but I see no reason to give a pawn in the opening. }
6. Nc3 g6
{ We will win back the d-pawn eventually, but the first order of business is to castle.  6...a6  with the idea of ...b5, hitting the queen and preparing to fianchetto the bishop, is a flawed plan.  7.Nf3  b5  8.Bxb5  Oops, the pawn is pinned to the rook! }
7. Nf3 Bg7
{ This bishop is a monster along the a1-h8 diagonal as it has many targets and cannot be obstructed by a wall of pawns. }
8. Bc4
{ The most active square for the bishop, and adding defense to the d-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nb6
{ Now that we're castled, the knight is free to move, and move it shall.   Remember this maneuver! }
10. Qb3 Nxc4 { Depriving White of the bishop pair. } 11. Qxc4 b6
{ SPARRING POSITION   Now, at long last, we're ready to go ...Bb7 and win back the d-pawn. In the resulting position, White will still have an isolated d-pawn. With no weaknesses in Black's camp, Black is better. I recommend practicing playing against the IQP from this position so that you not only know that Black is better, but also feel it.   To conclude this Qa4+ line: White's idea is to hold onto the pawn.... but they can't. After we castle kingside, whether by ...Nb6, ...b6 or even ...a6 + ...b5, the pawn is doomed and White's isolated pawn will serve as a sour reminder of White's positionally dubious opening. }
