1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with 2. d4, and only later pushes the c-pawn. If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!    In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a sound gambit, but for simplicity's sake, I recommend cxd5, playing the same way regardless. }
3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Qa4+
{ Bringing out the queen before any other piece violates the rules we're taught as beginners, which probably explains why this move is played only 3% of the time in this position. But, there is a method to White's madness.   GM Baadur Jobava enjoys this specific way of playing against the Caro-Kann and it seems to be a favourite weapon of blitz specialist, GM Alexander Bortnyk. They want to:   A@@EndBracket@@ slow down our development by luring our knight to d7 and   B@@EndBracket@@ hold on to the d-pawn for as long as possible. }
5... Nbd7
{ Remember to block with the knight! Yes, it temporarily hems in our light-squared bishop, but it turns out to be the most flexible move. After we castle, it can move out of the way to b6, or the bishop can be fianchettoed on b7 with pressure on d5.   5...Bd7  is known to be an inferior way to block the check since after  6.Qb3  White holds onto the d-pawn and claims the d7-bishop is misplaced. It's instructive to note that the engine's favourite continuation for Black would be to gambit a pawn with  e6  when after something like  7.dxe6  Bxe6  8.Bc4  Bxc4  9.Qxc4  White is up a clean pawn.   Ok, that pawn happens to be the weak d-pawn, so a draw is still the most likely result, but I see no reason to give a pawn in the opening. }
6. Nc3 g6
{ We will win back the d-pawn eventually, but the first order of business is to castle.  6...a6  with the idea of ...b5, hitting the queen and preparing to fianchetto the bishop, is a flawed plan.  7.Nf3  b5  8.Bxb5  Oops, the pawn is pinned to the rook! }
7. Nf3 Bg7
{ This bishop is a monster along the a1-h8 diagonal as it has many targets and cannot be obstructed by a wall of pawns. }
8. Bc4
{ The most active square for the bishop, and adding defense to the d-pawn. }
8... O-O 9. d3
{ This is the start of one of the mainlines of the Pseudo-Panov, frequently employed in online games by the blitz specialist, Olexandr Bortnyk. }
9... a6
{ The point of d3 is that it discourages ...Nb6 and capturing on c4 with the knight, as it would help repair White's structure. So, we will hit the bishop a different way. We are preparing ...b5 at the right moment. }
10. Qa3
{ White steps out of any ...b5 tactics.   10.O-O  blunders a well-known tactic.  10...b5  which at first sight looks impossible because of the hanging a8-rook.  11.Bxb5  Nb6  The key move, which both attacks the queen and defends the rook, allowing ...axb5 next move no matter what.  12.Qb3  axb5  Black is winning. }
10... b6
{ Patiently developing and arranging support for the a8-rook before pushing ahead with ... b5.  Don't run into   10...b5  when after  11.Bxb5  recapturing on b5 is impossible because of the hanging rook on a8. }
11. O-O Bb7
{ Now the rook is defended, so ...b5 becomes available. Our plan is ...b5, continue to harass the bishop with ...Nc5, and eventually win that d-pawn in the end. }
