{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Bb5+
{ This one is more common than  5.Qa4  ,  but is equally harmless and even easier to play against because the bishop on b5 is even more of a target than the queen on a4. }
5... Nbd7
{ Don't forget to block with the knight, just like after Qa4+.  5... Bd7  would be best if White was forced to exchange bishops, but after   6.Bc4  White gets to hold onto the bishop for longer than they should. }
6. Nc3 { Defending the d-pawn. } 6... a6
{ It's time to ask the b5-bishop to announce its intentions. } 7. Qa4
{ This is the logical follow-up to Bb5, pinning the a-pawn and making it more difficult for difficult for us to develop our c8-bishop. }
7... g6
{ We could go  7...Rb8  instead, reinstating the threat on the bishop, but I prefer just getting on with kingside development. Eventually after we castle, our d7-knight will be free to move and ...Nb6, if allowed, would cause White some problems.    So, I'm not sure we need to spend an extra move sidestepping the pin. }
8. Nf3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O
{ Now ...Nb6 is a big threat with a double attack on the queen and bishop @@StartBracket@@since the knight also defends the a8-rook@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Bxd7 Bxd7
{ We've won the bishop pair with tempo on the queen, and it's only a matter of time before we recapture the d-pawn. }
11. Qb3 Bc8
{ I chose to end the variation here @@StartBracket@@and not the move before@@EndBracket@@ just because this is such a cool backwards move. Our not-so-subtle intention is to play ...b5 @@StartBracket@@or ...b6 if needed@@EndBracket@@, ...Bb7 and take the d5-pawn. }
