2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with 2. d4, and only later pushes the c-pawn. If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!    In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a sound gambit, but for simplicity's sake, I recommend cxd5, playing the same way regardless. }
3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Nc3
{ The main move by far at all levels, following .  5.d4  White can always spend a move to push the d-pawn, but it begs the question, why not go with the proper Panov-Botvinnik Attack? After simple developing moves such as  Nxd5  6.Nc3  g6  we transpose to thevariation where White decides to play d4 on move 6. }
5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
Nxd5
{ This is the start of the most common variation in the Pseudo-Panov Attack. }
6... Qxd5
{ ... which is music to our ears since it helps us bring out her majesty! } 7.
Nf3 Nc6
{ Clearly the best square for the knight. allowing the c8-bishop to develop freely. }
8. Be2 g6 { We're sticking with our kingside fianchetto setup. } 9. O-O Bg7
{ The bishop is a monster along this diagonal, and look at its poor counterpart on c1, in a prison of pawns!   Ok, here's where it gets interesting. }
10. d4
{ 10.Rb1  Can you believe this is the most popular move for White in this position at amateur level? They saw that ...Bg7 puts pressure on b2, and even though it's already defended, felt the need to defend it a second time. But to their horror...  Qxa2  It actually undefends another pawn! Not only that, but the b1-rook is under attack and awkward to defend! White is already busted. I was amused to see this exact variation played a few times on the database.   It really shows that if you simply attack your opponent's undefended pieces or pawns, they are often so consumed with defending them that they lose sight of everything else.  Remember to always try to:  A@@EndBracket@@ put pressure on your opponent's pieces.  B@@EndBracket@@ ask your opponent questions - they could get them wrong. }
10... O-O 11. Be3 Be6
{ SPARRING POSITION   Here we see another example of a dream IQP position for Black as we have maximal pressure on d4 and there's not much dynamic potential in White's passive setup. This is a perfect sparring position because you can reach it from many different move orders, or even different openings! }
