2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with 2. d4, and only later pushes the c-pawn. If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!    In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a sound gambit, but for simplicity's sake, I recommend cxd5, playing the same way regardless. }
3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Nc3
{ The main move by far at all levels, following .  5.d4  White can always spend a move to push the d-pawn, but it begs the question, why not go with the proper Panov-Botvinnik Attack? After simple developing moves such as  Nxd5  6.Nc3  g6  we transpose to thevariation where White decides to play d4 on move 6. }
5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
d4
{ White thinks it better late than never to push d4, but this tends to resemble typical IQP positions where White has no reason to claim an advantage. }
6... g6
{ As in all IQP positions in this chapter, I prefer fianchettoing the bishop on g7 to add maximal pressure to the d4-pawn. }
7. Qb3
{ Let's now examine one of the few ways White can try to play actively in this structure. As always, the more White trades, the more it highlights the d4 weakness.  7.Nxd5  Qxd5  8.Nf3  Bg7  White is in store for a long, passive defense. }
7... Nb6
{ We would rather not capture the knight on c3, helping White defend their own centre, nor play something ...e6 when after Nxd5, we would need to eventually recapture on d5 with a pawn. So, the simple retreat is very effective, still maintaining influence over the critical d5-square. }
8. Bb5+ Bd7
{ This kind of check is common at lower levels of play, but it's really only a check. }
9. Nf3 Bg7 10. Ne5
{ If White decides to take now, the best recapture would be  10.Bxd7+  Qxd7  since the knight's dream home is on c6 where it puts pressure on White's centre.  11.Ne5  Qf5  The queen is happy on f5 and White now needs to respond to the threat of losing a pawn after ...Bxe5. }
10... O-O
{ Since any capture on d7 helps us develop, we can simply castle and avoid the pin.    Now we may be threatening a move like ...Be6. }
11. Nxd7 N8xd7 12. Be3 { Defending the d-pawn. } 12... Nf6
{ I sound like a broken record, but it really is a running theme in this chapter: Black is slightly better due to the weakness on d4. We have dynamic options of ...Ng4, ...Nfd5, and improving moves such as ...e6, ...Qe7, and bringing the rooks to the centre. }
