5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
Nf3 Nc6 { White develops both knights, and we do the same. } 7. d4
{ With the move d4, White brings the game back into proper Panov waters. } 7...
Bf5
{ Because of the blockade on White's IQP on d5, Black already has a comfortable position, and we would like to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn-chain, but it's important to put it on f5, not g4, where the game would transpose directly into a mainline of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack played often at master-level. }
8. Bc4
{ With the bishop on f5 instead of g4 @@StartBracket@@like in the mainline of the Panov at master-level,  8.Qb3  doesn't have the same effect. In fact, it's simply a blunder in view of  8...Ndb4  when White is hard-pressed to parry the threat of ...Nc2+ winning an exchange. }
8... e6
{ White attacked d5, so we defend, opening the diagonal for our dark-squared bishop to join the game.   You may be wondering, why isn't  8...Ndb4  working this time? Because we're not developing! After a sequence such as  9.O-O  Nc2  10.d5  Not White's only move, but the best one to punish our greed.  10...Nb8   @@StartBracket@@  10...Na5  11.Bb5  would lose the queen!@@EndBracket@@  11.Nh4  Nxa1  12.Nxf5  our knight is trapped in the corner and will be lost after which we would be down material. }
9. O-O Be7 { Simple development. } 10. Re1 Nb6
{ Now that we are mostly developed and it's a convenient moment, I prefer not allowing White to capture on d5, giving us an IQP as well. }
11. Bb3 O-O
{ White's best course of action is likely to push 12.d5  when after several exchanges, neither side should have any claim for an advantage.   However, if they do nothing, our next moves can be ...Bf6, putting pressure on the centre, and maybe even ...Nb4 can be annoying for White to meet. }
