{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. c4
{ This is the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   In the pure Panov-Botvinnik Attack, White takes the full centre with 2. d4, and only later pushes the c-pawn. If you're looking at White's first two moves and they look a bit funny to you, your intuition is right on the money!    In this position, the most likely scenario is that both White's e-pawn and c-pawn get exchanged for our c and d-pawn. But, it's not what's traded that matters - it's what remains on the board. After such a trade, White would be left with anIQP which could easily be a weakness.   While most IQP positions are playable, I would contest it's too early to commit to such a structure. Therefore, as long as we play good, standard moves, we should have no problems at all, and often White is the one under pressure. }
2... d5 3. cxd5
{ 3.exd5  This capture perhaps allows us the extra option of  3...Nf6  ,  a sound gambit, but for simplicity's sake, I recommend cxd5, playing the same way regardless. }
3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Nc3
{ The main move by far at all levels, following .  5.d4  White can always spend a move to push the d-pawn, but it begs the question, why not go with the proper Panov-Botvinnik Attack? After simple developing moves such as  Nxd5  6.Nc3  g6  we transpose to thevariation where White decides to play d4 on move 6. }
5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
Nf3 Nc6 { White develops both knights, and we do the same. } 7. Bc4
{ This looks like the most active square for the bishop, eyeing the tender f7-square and attacking our knight. }
7... Nb6
{ A fine square for the knight where it still has influence on the d5-square, and gains a tempo on the bishop. }
8. Bb3 g6
{ The fianchetto structure is especially effective against IQP positions not only because the g7-bishop eyes d4, but also because it's harder for White to attack us.   8...Bg4  is completely off-limits because of a tactic that should befamiliar to you from the Classical / Two Knights chapter.  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Ng5+  with a double attack on the king and bishop.  Kg8  11.Qxg4  White is up a pawn with an attack on our king. Bad news!   A reminder: When there's a knight on f3 and bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, think twice before pinning that knight! }
9. d4
{ White should definitely push the pawn to d4 sooner or later. in order to develop their queenside. }
9... Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. Be3
{ A passive post for the bishop, but a post nonetheless. } 11... Bg4
{ Straightforward play: They defend the pawn, we attack it - this time indirectly. }
12. h3
{ White has nothing better than to allow some clarifications.  12.d5  would allow unnecessary pressure on f3 after  Ne5  . }
12... Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxd4 { Operation: take the d-pawn is complete. } 14. Qxb7
Nf5
{ We don't mind trading the b-pawn for White's central pawn.  14...Nxb3  15.axb3  is playable, but I don't like helping White develop the a1-rook down the a-file. }
15. Rfd1 Qc8
{ The position is wide open and anything can happen and the better player will most likely win.  White can't avoid both the queen exchange and ...Nxe3, taking back the bishop pair. }
