3... cxd5 4. exd5
{ The only reasonable move for White.  4.e5  Qa5  would be an Advance Variation, supercharged for Black as White can't even take the full centre due to the pin. }
4... Nf6
{ Resist the urge to recapture immediately with the queen. It's much better to keep her at home for now and centralise our knight! }
5. Nc3
{ The main move by far at all levels, following .  5.d4  White can always spend a move to push the d-pawn, but it begs the question, why not go with the proper Panov-Botvinnik Attack? After simple developing moves such as  Nxd5  6.Nc3  g6  we transpose to thevariation where White decides to play d4 on move 6. }
5... Nxd5 { This time, we are allowed to capture the d5-pawn right away. } 6.
Nf3 Nc6 { White develops both knights, and we do the same. } 7. Bc4
{ This looks like the most active square for the bishop, eyeing the tender f7-square and attacking our knight. }
7... Nb6
{ A fine square for the knight where it still has influence on the d5-square, and gains a tempo on the bishop. }
8. Bb3 g6
{ The fianchetto structure is especially effective against IQP positions not only because the g7-bishop eyes d4, but also because it's harder for White to attack us.   8...Bg4  is completely off-limits because of a tactic that should befamiliar to you from the Classical / Two Knights chapter.  9.Bxf7+  Kxf7  10.Ng5+  with a double attack on the king and bishop.  Kg8  11.Qxg4  White is up a pawn with an attack on our king. Bad news!   A reminder: When there's a knight on f3 and bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal, think twice before pinning that knight! }
9. d4
{ White should definitely push the pawn to d4 sooner or later. in order to develop their queenside. }
9... Bg7 10. d5
{ A risky approach, since the further the pawn advances into our territory, the more vulnerable it can be. }
10... Na5
{ The only productive square for the knight, effectively removing a defender of d5. }
11. O-O
{ 11.Bc2  would allow  Bxc3+  removing the defender of d5.  12.bxc3  Qxd5  White doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn here. }
11... Nxb3
{ Of course given the chance, we will take White's prized light-squared bishop. }
12. Qxb3 O-O 13. Rd1
{ 13.Re1  would allow  Bxc3  14.Qxc3  Nxd5  Winning the d-pawn with an attack on the queen. }
13... Bg4
{ Developing a piece with the threat of ...Bxf3, ruining White's kingside structure. }
14. Ne4
{ White defends f3 with the queen, and now has ideas of pushing the d-pawn. }
14... Bf5
{ The bishop does a little stutter-step, now harassing White's most active piece, preventing the d6 advance. }
15. Nc5
{ If both sides are content with a draw, the game could end in a repetition like this:  15.Nc3  Bg4  16.Ne4  But by no means are we forced to repeat. We could instead play on with a move like ...Qc8 similar to the mainline. }
15... Qc8
{ A cozy square for the queen, attacking the knight, and getting off of the same file as White's rook. Black must be slightly better due to the active bishop pair, but knights can be tricky! }
16. Be3 { Developing and defending the knight. } 16... Bg4
{ A very uncomfortable position for White. It's not clear what the advanced d-pawn is doing for White, and meanwhile the threat of ...Bxf3 is very annoying. This also reveals one reason 15...Qc8 was more precise than, say, 15...Qc7: The queen is better placed eyeing the kingside light-squares and if ...Bxf3 is allowed, we can jump in with ...Qh3.   This isn't a make-or-break subtlety, but instructive nonetheless. }
