[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pseudo-Panov Attack"]
[Black "Kateryna Lagno vs. Aleksandra Goryachkina, Rus. Women Ch. 2016"]
[Result "*"]

{ Now let's see a game between two of the top Women players in the world! Kateryna Lagno and Aleksandra Goryachkina are two Russian heavyweights battling it out for the Russian Team Championship in 2016. It's a perfect example of what happens if White plays in the most provocative, aggressive manner and how quickly it can backfire when the position doesn't support it.   It's a masterclass by the amazing Goryachkina, and showcases some brilliant knight maneuvers as well! }
1. c4 c6 2. e4
{ The game started as an English Opening with 1. c4, but has now transposed to the Pseudo-Panov Attack! }
2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Bb5
{ Allowing Black to recapture on d5 followed by putting pressure on the c6-square seems to be the most testing way of playing for White. }
7... g6 8. Qa4 Qd6
{ Bringing out the queen to defend where it keeps tabs on both knights! The queen is subject to some harassment, but Goryachkina demonstrates how to perfectly weather White's initiative and later turns her countrywoman's aggression against her.   8...Bd7  drops the knight!  9.Nxd5 }
9. Ne4
{ Lagno may have had this prepped and reasoned that these attacks on Black's queen was a good practical decision, forcing her opponent to find some precise defensive moves. }
9... Qe6
{ Accurate! Goryachkina attacks and pins the knight, encouraging some concrete play. Note: When your opponent is starting aggressive actions before their development is finished, as long as you carefully calculate you can survive the immediate attack, it can be a good idea to encourage further action in order to distract your opponent from finishing development. Eventually their initiative will dissipate, and your superior development may leave you with a better, or even winning position @@StartBracket@@as is the case in this game. @@EndBracket@@   9...Qc7  10.Qd4  Nf6  11.Nxf6+  exf6  12.Qxf6  Qe7+  13.Qxe7+  Bxe7 }
10. Ng5 { A fine move in itself, but White is neglecting development. } 10...
Qd7 11. Nc5 Qc7
{ With some precise retreats, Black's position is under control. All of a sudden, White is the one who should be precise to make sure their pieces aren't clumsy and miscoordinated by the time they finish development. }
12. O-O
{ White's first real mistake, but an understandable one. White needs to finish developing, but this gives Black time to castle with no issues.   12.Qd4  The only way to play for an advantage, but if you don't know it, a difficult move to play since it gives up pressure on c6. The queen takes a nice, central post with tempo, double-attacking the knight and h8-rook, forcing Black's response.  12...Nf6  13.Qc4  The point of White's queen maneuver - now the tender f7-square is under attack and the only way to defend it is  13...e6  locking in Black's light-squared bishop for now.  The position is unclear and a tough battle is ahead, but I would still take Black as our moves come easier. }
12... Bg7 { Now there's no Qd4 and ...O-O is next. } 13. Bc4
{ Lagno understandsd with ...O-O next, the queen and bishop will be misplaced, so she repurposes the bishop to a more active diagonal.   13.Qc4  e6  is an improved version for Black since our knight can stay on d5. }
13... Qd8
{ Another precise defensive move! The queen is no longer needed to defend c6, and returns home to watch over the central knight. }
14. Nxb7
{ An extremely instructive mistake! White spots a tactic that can win her a pawn, so she goes for it, initiating even more action without finishing development. It will take 3 moves to actively develop White's queenside, so even without calculating, it makes sense that White is not ready to go pawn-grabbing. Pay attention to how Goryachkina masterfully exploits her opponent's ambition.   In case you're wondering whether Black would be content with a draw by repetition after  14.Bb5  The answer is likely a resounding 'no!' Black could simply gambit the c6-pawn with  14...O-O  15.Bxc6  bxc6  16.Qxc6  Bf5  and Black's lovely bishop pair and superior development more than compensate for the pawn. White will also likely lose even more time running around with the queen. Black is much better! }
14... Bxb7 15. Qb5
{ White's operation requires another queen move to threaten the fork, and yet another one to win back the piece.  Time is precious in chess! }
15... O-O 16. Qxb7
{ Lagno at least wants the bishop pair for her troubles.   16.Bxd5  Qd7  would have been the best way to make the best of a bad situation, but Black's rooks are quickly joining the action on b8 and d8, and Black's activity, once again, is more than sufficient compensation for the pawn. }
16... Ndb4
{ The best move, putting White's queen in a bit of a queenside cage. Now, ...Rb8 threatens to trap the queen! }
17. Qb5
{ Forced, in order to save the queen.   17.a3  Rb8  would trap the queen and White can resign. }
17... Rb8 { A developing move with even more time against the white queen! }
18. Qa4 Ne5
{ You can see Black's pieces are starting to move forward, often with tempo against White's pieces. }
19. Be2
{ Although the trouble started many moves ago, this is a decisive positional mistake. A knight really can't be allowed to land in front of the d-pawn. This applies in any stage of the game.   19.d3  Nbxd3  20.Rd1  Giving up the d-pawn was well-worth allowing White's pieces some activity! }
19... Ned3
{ Now, White's position is beyond bad - White has nothing to do and is a sitting duck with 3 pieces trapped on the 1st rank.  It's really a picturesque example of positional domination. Let's see how Goryachkina converted it to a win. }
20. Nf3
{ If White has a prayer of surviving, she will need to trade off the knights blockading White's position, so Lagno is looking for Ne1. }
20... e5
{ A small inaccuracy, temporarily blocking the g7-bishop's vision, but one that's hard to criticise.   20...Qc8  Very precise! Due to the pressure on c1, White isn't given the opportunity to play Ne1 and remove the blockade.  21.Bxd3  Nxd3  22.Ne1  would drop the bishop.  22...Nxc1 }
21. a3
{ White is desperately trying to remove the d3-blockade, but Goryachkina is an amazing calculator and she had foreseen the following idea.   21.Bxd3  Would have been the way to minimize the damage.  21...Nxd3  22.Ne1  e4  23.Nxd3  exd3  But although exchanging a couple pairs of pieces has reduced the pressure on White's position, White would still need to find a way to develop.  24.Rb1  Re8  25.b4  I can imagine White holding a position like this.   21.Ne1  would be the wrong move-order as after  21...Nxc1  22.Rxc1  Black wins the d-pawn, although the game becomes more complicated than it needed to be.  22...Qxd2 }
21... Nf4
{ Attaking the e2-bishop and making way for the other knight to replace it on d3. What great knight cooperation! }
22. Bd1 Nbd3 23. g3
{ This time, Lagno attempts to break the knight's coordination from the other side. }
23... Nc5
{ But again, White's misplaced queen allows the same motif! One knight makes way for the other on d3. }
24. Qc4 Nfd3
{ After a magnificent dance of the knights, they are finally stable and dominant. }
25. Bc2
{ White continues their mission to trade off the knights, but it's too little, too late.   25.b4  is not possible in view of  25...e4  with a double attack on the f3-knight and a1-rook. }
25... e4
{ This move does it all - attacks the f3-knight, supports the d3-knight, and increases the scope of the g7-bishop. }
26. Bxd3
{ 26.Ne1  is just as good an attempt as any, and consistent with the idea of trading the knights. Many moves win, but I like  26...Rc8  when Black will win another tempo on the queen.  27.Nxd3  Nxd3  28.Qb3  Re8  29.Bxd3  exd3  White has succeeded in removing the blockade, but has 3 melons on the back-rank. Black can now start an un-defendable attack with moves like ...Bd4 and ...Re2. }
26... Nxd3 27. Qxe4
{ White decides to die on a full stomach by taking another pawn. } 27... Re8
{ Even though White has two extra pawns, White's rooks and c1-bishop are not participating in the game! In such a position, tactics will soon become available for the side with the active pieces. }
28. Qa4 Qd5 29. Nh4 Nxf2
{ Black breaks through White's kingside shelter, and Lagno resigned. If the knight is taken, }
30. Rxf2 Re1+ 31. Rf1 Bd4+
{ White would be forced to give up the queen, and checkmate is still just around the corner.   This game is an amazingly instructive example highlighting the importance of development and how to react against early aggression. }
