{ Quick castling is especially important in all of the variations where a piece is pinned on c6 or d7. }
8. Qa4 { White threatens to take twice on c6, winning at least a pawn. } 8...
Qd6 { 8...Bd7  Don't defend it like this!  9.Nxd5 } 9. Ne4
{ We will have a look at the most testing moves for White to play from here. }
9... Qe6 { Our queen pins the knight and continues to defend c6. } 10. O-O Bg7
11. Re1 { This one looks scarier than it is. } 11... O-O
{ We've broken the pin, but our queen is still a little vulnerable. As long as we stay vigilent, White's initiative is about to expire. }
12. d4 Rd8
{ A cold-blooded move, putting pressure on White's centre and understanding there's no immediate discovery that acheives anything for White. }
13. Nc5 Qd6 { Everything is under control. } 14. Bxc6
{ Black was threatening to take on d4, so White correctly evaluates the best way to diffuse the pressure is to finally take on c6. }
14... Qxc6 15. Qxc6 bxc6
{ Both sides have weak pawns, and nice knight outposts, but in order to give us our weak pawn, White had to part with the bishop pair. We have many ways to continue here including ...Bg4 and putting more pressure on d4, expanding on the queenside, but the engine pointed out a very clever plan: expanding on the kingside with ...f6, ...g5 and maybe ...g4, displacing the f3-knight, which is the 'glue' in White's position. During this operation, the g7-bishop could be repurposed via f8 and perhaps combined with an eventual ...e6 or ...e5, depending on the circumstances.   A few words of conclusion on the Pseudo-Panov Attack: Because so many central pawns are exchanged, the position tends to be more open than most possible lines in the Caro-Kann. That means you need to be tactically astute. In the Qa4+ and Bb5+ lines, do your best to remember which piece to block with and quickly castle.   Otherwise, just remember to fianchetto the bishop queenside, pressurize the d-pawn, and carry on. :@@EndBracket@@ }
