[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Pseudo-Panov Attack"]
[Black "Jovana Rapport vs. Jovanka Houska, Isle of Man, 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6 5. Bb5+ Nbd7
{ This game was from several years ago in the Isle of Man tournament against Jovana Rapport. It was a dynamic, back and forth game which shows the typical struggle of fighting against an isolated pawn vs. White's attempted kingside attack, and how to react to it. }
6. Nf3
{ A rare move, offering back the d-pawn. Usually White starts by developing the other knight out to c3. But there's really no difference in how I recommend playing against it. }
6... a6
{ 6...Nxd5  I believe is a bit too early to recapture for my taste, when we can slowly develop, castle, unpinning our knight, and more comfortably recapture later.  7.Nc3  e6  is playable, but it's a different setup than the one I enjoy with ...g6. }
7. Ba4 g6
{ 7...b5  8.Bb3  Bb7  9.O-O  Nc5  is another extremely healthy way of playing, comfortably winning back the pawn and probably also the bishop pair. }
8. Nc3 Bg7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nb6 11. Bb3 Nbxd5 12. d4
{ Now I have an interesting version of an IQP position that should be great, since White has spent so many moves bringing the bishop to b3.   As you can see, I already have an effective blockade in front of the d-pawn, and given the time, my next moves will be to finish developing and bringing the rooks to the d-file, maximizing pressure on the pawn. }
12... b5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bg5
{ White's threat is to take on d5, then on e7, winning a pawn. } 14... Bf6 15.
Qd2 Bb7 16. h4 { A thematic move as White wants to attack the king. } 16... e6
17. Rac1 Be7
{ Here I had an interesting idea to fight against White's bishop.  I want to prepare ...f6, which does weaken the e-pawn, but as long as it's well-defended, the f-pawn actually restricts White's active options. }
18. a3 Re8 19. Ne5 Qd6 20. Ng4 f6 21. Bh6 Rad8
{ Here it's not so easy for White to put further pressure on my position and I continue to pile up on d4. }
22. Ne3 Rd7 23. Qe2 Bf8 24. Bxf8 Kxf8 25. Bxd5 Bxd5
{ These trades, I feel, have reduced the possibility of my king being attacked. As a rule of thumb, piece exchanges tend to favour the side playing against the isolated pawn. }
26. Qg4 Kg7 27. h5 g5
{ Preferring to keep the kingside as closed as possible. } 28. Rc5 Ba8 29. Rd1
Qf4 30. Qe2 Red8 31. h6+ Kg6
{ 31...Kxh6  would allow White some activity after  32.Ng4+  with a discovered attack on the e-pawn.  32...Kg6  33.Qxe6 }
32. d5
{ White was going to lose the d-pawn anyway, so she wants to do it on her own terms. }
32... Bxd5 33. Nxd5 exd5 34. Rc6 Qe4 35. Qd2 d4
{ Now suddenly it's us with the isolated pawn, but it's also a big, strong, passed pawn and the hero of the game. }
36. Rxa6 d3 37. Re1 Qf4 38. Qxf4 gxf4 39. Rc6 d2 40. Rd1 Re7
{ The threat of ...Re1 prompted my opponent to resign here. } 41. Kf1
{ only defers the threat by one move and after } 41... Rde8
{ There's no stopping ...Re1 with either checkmate, or winning material. } *

