1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 9% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@   The Hillbilly Attack, while uncommon at higher levels, is actually the third most popular setup for amateurs. So, pay attention because you will see it more often than you'd expect.   2.d3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 3% of Caro-Kann games@@EndBracket@@   A cheeky variation, choosing not to occupy the centre after which White has a few ways of playing.  2...d5  3.Nd2  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 7%@@EndBracket@@   White is looking for a King's Indian Attack setup involving g3, Bg2, O-O and future kingside expansion.   3.exd5  @@StartBracket@@Frequency:  33%@@EndBracket@@   Entering an Exchange Variation except with a pawn misplaced on d3 instead of d4.  3...cxd5  4.Nf3  Nc6  5.Be2  e5  In many of the 2. d3 variations, we can set up the central pawn duo. Black clearly has no problems here.   3.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@Frequency: 13%@@EndBracket@@   A provocative move after which we could take on e4 and go into an endgame @@StartBracket@@what White is hoping for@@EndBracket@@ or push ahead with ...d4, but for simplicity sake I'm recommending  3...e5  The knight on c3 is a little funny, and might even be kicked backwards by ...d4 next. Black has a space advantage and a nice game!   3.Nf3  @@StartBracket@@ Frequency: 12%@@EndBracket@@   A common blitz weapon at higher levels, tempting Black into taking on e4 and entering an endgame that can be difficult for Black to handle.  3...Bg4  A super solid way to play, intending to trade the bishop for the knight if needed followed by creating our pawn-triangle with ...e6.  3...e5  The most principled setup against the King's Indian Attack, taking the full centre and intending ...Bd6, ...Nf6, and ...O-O followed by play on the queenside. }
2... d5 3. exd5 cxd5
{ Our usual central thrust comes with a gain of tempo this time. } 4. Bb3
{ Why White would prefer the bishop on the a2-g8 diagonal is an enigma, but I suppose a hillbilly has their reasons. }
4... Nf6 5. d4 Bg4
{ A similar approach I recommend against the Exchange Variation, only this time the queen can't run away towards the queenside.  White has the choice between several unsavory options and at the end of the day, the b3-bishop is misplaced. }
