1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ We will now round out our course by examining some of the bits and bobs White can throw our way. Because the setups are unusual, how we play against them is a bit less consistent than in other chapters. The Move-Trainer will be especially useful in this chapter, as a result.   2. d3 says I'm not coming at you with my pawns, and I'm content quietly developing my pieces from a distance. }
2... d5 { The normal Caro-Kann second move, and the justification of 1. c6. }
3. exd5 cxd5
{ Here we have the Exchange Variation except with the pawn on d3 instead of d4.   This difference is, unsurprisingly, in Black's favour primarily because White's light-squared bishop is hemmed in by the d3-pawn. White can't put any pressure on our position if they play like this, but just for the sake of being thorough, let's see what a middlegame position could look like if White develops normally. }
4. Nf3 Nc6 5. Be2 e5
{ With the pawn on d3, we are able to take the full centre, as we should! } 6.
Nc3 Nf6 { Knights before bishops! } 7. O-O Bd6 8. Bg5
{ White's only active means of developing this bishop, pinning the knight and threatening to take the d-pawn. But, as we've seen in the Exchange Variation chapter, White's bishops are usually misplaced on our side of the board where they will be either traded, or targets.   8.Be3  would run directly into  d4  with a fork! }
8... Be6
{ Both sides have developed their pieces, but Black has developed their pieces a little better, our centre as proof.   Next, we can either calmly castle, or start harassing White's bishop with ...h6 / ...g5 when our kingside expansion can give good chances.   A sample line could be:  9.Qd2  h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  g4  asking the knight an uncomfortable question.  12.Nh4  the most active-looking square  Nh5  with ...Be7 next, threatening to trap the knight!   Play could proceed in many other ways as well, but, in contrast to most Caro-Kann positions, I wanted to highlight an instance where kingside expansion can be an option @@StartBracket@@but usually only if you haven't already castled short@@EndBracket@@. }
*

