[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ We will now round out our course by examining some of the bits and bobs White can throw our way. Because the setups are unusual, how we play against them is a bit less consistent than in other chapters. The Move-Trainer will be especially useful in this chapter, as a result.   2. d3 says I'm not coming at you with my pawns, and I'm content quietly developing my pieces from a distance. }
2... d5 { The normal Caro-Kann second move, and the justification of 1. c6. }
3. Nc3
{ A very rare move, guarding the queen in in case Black decides to take on e4 and exchange queens. In that case, White would retain castling rights. }
3... e5
{ The most principled move. We are offered the full centre, so we should take it.   Again, White is really hoping for an endgame after this sort of thing...  3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  5.Nxd1  When this time, White need not even revoke castling rights. This is, of course, playable, but is clearly what White was hoping for. Let's not indulge them. }
4. Nf3
{ White's most popular move at master-level, attacking e5, but it's a mistake.   4.f4  would be a consistent approach given the way White has developed, but it's not so effective given our control of the centre!  exf4  Our pawn was attacked, so first we capture with tempo...  5.Bxf4  d4  6.Nce2  c5  This kind of space advantage is very pleasant for Black, especially since White's kingside development is stunted by the awkward e2-knight.   Furthermore, we could imagine trading off a pair of bishops with ... Bd6 and a knight landing on the nice e5-blockading square with a comfortable edge.   At lower levels, it's no surprise White's most common move is  4.exd5  but after  cxd5  Black has a dream position: the full centre, the c6-square for the knight, and good squares for the rest of the pieces. }
4... d4 { I think this is the right time to take a space-advantage. } 5. Ne2
Bd6 { Defending the pawn! } 6. c3
{ To play devil's advocate for White's setup, we should focus on the only move after which White MIGHT have an equal game, challenging our centre.    Against anything else, we will continue with ...c5, ...Nc6, with a permanent clamp on the position. }
6... c5
{ Bolstering the centre.  Now, we will usually recapture on d4 with the c-pawn, minimizing kingside counterplay for White. }
7. b4
{ The idea behind White's last move - fighting for some space. At least now maybe it's not so convenient for Black to play ...Nc6. }
7... b6 { The best move, when we can recapture on c5 with the b-pawn. } 8. g3
Ne7
{ Our space advantage gives us a more comfortable game. Next we will castle, continue development, and one day we could consider taking on c3 when there is suddenly the nice d4-outpost for a knight and play against White's backward d-pawn. }
