[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. d3
{ We will now round out our course by examining some of the bits and bobs White can throw our way. Because the setups are unusual, how we play against them is a bit less consistent than in other chapters. The Move-Trainer will be especially useful in this chapter, as a result.   2. d3 says I'm not coming at you with my pawns, and I'm content quietly developing my pieces from a distance. }
2... d5 { The normal Caro-Kann second move, and the justification of 1. c6. }
3. Nf3
{ This time, White starts by developing their king's knight, which could very well transpose to the King's Indian Attack as seen before.   It's a cagey move that's played at high-levels often as a blitz weapon, but there are many ways Black can react. }
3... Bg4
{ Pin it to win it!    We are given a chance to develop the bishop outside the pawn chain, and in this case, similar to some lines in the Exchange Variation, we are ready to give up the bishop pair at a moment's notice.   3...dxe4  4.dxe4  Qxd1+  is the mainline, going into an endgame where White gives up castling rights. I prefer to avoid this scenario as White is clearly prepared for this endgame and it can actually be quite tricky to play for Black.   Additionally, there's a devilish trap line that you should know to avoid at all costs:  3...dxe4  4.Ng5  exd3  5.Bxd3  Black wins a pawn, but the trap is set.  Nf6  an all-too-common mistake.  6.Nxf7  winning a rook or a queen!  Kxf7  7.Bg6+  a discovered attack on the queen seals the deal.  hxg6  8.Qxd8  .   For this reason, this is a common blitz weapon at the top-level and has been tried by pretty much all the top players: Carlsen, Caruana, Aronian, So, and especially often and with great success by Dmitry Andreikin, the star of our Fantasy Variationmodel game. }
4. h3
{ White's best try is to seize the bishop pair, but since White wasn't ambitious about the centre, we don't mind giving it up here. }
4... Bxf3
{ The correct response.  4...Bh5  is playable, but I want to avoid any sticky situations arising after  5.g4  Bg6  6.h4  when the bishop can be harassed further. }
5. Qxf3 e6
{ Solid. We have rid ourselves of our 'bad' c8-bishop, and we are using our pawns to control the light-squares.   It's not clear to the untrained eye why we shouldn't go for the immediate  5...e5  and, in fact, it's playable! But the thing is, it's not as convenient for us to develop here since ...Bd6 drops the d5-pawn. After normal moves such as  6.Nd2  Nf6  7.g4  h6  8.h4  Again, White is allowed more kingside play than is necessary and the threat of g5, removing the defender of d5 is annoying.   It turns out the queen is well-placed to pressurize d5 in this line. }
6. g3
{ The most sensibile way for White's light-squared bishop to develop. by maximising pressure on d5, White wants to make it hard for us to push any of our central pawns. }
6... Nd7
{ Clearly the best square for this knight since the c6-square isn't becoming available anytime soon.  Additionally, we prepare ...Ngf6 by controlling the e5-square in case the pawn pushes forward. }
7. Bg2 Ngf6 8. O-O Bc5 { The bishop comes out to a lovely, active diagonal. }
9. Qe2
{ White has many moves, but this is the most popular at higher levels, stepping out of the way of the fianchettoed bishop and threatening e5 which we don't want to allow! }
9... dxe4 10. dxe4 e5
{ Next we will castle, play ...Qc7, likely ...a5 to activate the queen's rook and eventually the bishop can be replaced on c5 by a knight where it puts pressure on White's centre. }
