[White "7) Offbeat Setups"]
[Black "🧨 Offbeat: 2.Ne2 🧨"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Ne2
{ This is considered a serious sideline because the knight is surprisingly flexible from e2, and can jump to various annoying squares including g3, f4, or d4, depending on the situation. }
2... d5 3. e5
{ Here we have an Advance Variation with Ne2 instead of d4. White wants to argue the knight can sometimes cause some annoyance and only later d4 can be played.   I highly doubt an amateur will be playing this subtle move-order.   3.d3  As we've seen, if White doesn't take the full centre, we will!  3...e5 }
3... Bf5 { Our usual approach to the Advance Variation. } 4. h4
{ We've seen this idea before. White sees the f5-bishop as a target and wants to try to make life hard for it.   Interestingly,  4.Ng3  can easily lead to a direct transposition to theline in the Advance Variation chapter with an early Ne2.  4...Bg6  5.h4  h5  6.d4  e6  If White doesn't go for an early e6 themselves, we can play it with a comfortable game. This is a transposition to the early Ne2 in the Advance Variation.   4.Nd4  Play is quite similar to the mainline here, but perhaps even more favourable for Black. For example, after  4...Bg6  5.e6  Qd6  6.exf7+  Bxf7  ...e5 is coming and the knight is probably misplaced. }
4... h5 { In general, we are always meeting h4 with ...h5. } 5. Ng3 Bg6
{ Keeping the pawn defended. } 6. e6
{ I decided to cover this e6 push in a trainable variation because it requires careful handling. White doesn't want to allow ...e6 with our pawn triangle.   There are a few different cirucumstances under which this kind of push is possible, but I've evaded them through my repertoire choices for the most part. }
6... fxe6
{ I recommend taking the pawn, playing ...Qd6, and ...e5. The kingside has been weakened with this capture, so the king is likely going the other direction. }
7. d4 Qd6
{ Next on the agenda is ...Nd7 and ...e5, putting our big centre to use.   7...Nd7  is inferior since the queen is needed on d6 to advance the centre, and in some cases, to defend the e-pawn. }
8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nd7
{ White has taken aim at the weakened kingside light squares, so we prepare a nice path out of there for our king. }
10. Qg6+ Kd8 { ... e5 is next, and White's queen is probably misplaced. } 11.
Nxh5
{ White might want to regain the pawn they gave us on e6, but we're more than happy trading a flank pawn for a central pawn. }
11... e5 12. Qxd6 exd6
{ What a beautiful pawn centre! This is more than Black could ever hope for in the opening. }
