1. e4 c6 2. Nc3
{ Such a second move could transpose to the Classical or Two Knights Variations but there is a rare independent try as well that I've seen Daniel Naroditsky playing lately. }
2... d5 3. Qf3
{ I admit this is an interesting idea. White, of course, is adding pressure to the d5-square, but after a trade on e4, thinks the queen is well-placed on f3, from where it takes aim at the tender f7-square. For that reason, I made this a dynamite line. }
3... dxe4
{ We are taking that central pawn, just like in the Classical and Two Knights. }
4. Nxe4 Nd7 { For consistency sake, we can go for the same Karpov setup. } 5.
d4 Ngf6 6. Bc4 e6
{ I think we should respect Daniel Naroditsky and his Qf3 idea, and stay solid. There's no reason White should have much if we develop simply and aim for Old Faithful.   6...Nb6  Taking the d-pawn, while objectively best, can become extremely hard to play if we are too far behind in development, for instance after  7.Bd3  Qxd4  8.Ne2  And it's not clear where the queen wants to go. I think there's a simpler option.   Please don't get checkmated by taking the knight:  6...Nxe4  7.Bxf7+  . }
7. Bg5
{ White can choose to castle either direction in this position. Let's first check what play can look like if White looks for something a little spicier and tries castling queenside. }
7... Be7
{ As always, we really want to encourage trades, which will alleviate our space disadvantage.   Besides, the d6-square is covered by the knight here. }
8. O-O-O Nxe4 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Qxe4 a5
{ The most important pawn advance in this structure when facing a queenside castled king. The black a-pawn wants to march as far as it possibly can down the board which will provoke either White's a-pawn or b-pawn to move, creating a weakness we can use to attack.   If the b-pawn budges, the dark-squares are weak and White will always need to watch out for an invasion on b2.   If the a-pawn decides to stop the progress of our own a-pawn by playing a3, it is a hook we can use to open the position with by pushing the b-pawn forwards.  Next we will play ...Nf6, bringing a defender to the kingside, where we are most likely to castle when the time is right, then push the a- and b-pawns up the board to start an attack. }
