[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Offbeat Setups"]
[Black "Offbeat: 2.Bc4 (Hillbilly Attack) #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Bc4
{ Last, and probably also least, let's have a quick look at the so-called Hillbilly Attack!  White disregards the opening principle of knights before bishops and brings the bishop to a seemingly active diagonal. But in reality, once we put pawns on d5 and e6, it's simply misplaced along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... d5
{ This time, our second move comes with the bonus of gaining time against the bishop! }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3
{ The only logical move. If the bishop retreated to the same diagonal it came from, we would have to issue a sanity check on the White player. But from here, the bishop is going to stare at our wall of pawns. }
4... Nf6
{ Developing the kingside knight to its most natural square. It's a flexible move to see what White does next. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 6. h3
{ One of the most critical approaches, asking the bishop what it would like to do before White castles. }
6... Bh5
{ 6...Bxf3  7.Qxf3  e6  is an approach we've seen before in response to this early h3 idea, but since White's bishop is so poorly placed on b3, we aren't quite as worried about an attack on our king. }
7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5
{ White continues its mission to harass the bishop, intending h4-h5 next. }
8... e6
{ Keep calm and carry on developing the kingside!  (We definitely don't want to touch our h-pawn and allow a structure such as the one after)   8...h5  9.Nxg6  fxg6  10.g5  when the e-pawn and both g-pawns will be permanent weaknesses. }
9. h4 d4
{ Now that White is threatening to trap our bishop, it's time to create a cozy square on d5 for it. Now if h5 is played, we can maneuver the bishop from g6-e4-d5.   10.d3  fails tactically to  10...Qa5+  forking the king and knight.  11.Kf1  Qxe5  12.h5  White can still trap the bishop, but we've already won a piece so we are happy giving up our extra piece for a pawn and after  12...Bxh5  13.gxh5  Nc6  White's king is forever exposed, unable to castle, and Black is up a healthy pawn for no compensation. }
10. Qe2
{ A normal square for the queen now that the light-squared bishop has been developed, lining up against the king. }
10... Nbd7
{ This move illustrates the standard plan if White maintains the pawn duo on h4 and g4, which are undoubtedly overextended. We will trade off the powerful knight on e5 next then play ...h5 to counteract White's kingside space advantage.  Black has a nice advantage due to the weaknesses left behind by the white kingside pawns combined with their lack of development. }
