[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Offbeat Setups"]
[Black "Offbeat: 2.Bc4 (Hillbilly Attack) #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ This course is all about what happens after the King's Pawn Opening, AKA 1. e4.   This is the oldest and most popular first move in chess so you can bet it will come up in many if not most of your games. }
1... c6
{ Let's get straight into it, shall we?   With this modest pawn move, we enter my beloved Caro-Kann Defense and with it, a world of strategic delight. While ...c6 doesn't occupy the center with a pawn, it prepares to do just that on the very next move with ...d5.   Already we should be feeling happy because we are going to be more familiar and prepared for the coming battle than our opponent! }
2. Bc4
{ Last, and probably also least, let's have a quick look at the so-called Hillbilly Attack!  White disregards the opening principle of knights before bishops and brings the bishop to a seemingly active diagonal. But in reality, once we put pawns on d5 and e6, it's simply misplaced along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... d5
{ This time, our second move comes with the bonus of gaining time against the bishop! }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3
{ The only logical move. If the bishop retreated to the same diagonal it came from, we would have to issue a sanity check on the White player. But from here, the bishop is going to stare at our wall of pawns. }
4... Nf6
{ Developing the kingside knight to its most natural square. It's a flexible move to see what White does next. }
5. Nf3 Bg4 { The ideal square for the bishop. Pin it to win it! } 6. O-O e6
{ The poor bishop on b3 seems to have gotten lost on the queenside. } 7. h3
{ Another one of those nervy moves amateurs often make. It doesn't hurt the position that much, but it's a sign they're uncomfortable with a piece in their territory. }
7... Bh5 8. d3
{ The most common move, and a very unambitious one. We've seen this in other most popular variations from other chapters. I think it's a sign that amateurs have a tendency to play passively with their pawns, but aggressively with their pieces when they perceive them that way.   Better is the normal  8.d4  ,  taking White's fair share of the centre. }
8... Bd6
{ The ideal square for our dark-squared bishop where it exerts influence in both directions. }
9. Bg5 { There's the trademark pin, but it's a fine move here. } 9... O-O 10.
Nbd2
{ White has chosen a logical setup but there should be pawns on d4 and c3 instead of d3 and c2 and the bishop should be on d3 instead of b3. These factors make a huge difference in the evaluation, and are the reason Black is better. }
10... Nc6 { Normal! } 11. Qe1
{ A strange move. It would be more normal to bring a rook there, but I guess the amateur players want to unpin. }
11... a5
{ Activating or developing the rook on a8! Next we want to trap the bishop with ...a4. If they prevent this, we can expand in the centre with a well-prepared ...e5.    Black is significantly better due to the poor bishop on b3 and the lack of central space. This variation is proof that against weird variations like the Hillbilly Attack, if you just play normal chess and develop your pieces, you can emerge from the opening with an advantage almost as if by magic. }
