[White "7) Offbeat Setups"]
[Black "🤺 Offbeat: 2.Bc4 (Hillbilly Attack) #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ Last, and probably also least, let's have a quick look at the so-called Hillbilly Attack!  White disregards the opening principle of knights before bishops and brings the bishop to a seemingly active diagonal. But in reality, once we put pawns on d5 and e6, it's simply misplaced along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... d5
{ This time, our second move comes with the bonus of gaining time against the bishop! }
3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bb3 Nf6
{ Standard development. It's pretty clear our knights belong on f6 and c6. You will see why we start with this knight after our next move. }
5. d4
{ White really has nothing better than to push d4, taking their fair share of the centre and facilitating the development of their dark-squared bishop. }
5... Bg4
{ ...Nf6 supports move, when we can play the same way we do against the Exchange Variation. The Hillbilly Attack is only an Exchange Variation with a misplaced bishop on b3. As a rule of thumb, ...Bg4, attacking the queen is especially disruptive when the queen can't come out to the queenside with Qb3, for example. That's because White doesn't want a pinned knight, nor is it any good to play f3. }
6. Ne2
{ The lesser of all evils.  6.f3  Bd7  We could also play ...Bf5, but this is even safer, when our bishop won't be subject to harassment on the kingside.  7.Ne2  e6  White's moves have made very little sense.   The f3-pawn and the b3-bishop hurt White's position much more than it's worth to put our light-squared bishop inside our pawn-chain. Black is slightly better. }
6... e6 { The move that makes fun of the hillbilly bishop. } 7. O-O Nc6 8. c3
Bd6
{ SPARRING POSITION   Black is better based solely on the fact that White's bishop is misplaced, and it cost them an extra move to misplace it! After ...Qc7 and ...O-O, we can look forward to a smooth minority attack with ...b5-b4, undermining White's pawn chain. That's about it as far as the rare options for White. The 2. d3 variations are interesting and viable, in which I recommend a solid kingside fianchetto setup, and remember to take the full center with ...e5 if allowed. The Hillbilly Attack is less threatening than the name indicates, as White's hillbilly bishop is off drinking moonshine somewhere on the queenside.   There you have it, ladies and gentlemen - the Caro-Kann! You're now equipped with the greatest opening in chess! Whenever you're ready for a refresher on how to play a certain variation, I suggest starting with the chapter overview and playing through the model game. Another great way to improve your openings is to find a player who plays the same setup and carefully play through their games. I hope you've learned a lot, not only about the opening, but also about chess strategy in the process.   May it bring you success in your games! }
