[White "7) Offbeat Setups"]
[Black "Offbeat: 2.Bc4 (Hillbilly Attack) #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c6 2. Bc4
{ Last, and probably also least, let's have a quick look at the so-called Hillbilly Attack!  White disregards the opening principle of knights before bishops and brings the bishop to a seemingly active diagonal. But in reality, once we put pawns on d5 and e6, it's simply misplaced along the a2-g8 diagonal. }
2... d5
{ This time, our second move comes with the bonus of gaining time against the bishop! }
3. Bb3
{ This is the mainline Hillbilly, which almost sounds like an oxymoron.  White doesn't bother taking our central pawn, allowing the c6-square to become available for our knight, and instead has some aggressive attentions involving the weak f7-square. }
3... dxe4 { White has offered us a free pawn, and it is free. } 4. Qh5
{ All we need is one or two accurate defensive moves to deflate White's attack. }
4... g6 5. Qh4 Bf5
{ I like defending with the bishop and staying flexible with the knight which, in some cases, may want to develop to a square other than f6, or perhaps keeping the a1-h8 diagonal open for the bishop for the time being. }
6. Nc3
{ 6.g4  is another ambitious attempt, but the simple  6...Bc8  suffices since the e4-pawn is no longer under attack. Play could continue:  7.Nc3  Bg7  8.Nxe4  Nf6  9.Nxf6+  Bxf6  10.Qg3  h5!  11.g5  Bg7 }
6... e6
{ Trades are good, as always! Let's trade off White's most active piece. } 7.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. f3
{ White prefers their knight on f3, but this move gives up hope of ever recapturing that pawn, and so goes down a pawn permanently.   Notice there's no realistic way of going about winning back the pawn anyway. }
8... exf3 9. Nxf3 Bd6 10. d3 Nd7
{ Black can expand on both flanks, harass the b3-bishop, and be happy with an extra pawn for very little compensation. }
