[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caro-Kann Endgame"]
[Black "Caro-Kann Endgame Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

{ A course on the Caro-Kann wouldn't be complete without addressing the endgame.   One of the great things about the Caro-Kann is that because White often takes some strategic liberties to fight against our solid pawn structure, endgames tend to favour Black. This is one of the reasons I've been harping on about the fact that trades benefit Black in the Caro-Kann. They bring us that much closer to an endgame!    This isn't an endgame course, so we won't be covering any endgame theory, nor engaging in some kind of strategic deep-dive.  The purpose of this chapter is to show a few examples of successful transitions to an endgame which could arise from variations in the course, and celebrate the triumph of Black's overarching strategy. This way, you can start to see the Caro-Kann from start to finish.   We will show one cool example of each the following themes:   A@@EndBracket@@ Minority attack   B@@EndBracket@@ Playing against the isolated queen's pawn   C@@EndBracket@@ Importance of Tactical Sharpness and Transformation of Advantages in an endgame.   If you want to take your Caro Endgame learning to the next level, I recommend:  A@@EndBracket@@ Studying typical pawn structures which arise from our course  B@@EndBracket@@ Finding a Caro-Kann hero and going through all their games in the Caro-Kann using an online database, paying particular attention to the endgame  I hope you enjoy, and that you can start to get a sense for how Caro-Kann games are won. }
1. -- *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caro-Kann Endgame"]
[Black "Minority Attack: Vlastimil Hort vs. Keith C Arkell, Bunratty Masters, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ Grandmaster Keith Arkell is a mainstay of British Chess circuit, internationally renowned for his endgame expertise. As evidenced by this game, Keith can take even the most miniscule pull from a position and grind it into a win. Even against Hort's caliber, who used to be among the top players in the world. }
1. e4 c6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Nd7 5. Nf3 Ngf6 6. Nxf6+ Nxf6 7. Bc4 Bf5
8. O-O e6
{ Hort has chosen a relatively toothless variation which is covered in the theory section.  Let's talk about this pawn structure, because the pawn structure is a major strategic element of the endgame, and in the Caro-Kann, our pawn structure tends to be more healthy than White's, giving us great practical chances. In this position, the d5-pawn has been exchanged for White's e4-pawn, leaving a hole on d5. This occurs in the Classical and Two Knights variations. Arkell has managed a good version of this structure since the light-squared bishop has made it outside the pawn chain. This structure is related to the structure that arises after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c6  2.d4  d5  3.exd5  cxd5  when a pawn is on d5 instead of c6.  Either way, Black's main plan is to play on the queenside with aminority attack. This means pushing the queenside pawns forward with the hope of creating a pawn weakness in White's camp.   Why is it called the minority attack?   Because Black has 3 pawns on the queenside compared to White's 4 pawns. In contrast, on the kingside, Black has a 4-3 pawn majority. A long time ago, before modern chess strategy was developed, it was thought you need to play on the side of the board where your pawn majority is. Therefore, pawn minorities were considered useless and weak.    Here, Keith's first course of action, structurally, will be ...c5, just like every chapter in the course when a pawn remains on c6. This usually results in a trade of our c-pawn for White's central d-pawn, which is in Black's favour. It also opens the c-file which we can use to attack.  The last thing I'll mention about this structure is that the d5-square can be utilized by a piece, often a knight. Meanwhile, White will need to find creative, but often strategically risky, ways of attacking our kingside.    Let's see what happened in the game. I won't scrutinize the moves of either side, but I will pause at key moments to explain important endgame concepts. }
9. Re1
{ Here is a lovely bonus game by Keith Arkell from the same position:  9.c3  Be7  10.Bd3  Bxd3  11.Qxd3  O-O  12.Bg5  h6  13.Bh4  c5  14.Rad1  Qb6  15.Qe2  Rfd8  16.Bg3  Rac8  17.Be5  a6  18.h3  Qc6  19.Rfe1  b5  20.dxc5  Qxc5  21.Bd4  Qc7  22.Ne5  Bc5  23.Bxc5  Qxc5  24.Rd3  Rxd3  25.Nxd3  Qc4  26.Nb4  Qxe2  27.Rxe2  a5  28.Nd3  Nd5  29.f4  Rd8  30.f5  Ne7  31.Ne5  Nxf5  32.Nc6  Rd1+  33.Kf2  a4  34.Re5  Nd6  35.Nd4  Rb1  36.b3  Rc1  37.Nxb5  Rc2+  38.Ke3  Nxb5  39.Rxb5  Rxc3+  40.Kd4  Rc2  41.Ra5  axb3  42.axb3  Rxg2  43.b4  f5  44.b5  f4  45.b6  Rb2  46.Kc5  f3  47.Ra8+  Kf7  48.Ra3  f2  49.Rf3+  Ke7  50.Kc6  Rc2+  51.Kb5  e5  52.b7  e4  53.Rf4  e3  54.b8=Q  Rb2+  55.Rb4  f1=Q+  56.Kc6  Qc1+  57.Kd5  Qd2+  0-1 @@StartBracket@@57@@EndBracket@@ Barron,M @@StartBracket@@2123@@EndBracket@@-Arkell,K @@StartBracket@@2406@@EndBracket@@ Dresden 2018 }
9... Bg4 10. c3 Be7 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 O-O 13. Bd2 Nd5
{ A natural square for the knight, typical of this structure. Note that if White ever decides to push the c-pawn further to c4 in this structure, the d4-pawn would be a weakness for Black to target. }
14. Rad1 Bg5
{ Black is encouraging as many trades as possible. This is especially effective when Whtie has the bishop pair. }
15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Re5 Qf6 17. Bxd5 cxd5 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. Re3 b5
{ Now the endgame really begins, as well as Black's minority attack. The position is objectively equal, but because of Black's extra pawn presence in the centre, Keith has great practical chances, and he understands the minority attack better than almost anybody on the planet.   Keith wants to arrange the ...b5-b4 break to soften the white pawns. }
20. f4 Rfe8 21. Rde1 Rab8 22. f5
{ White is clearly targetting the e-pawn, but the Caro-Kann structure provides such solidity in the centre that it's hard to break! }
22... Rb6 { A calm, defensive move. } 23. a3
{ Trying to slow down the ...b4-break. } 23... a5
{ Supporting the ...b4-break. } 24. Kf2 Kf8
{ Simply for illustrative purposes, let's see a couple of typical structural transformations resulting from the minority attack.  24...b4  25.axb4  axb4  26.Kf3   26.cxb4  Rxb4  Mental Snapshot #1: White has weak, isolated d and b-pawns for Black to attack. Very good for Black.  bxc3  27.bxc3  Mental Snapshot #2: White has a backwards c-pawn for Black's rooks to attack - very good for Black as well, all things being equal. }
25. g4 Ke7
{ In the endgame, the king's activity is vital. Keith decides to assign the king the task of defending the centre so the e8-rook can roam elsewhere. }
26. Kg3 Rg8
{ There's no law that states all of your moves need to be towards the queenside. Keith is looking for ...h5 in order to   Black isn't ready for  26...b4  yet since  27.axb4  axb4  28.cxb4  Rxb4  29.fxe6  would allow the centre to collapse. }
27. Kf4 h5
{ This is quite advanced, but in endgames, thePrinciple of Two Weaknesses says that often creating a single weakness isn't enough to win.    It's hard to say if Keith was thinking about winning, or just doing a bit of harmless probing in this position, but Keith is clearly aiming for the creation of a pawn weakness in White's camp on both the queenside and kingside. }
28. Rg3 { 28.gxh5  would allow too much activity after  28...Rg5 } 28... hxg4
29. h4
{ 29.Rxg4  is another way an isolated h-pawn could have emerged, after which I assume Keith had  29...Rh8  in mind.   29.hxg4  isn't so desirable for White since it would allow  29...Rh8  and marginally more active rooks for Black. }
29... b4 { The fruition of the minority attack! } 30. axb4 axb4 31. Rxg4 Rh8
{ Keith wants both sets of rooks on the board because it's easier to target White's weaknesses. }
32. Ra1 bxc3 33. bxc3
{ Now, White's weaknesses are visible - h4 and c3.  Keith is really in his element. }
33... Rh5 34. Ra7+ Kd6 35. fxe6 fxe6 36. Kg3 Rh8 37. Rgg7
{ Rooks on the 7th rank are usually an incredibly potent force, but here, there are no targets for the rooks and after }
37... Rc8
{ White's c-pawn is under attack and the c6-square is a cozy hiding place for the black king. }
38. Rgd7+ Kc6 39. h5 Rb3 40. h6 Rxc3+ 41. Kf2 Rh3 42. h7 e5
{ White's h7-pawn has come to a screeching halt, while suddenly Black's dynamic pawn centre comes to life! }
43. Rg7 Rb8 44. Kg2 Rh5 45. Ra6+ Rb6
{ Now that Black has established a strong central advantage, Keith doesn't mind exchanging a pair of rooks. }
46. Ra8 Rb2+ 47. Kg3 Rbh2
{ Now, because of the coordination of Black's rooks, and the awkward placement of White's king, White's two weaknesses can be counted as    A@@EndBracket@@ the king   B@@EndBracket@@ the centre  The position is objectively equal, but much more fun for Black to play. }
48. Ra6+ Kb5 49. Rxf6 exd4 50. Rb7+ Kc4 51. Rc6+ Kd3
{ The active king could eventually do a great job of escorting the pawns up the board. }
52. Rcc7 Rc2 53. Rd7 Rc8 54. Kg4 Rh1 55. Rxd5 Rcc1 56. Rd8 Rcg1+ 57. Kf5 Rh5+
58. Kf4 Rgh1 59. Rbd7
{ Fatigue eventually sets in. This allows Black to win the h-pawn for free.   59.Rdd7  should have been preferred, patiently defending the h-pawn. }
59... R1h4+ { First, protecting the d-pawn with check. } 60. Kf3 Rxh7
{ At this point, things go down-hill quite quickly for White since White's king is so open and Keith's extra d-pawn provides great cover for his. }
61. Rd6 Rf7+ 62. Kg3 Re4 63. Ra8 Rg7+ 64. Kf3 Rf7+ 65. Kg3 Rc7 66. Kf3 Re3+ 67.
Kf4 Re1 68. Ra3+ Rc3 69. Ra4 Rf1+ 70. Kg4 Rc4 71. Ra2 Kc3 72. Kg3 Rf8 73. Kg2
Kd3 74. Ra3+ Ke4 75. Re6+ Kd5 76. Raa6 Rc2+ 77. Kg3 Rc5 78. Red6+ Ke4
{ Suddenly, Black's king has found a square safe from checks and White's king is in the danger zone. Remember, it's not all about grabbing pawns in the endgame.   With major pieces on the board, the king can always be a target! }
79. Ra4
{ 79.Re6+  Re5  80.Rxe5+  Kxe5  This is a winning theoretical endgame that Keith could convert in his sleep. Check out theLucena technique to learn how. }
79... Rg5+ 80. Kh4 Rd5 81. Re6+ Kf4
{ Mate in one is threatened with ... Rh8#. } 82. Kh3 Kf3 83. Kh4 Rh8+
{ White is getting checkmated next move. There are many, many ways a minority attack can take shape. As a Caro-Kann player, we employ the minority attack most often from the Exchange Variation but also from the Classical and Two Knights variations. These are two of the Big 3 so I suggest you familiarize yourself with all the strategic ins and outs of the minority attack.   Maybe one day you can be an expert like Keith Arkell! }
