[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caro-Kann Endgame"]
[Black "Rafal Tymrakiewicz vs. Levy Rozman, Titled Tuesday, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

{ For our example of how to play against the isolated pawn, I happened across this online game by the fan favourite and Youtube sensation, Levy Rozman from a few years ago. His opponent is a Polish FM in this Titled Tuesday event. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Nf3 Be6
{ Levy likes my recommended setup against the Panov-Botvinnik Attack. } 7. cxd5
Bxd5
{ Suddenly, there's an isolated pawn and Black is feeling great! Even strong players sometimes don't know what better to do against the pressure ...Be6 puts on the c-pawn. }
8. Be2 e6 9. O-O Be7
{ The theory in the course ends here because there's nothing concrete happening, and your ability to handle these positions will be largely determined by your knowledge and experience against the IQP.   Let's fast-forward a few moves to the endgame. }
10. Be3 a6 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Re1 Rc8 13. h3 h6 14. Qa4
{ Probably the wrong direction for the queen. } 14... Qb6 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Qb3
Qxb3 17. axb3
{ White, quite cooperatively, has allowed a queen exchange which typically is not in White's favour since the side with the IQP usually likes to attack.   Not only that, but White's queenside structure is compromised and the b-pawn is quite vulnerable. White is already in serious trouble. }
17... Nxe3
{ Very often in IQP positions, the pawn structure transforms to something else - for example, if we capture a white piece on e3 @@StartBracket@@as in this game@@EndBracket@@ or on c3.   For illustrative purposes, let me show another method of playing against the IQP. The next moves won't be the best for White, but they represent what can lead to a dream scenario for the side fighting against the IQP.  17...Na5  Keeping the strong knight on d5 since the e3-bishop isn't going anywhere.  18.Bc4  Rfd8  19.Bxd5  Rxc1  20.Rxc1  Rxd5  21.Rc3  Nc6  22.Kf1  Bf6  Once again - not the best moves for either side, but this kind of position shows the vulnerability of the IQP. All of Black's pieces target the pawn, and all of White's pieces are passively defending it.  23.Ke2   Whenever White tries to defend the IQP from behind, tactics such as  23.Rd3  e5  become available, making use of the pinned d4-pawn.  Nxd4+  Taking the pawn is alright, but often the threat is better than the execution and it's even better to maintain pressure and slowly improve your position with moves like ...g5, ...Kf8-e2-d6, and only later taking the pawn. This could prevent some of your opponent's counterplay if you capture too early. }
18. fxe3
{ Yes, White has been absolved of the IQP, but White still has three pawn islands to Black's two.   A pawn island is a group of pawns that sit on adjacent files and can defend each other. It's better to have fewer pawn islands so that your pawns can march down the board in unison. }
18... Na5 { The b-pawn can't be conveniently defended. } 19. Rxc8 Rxc8 20. Bd1
{ In order to defend the pawn, White has taken on a passive setup. } 20... Rc1
21. Kf2
{ 21.Ne5  would have put up more resistance, rerouting the knight to d3 to evict our active rook. }
21... Rb1
{ Doubled pawns can't defend each other! Levy is able to scoop up one of the pawns after all. }
22. Nd2 Rxb2 23. Re2 b5 24. g3 Ba3 25. Ne4 Rb1
{ A mistake, allowing White's rook some activity. } 26. Bc2
{ 26.Ra2  Lots of pieces on the a-file, and suddenly it's not easy to make progress for Black.  26...Bb4  27.Ke2 }
26... Rc1 27. Nc5 Bxc5 28. dxc5 Kf8
{ Levy wants to use the king to control White's c-pawn. } 29. Rd2 Ke7 30. Ke2
b4 31. Kd3 Kd7 32. Kd4 f6 33. Bd1 Nc6+ 34. Kd3 Rxc5
{ Levy wins another pawn and cleanly converts the game. In the Caro-Kann, we most often encounter IQP structures from the Panov-Botvinnik Attack or the Pseudo-Panov Attack.   This structure occurs in a wide range of openings beyond the Caro-Kann as well, so it pays to book up on the typical plans, and not to underestimate the attacking potential of the side with the IQP when played correctly. }
35. Bf3 Rc3+ 36. Ke2+ Kc7 37. Bxc6 Kxc6 38. Rd8 Rxb3 39. Rc8+ Kd7 40. Ra8 Ra3
41. Ra7+ Kd6 42. Rxg7 b3 43. Rb7 a5 44. Kd3 a4 45. Kc3 Ra2 46. Kc4 b2 47. Kc3
a3 48. Kc2 Ra1 49. e4 Rc1+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caro-Kann Endgame"]
[Black "IQP: Review #1"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/1p2bpp1/pqn1pn1p/3b4/Q2P4/2N1BN1P/PP2BPP1/2R1R1K1 w - - 0 15"]
[SetUp "1"]

15. Nxd5 { How did Levy recapture the piece on d5? } 15... Nxd5
{ Correct.   Against the IQP, you should usually try to recapture on this square with a piece so that pressure can be applied along the d-file, in this case.   15...exd5  would give us an isolated pawn as well! }
16. Qb3
{ Bonus question: White is offering a queen exchange. Should you accept? }
16... Qxb3
{ White, quite cooperatively, has allowed a queen exchange which typically is not in White's favour since the side with the IQP usually likes to attack. Not only that, but White's queenside structure is compromised and the b-pawn is quite vulnerable. White is already in serious trouble. }
