[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "The Caro-Kann Endgame"]
[Black "Benjamin Gledura vs. S.L. Narayanan, Titled Tuesday, 2018 "]
[Result "*"]

{ Now we will see an example of a transition to an endgame from pretty early on in an Advance Variation middlegame.    It was played by Indian heavyweight, S.L Narayanan @@StartBracket@@not to be confused with the Chessable author, Srinath Narayanan@@EndBracket@@ against Benjamin Gledura, who is also a popular Chessable author. It's a blitz game played on Chess.com's Titled Tuesday, but I couldn't help but share it since Narayanan adopts my recommended setup against the mainline of the Advance Variation and it features a nice balance of tactical awareness and strategic follow-through.    This game displays an understanding of our harmonious opening setup, calculation in critical moments, and staying active in a pawn-up endgame scenario. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. e5 Bf5 4. Nf3 e6 5. Be2 Ne7 6. O-O c5
{ I was delighted to see Narayanan using my recommended setup with ...Ne7 followed by deploying Old Faithful on the next move.   The c6-square now belongs to the e7-knight, which provides nice development squares for our remaining pieces.  If you need a refresher on this setup,check here. }
7. c3 Nec6 8. Be3 Nd7 9. Ne1
{ With this backwards move @@StartBracket@@which is the first deviation from the theory section of the course@@EndBracket@@, Gledura wants make way for f4 and maybe even g4 to attack on the kingside and possibly to re-route the knight to d3, forcing us to make a decision about the c5-pawn. But, against this kind of slow move, as long as we continue to play in the centre, we're in good shape.   A more normal, developing move is  9.Nbd2  after which  9...Be7  with ...O-O next leaves Black fully content. }
9... cxd4 { The modest developing move  9...Be7  is also possible. } 10. cxd4
Qb6
{ But I really like the way Narayanan sensed the moment when White moved backwards to actively pressurize White's centre. Besides, it wasn't clear whether the f8-bishop belongs on e7, or maybe another square! }
11. Qd2
{ White should have preferred normal development with  11.Nc3  with a thematic sacrifice of the b2-pawn for excellent counterplay.  11...Qxb2  12.Rc1  Compared to the game, White has given up the b-pawn instead of an important central pawn and since Black lags in development, White retains good chances for an attack. }
11... Bb4
{ It turns out b4 is the destination of the dark-squared bishop this time, which can often happen after an exchange on d4. }
12. Nc3 Ndxe5
{ Boom!!!  Excellent tactical vision in a blitz game, and a pattern to remember in this structure. The d4-square is cleared to allow a ...d4 fork! This tactic doesn't win us material, but Black is more ready for the position to open because of White's slow moves, Ne1 and Qd2.   The lackadaisical  12...O-O  would allow White to complete his maneuver  13.Nd3  with a fine position. }
13. dxe5 d4 14. Bxd4 Qxd4
{ Before offering any exchanges, especially a queen exchange, it's important to evaluate the resulting position after the trade.  Narayanan understood that if White takes the queen, because of the superior activity of Black's pieces and the tempo on the e2-bishop, Black should be doing well. }
15. Qxd4
{ It's possible to avoid losing material by defending the queen with a move such as  15.Rd1  But Black's position is excellent after  15...O-O-O  renewing the threat of ...Qxd2, and introducing the threat of ...Qxe5.   15...Qxe5  would allow  16.Qd7+  16.Qxd4  Nxd4  Black's bishop pair and White's tangled pieces give Black an advantage. }
15... Nxd4
{ Now that queens are off the board, it can be argued we are in the endgame stage.   I like to consider four factors when evaluating a position:    A@@EndBracket@@ piece activity  B@@EndBracket@@ material   C@@EndBracket@@ pawn structure   D@@EndBracket@@ king safety In an endgame, you could sometimes replace 'king safety' with 'king activity'.    In this position, Black has superior piece activity and king activity @@StartBracket@@since the king is closer to the centre@@EndBracket@@. The space advantage is less meaningful in an endgame after pieces have been exchanged, and the material is equal. }
16. Bd3
{ Gledura wants to exchange one of Black's bishops and unravel his pieces, but in the endgame, very often one type of advantage is replaced by another.    The next sequence effectively neutralizes Black's piece activity, but gives up material in doing so. Endgame expertise involves learning how to psychologically adapt to these transitions and even forcast and manifest them!   16.Bd1  is a sad move that maintains material balance for now but  16...Ke7  allows Black's pieces, including the bishop pair, to dominate the position. }
16... Bxd3 17. Nxd3
{ White understands Black has a kind of initiative, but probably wasn't expecting to lose a pawn by force. }
17... Bxc3
{ Narayanan 'cashes in' the advantage of activity in the form of a pawn. } 18.
bxc3 Ne2+ 19. Kh1 Nxc3
{ Black is up a pawn but he still needs to finish developing. } 20. Rfc1 Nd5
{ Let's pause to talk about the Advance pawn structure in the endgame. This structure provides an outpost on d5 for Black and on d6 for White. With knights on the board, this feature matters.    In order to undermine White's outpost, and to open up an extra file, Black likes to break with ...f6, which also has the merit of opening the f-file for a black rook.  Controlling the open files is key in this endgame where rooks dominate. }
21. Nc5 b6 22. Ne4 Ke7
{ A great decision by Narayanan, keeping the king close to the action.   22...O-O  is playable, but would give up some of the advantage simply because the king is further from the centre, where it could be controlling some key squares. }
23. g3
{ White prepares the f4 advance, supporting the e5 pawn in anticipation of ...f6. }
23... f6
{ A thematic move in Advance Variation endgames. White must either give up the central pawn, or allow Black to capture and open the f-file. }
24. f4
{ White usually doesn't like to take  24.exf6+  gxf6  and give up their centre, and with it, the best square on d6 for the knight. }
24... fxe5 25. fxe5
{ Additionally, it's easier to defend the e6-pawn than for White to defend the e5-pawn. }
25... Rac8 { Simply developing, and contending White's control of the c-file. }
26. Nd6 { White hopes into its outpost and demands control of the c-file. }
26... Rxc1+ 27. Rxc1
{ Trades benefit the side who is up material and because of our ...f6 operation, we have an open file for our remaining rook! }
27... Rf8 28. Kg1 Kd7
{ A beautifulprophylactic move, putting the king to work where it takes on the responsibility of preventing the white rook's entry.   Now, both the rook and knight can get active, and piece activity is paramount in the endgame! }
29. a4 Rf3 { The rook is preparing to take aim behind White's weak pawns. } 30.
Rc8 Ne3 { Threatening mate in one. } 31. Rc1 Nd5 32. Rc8 Re3 33. Ra8 Rxe5
{ Black is now up two pawns since the knight is now hanging in space. } 34. Nb5
a5 35. Ra7+ { White finally wins back a pawn, but the a-pawn is doomed. } 35...
Kc6 36. Rxg7 Re4 37. Rxh7 Rxa4
{ Both sides have two connected passed pawns on opposite sides of the board, but Black's are coming a lot quicker! And for the second time, Black wins a pawn with tempo on the knight which loses its protection. There's not much more to see up until the end of the game. }
38. Na7+ Kc5 39. h4 Ra1+ 40. Kh2 a4 41. h5 a3 42. Nc8 Nf6 43. Rc7+ Kb5 44. Nd6+
Ka6 45. Rc4 b5 { Don't fall for  45...a2  allowing  46.Ra4 } 46. Rc6+ Ka5 47.
Rc8 a2 48. Ra8+ Kb6 49. g4 Nxg4+ 50. Kg3 Rg1+
{ Narayanan gives a final check, clearing the promotion square, and in view of ...a1=Q, White resigned. A smooth win featuring precise the transfer of advantage from activity to material, and some thematic strategies against the Advance pawn structure. }
*

